{"title_page": "El Cuatrero", "text_new": "{{Infobox professional wrestler\n| name = El Cuatrero\n| image =El Cuatrero.jpg\n| image_size =\n| alt =\n| caption =El Cuatrero holding the [[CMLL World Middleweight Championship]] in the air, November 2018\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = 1996\n| birth_place = Lagos de Moreno, Jalisco, Mexico<ref name=MedioIntro/>\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| resides =\n| spouse =\n| children =\n| family = {{Unbulleted list|[[Cien Caras]] (father)<ref name=MedioIntro/>|[[Sans\u00f3n (wrestler)|Sans\u00f3n]] (brother)<ref name=MedioIntro/>|[[M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000]] (uncle)<ref name=MedioIntro/>|[[Universo 2000]] (uncle)<ref name=MedioIntro/>|[[Forastero]] (cousin)|[[Universo 2000 Jr.]] (cousin)|[[M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000 Jr.]] (cousin)}}\n| alma_mater =\n| names ={{Unbulleted list|'''El Cuatrero'''|M\u00e1scara Universal}}\n| height = {{Convert|185|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}<ref name=DivinasLuchas/><!-- In Mexico they measure height in meters so that should be first -->\n| weight ={{convert|94|kg|lb|abbr=on}}<ref name=DivinasLuchas/><!--In Mexico they measure weight in kilograms so that should be first -->\n| billed =\n| trainer ={{Unbulleted list|[[Universo 2000]]<ref name=Starmedia/>|[[\u00daltimo Guerrero]]|[[Virus (wrestler)|Virus]]|[[Franco Colombo]]}}\n| debut =2010<ref name=MedioIntro/>\n| retired =\n| website =\n}}\n'''''El Cuatrero''''' (born 1996) is a Mexican ''[[Lucha libre|luchador]] enmascarado'', or [[wrestling mask|masked]] [[professional wrestler]] currently working for ''[[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]]'' (CMLL) based in Mexico City. He is the son of ''lucha libre'' legend [[Cien Caras]] and the nephew of [[M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000]] and [[Universo 2000]]. Cuatrero, his brother [[Sans\u00f3n (wrestler)|Sans\u00f3n]] and their cousin [[Forastero]] form a trio known as ''Nueva Generaci\u00f3n Dinamitas'' (\"New Generation Dynamites\"), the successor to ''[[Los Capos|Los Hermanos Dinamita]]'' (Cien Caras, M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000 and Universo 2000). His real name is not a matter of public record, as is often the case with masked wrestlers in Mexico where their private lives are kept a secret from the wrestling fans.<ref name=Mondo>{{cite book | author= Madigan, Dan | title= Mondo Lucha Libre: the bizarre & honorable world of wild Mexican wrestling | publisher= HarperColins Publisher | year= 2007 | chapter = Okay... what is Lucha Libre? | pages = 29\u201340|isbn=978-0-06-085583-3}}</ref> His [[ring name]] is Spanish for \"The Horse thief\" or  \"The [[Cattle Rustler]]\", reflected in the cowboy-inspired ring gear and mask he wears during shows.\n\nEl Cuatrero is the current [[CMLL World Middleweight Champion]] and at one point held four championships simultaneously, which included the [[CMLL Arena Coliseo Tag Team Championship]] (with Sans\u00f3n), the [[Mexican National Trios Championship]] (with Sans\u00f3n and Forastero) and the Occidente Trios Championship (with Sans\u00f3n and Forastero). He won the mask of [[\u00c1ngel de Oro]] in the main event of CMLL's 2018 ''[[Homenaje a Dos Leyendas]]'' show on March&nbsp;16, 2018.\n\n==Personal life==\nEl Cuatrero was born in 1996, a son of [[professional wrestler]] Carmelo Reyes Gonz\u00e1lez, better known under the [[ring name]] [[Cien Caras]] (\"100 Faces\"). His older brother, known under the name [[Sans\u00f3n (wrestler)|Sans\u00f3n]] (\"[[Samson]]\") was born in 1994. His uncles Jes\u00fas (known as [[M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000]]) and Andr\u00e9s ([[Universo 2000]]) were also professional wrestlers.<ref name=MondoFamily/> Several of their sons followed their fathers into professional wrestling, including [[Forastero]], [[Universo 2000 Jr.]] and [[M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000 Jr.]]<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.mediotiempo.com/mas-deportes/lucha-libre/noticias/2012/08/05/wagner-destapo-a-mascara-2000-jr | title= Wagner destap\u00f3 a M\u00e1scara 2000 Jr. | last=Rodr\u00edguez | first=Alejandro | date=August 5, 2012 | accessdate=February 19, 2013 | work=MedioTiempo | language=Spanish | trans-title=Wagner unmasks M\u00e1scara 2000 Jr.}}</ref> Initially, Carmelo Reyes did not want his sons to become professional wrestlers, wanting them to get an education instead. He reluctantly agreed that they could train for ''Lucha Libre'' with their uncle Andr\u00e9s, but only as a hobby. During their training, Carmelo noticed how serious they took it and reluctantly agreed with their choice to become professional wrestlers.<ref name=DivinasLuchas>{{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Uz7nTR_jZSE | title=Divinas de la lucha Cuatrero y Sans\u00f3n | date=March 5, 2017 | accessdate=February 16, 2017 | first=Elisa | last=Tud\u00f3n | work=Divinas de la Luchas | language=Spanish | trans-title=Divine fighters Cuatrero and Sanson}}</ref>\n\nThere is a long tradition of wrestlers paying for the right to use a ring name in Mexican wrestling, including being allowed to portray a second or third-generation wrestler without being related to the originator.<ref name=MondoFamily>{{cite book|author=Madigan, Dan|title=Mondo Lucha a Go Go: the bizarre & honorable world of wild Mexican wrestling|publisher=[[HarperCollins]] Publisher|year=2007|chapter=A family affair|pages = 128\u2013132|isbn=978-0-06-085583-3}}</ref> It has been confirmed that wrestlers [[Cien Caras Jr.]] and [[El Hijo de Cien Caras]] are unrelated to the Reyes family, while it is unclear if [[Hijo de M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000]] is a blood relative or a purely fictional relative.<ref name=Adios>{{cite web|url=http://www.record.com.mx/blog/el-hijo-del-santo/2010-12-02/el-adios-del-hijo-de-cien-caras |title=El adi\u00f3s del Hijo de Cien Caras |authorlink=El Hijo del Santo | first=El | last=Hijo del Santo |date=December 2, 2010 |accessdate=February 19, 2013 |publisher=R\u00e9cord.com |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101204113931/http://www.record.com.mx/blog/el-hijo-del-santo/2010-12-02/el-adios-del-hijo-de-cien-caras |archivedate=December 4, 2010 |trans-title=Goodbye to El Hijo de Cien Caras}}</ref> Reyes later stated that he allowed the \"Cien Caras\" name to be rented by other wrestlers as his sons were very young and might not want to become professional wrestlers.<ref name=MedioIntro/>\n\n==Professional wrestling career==\n[[File:Nueva Generacion Dinamitas.jpg|thumb|left|[[Sans\u00f3n (wrestler)|Sans\u00f3n]], El Cuatrero and [[Forastero]] outside the ring in November 2018]]\nWhile the El Cuatrero name was first used in 2014, Sans\u00f3n said they made their in-ring debut around the year 2010 and worked locally in Lagos de Moreno, while finishing school.<ref name=MedioIntro>{{cite web | url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/mas-deportes/lucha-libre/noticias/2015/12/01/herederos-de-cien-caras-cerca-de-debut-en-arena-mexico | title=Herederos de Cien Caras cerca de debut en Arena M\u00e9xico | date=December 1, 2015 | accessdate=February 16, 2018 | language=Spanish | work=MedioTiempo | first=Apolo | last=Vald\u00e9s | trans-title=The successors to Cien Casas make their debut in Arena Mexico}}</ref> In an interview Cuatrero said that he wrestled briefly as \"M\u00e1scara Universal\", but his father did not like the name and suggested the name \"El Cuatrero\", Spanish for \"The [[Cattle rustler]] instead. This was inspired by the cowboy gimmick that his father and his uncles had used.<ref name=Starmedia>{{cite web | url=http://www.starmedia.com/noticias/sanson-cuatrero-reviviran-memoria-cien-caras-en-arena-mexico/ | title=Sans\u00f3n Y Cuatrero Revivir\u00e1n Memoria De Cien Caras En La Arena M\u00e9xico | date=December 28, 2015 | accessdate=February 16, 2018 | work=[[Starmedia|StarMedia]] | language=Spanish | trans-title=Sanson and Cuatrero revieve the memory of Cien Caras in Arena Mexico | archivedate=July 31, 2018  | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731125041/https://www.starmedia.com/noticias/sanson-cuatrero-reviviran-memoria-cien-caras-en-arena-mexico}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.elsoldemexico.com.mx/deportes/Sans\u00f3n-y-Cuatrero-los-\u201cNuevos-Dinamita\u201d-198235.html | title=Sans\u00f3n y Cuatrero, los \"Nuevos Dinamita\" | date=October 23, 2015 | accessdate=February 16, 2018 | language=Spanish | work=El Sol del Mexico | first=Armando | last=Isa\u00eds | trans-title=Sanson and Cuatrero, the \"New Dynamites\"}}</ref> During their time working locally in Lagos de Moreno, the duo won their first ''[[Lucha de Apuestas]]'', or bet match, when they defeated Los Centellas (I and II) and unmasked the duo.<ref name=DivinasLuchas/>\n\n===Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre (2014\u2013present)===\nThe Reyes  brothers worked locally until early 2014, when they began working in Guadalajara for the local ''[[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]]'' (CMLL) promoters in Arena Coliseo. They began training at the CMLL wrestling school, receving training from [[\u00daltimo Guerrero]], [[Virus (wrestler)|Virus]] and [[Franco Colombo]].<ref name=Starmedia/> The Reyes brothers made their CMLL debut on March 25, 2014, where they, along with Universo 2000 lost to the trio of [[Blue Panther]], [[Sagrado (wrestler)|Sagrado]], and [[Valiente (wrestler)|Valiente]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=108892 | title=CMLL Guadalajara Martes | date=March 25, 2014 | accessdate=February 18, 2018 | work=CageMatch| language=German}}</ref> While working in Guadalajara, El Cuatrero and Sans\u00f3n competed in a tournament to determine the number one contenders for the local Occidente Tag Team Championship, but the two were eliminated by the team of Flash and Flash II.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=124225 | title=CMLL Guadalajara Viernes | date=January 30, 2015 | accessdate=July 29, 2018 | work=CageMatch| language=German}}</ref> The brothers teamed up with Jocker, with the winners being crowned the new Occidente Trios Champions. The team made it all the way to the final match of the tournament but was defeated by Furia Roja, Mr. Trueno, and Ray Trueno.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=128976 | title=CMLL Guadalajara Domingos | date=March 5, 2015 | accessdate=July 29, 2018 | work=CageMatch| language=German}}</ref> On November 11, 2015, Cuatrero and Sans\u00f3n teamed up with their cousin Forastero and won the Occidente Trios Championship.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=140036 | title=LLE | date=November 11, 2015 | accessdate=July 29, 2018 | work=CageMatch| language=German}}</ref>\n\nOn January 5, 2017, El Cuatrero worked his first CMLL match in Mexico City in the company's main venue. as he participated in the 2017 version of ''[[La Copa Junior]]'' but was eliminated from the tournament before the finals.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/mas-deportes/lucha-libre/noticias/2016/01/06/puma-finalista-de-la-copa-jr-del-cmll | title=Puma, finalista de la Copa Jr. del CMLL | date=January 6, 2015 | accessdate=January 10, 2016 | work=MedioTiempo | language=Spanish | trans-title=Puma finalist in the CMLL La Copa Jr.}}</ref> At that point, the Reyes brothers began being referred to as ''Nueva Generacion Dinamitas'' (Spanish for \"New Generation Dynamites\"; NGD) as a reference to their heritage. On March 18, 2016, ''Nueva Generacion Dinamitas'' worked their first major show for CMLL, defeating [[Soberano Jr.]] and [[Oro Jr.]] in the opening match of that year's ''[[Homenaje a Dos Leyendas (2016)|Homenaje A Dos Leyendas]]'' show.<ref name=DosLeyendas2016SL>{{cite web | url=http://superluchas.com/cmll-homenaje-a-dos-leyendas-cobertura-y-resultados-21032016/ | title=CMLL \"Homenaje a Dos Leyendas\" \u2013 Cobertura y Resultados \u2013 21/03/2016 \u2013 M\u00e1ximo Sexy y Negro Casas, pelones | author=Dark Angelita | date=March 18, 2016 | accessdate=March 19, 2016 | work=[[S\u00faper Luchas]] | language=Spanish | trans-title= CMLL \"Homage to Two Legends \u2013 Coverage and results \u2013 21/02/1016 \u2013 M\u00e1ximo Sexy and Negro Casas bald}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://es-us.deportes.yahoo.com/fotos/homenaje-a-dos-leyendas-lucha-libre-arena-m%C3%A9xico-viernes-18-de-marzo-de-2016-slideshow/ | title=Homenaje a Dos Leyendas, Lucha Libre Arena M\u00e9xico, Viernes 18 de Marzo de 2016 | date=March 19, 2016 | accessdate=March 19, 2016 | publisher=[[Yahoo!]] | work=Yahoo! Deportes | first=Gonzalo | last= L\u00f3pez Peralta}}</ref> CMLL decided to have both El Cuatrero and Sans\u00f3n participate in their annual ''[[Torneo Gran Alternativa (2016)|Torneo Gran Alternativa]]'' (\"Great Alternativa Tournament\") where younger wrestlers team up with established veteran wrestlers. El Cuatrero was paired with [[Rey Bucanero]], but the duo lost to [[Trit\u00f3n (wrestler)|Trit\u00f3n]] and [[M\u00edstico II|M\u00edstico]] in the first round.<ref name=Medio2016BlockA>{{cite web | url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/mas-deportes/lucha-libre/noticias/2016/03/23/rey-escorpion-y-fujin-por-la-gran-alternativa | title=Rey Escorpi\u00f3n y Fuj\u00edn, por la Gran Alternativa | date=March 23, 2016 | accessdate=March 23, 2016 | work=MedioTiempo | language=Spanish | trans-title=Rey Escorpi\u00f3n and Fuj\u00edn go for the Gran Alternativa}}</ref> A year later, El Cuatrero was teamed up with his uncle M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000 for the 2017 version of the ''[[Torneo Gran Alternativa (2017)|Torneo Gran Alternativa]]'',  but like the 2016 tournament, El Cuatrero did not make it past the first round as the team lost to [[Esfinge]] and [[Atlantis (wrestler)|Atlantis]].<ref name=2017BlockAF4W>{{cite web | url=http://www.f4wonline.com/mexico/cmll-arena-mexico-results-la-gran-alternativa-tournament-begins-236681| title=CMLL Arena Mexico Results: La Gran Alternativa tournament begins | date=June 4, 2017 | accessdate=June 11, 2017 | work=Wrestling Observer Figure Four Online | first=Chris | last=Aiken}}</ref> While El Cuatrero's first years on the main roster had seen little success, July 2017 proved a turning point in how ''Nueva Generacion Dinamitas'' was booked as El Cuatrero and Sans\u00f3n defeated [[Black Terry]] and [[Negro Navarro]] to win the [[CMLL Arena Coliseo Tag Team Championship]], CMLL's second-highest ranked tag team championship.<ref name=NGD/> Three days later the trio defeated ''[[Los Hijos del Infierno]]'' ([[Ephesto]], [[Luciferno]], and [[Mephisto (wrestler)|Mephisto]]) to win the [[Mexican National Trios Championship]], making Ephesto a triple championship.<ref name=NGDTrios/> The trio would win CMLL's ''La Copa Dinastia'', defeating the trios of Blue Panther, [[Blue Panther Jr.]], [[The Panther (wrestler)|The Panter]] and then [[Dragon Lee (wrestler)|Dragon Lee]], M\u00edstico, and [[Comandante Pierroth|Pierroth]].<ref name=CopaDinastia2017/> \n\nOn January 19, 2018, as part of the annual [[Fantastica Mania 2018|2018 Fantastica Mania]] tour of Japan, El Cuatrero defeated [[\u00c1ngel de Oro]] to win the [[CMLL World Middleweight Championship]].<ref name=CuatreroMiddle/> The match and championship change was the beginning of a long-running storyline feud between El Cuatrero and \u00c1ngel de Oro, where challenges for a ''Lucha de Apuestas'' match soon followed.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/lucha-libre/2018/02/07/angel-de-oro-y-cuatrero-se-jugaran-las-mascaras-en-homenaje-a-dos-leyendas | language=Spanish | accessdate=July 30, 2018 | date=February 7, 2019 | work=MedioTiempo | title=\u00c1ngel de Oro y Cuatrero se jugaran las mascaras en Homenaje a Dos Leyendas | trans-title=\u00c1ngel de Oro, fighting for the asks at Homage to Two Legends}}</ref> On February 14, 2018, ''Nueva Generacion Dinamitas'' announced they were giving up the CMLL Arena Coliseo Tag Team Championship, with the storyline given that they were focusing on winning the [[CMLL World Tag Team Championship]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://twitter.com/CMLL_OFICIAL/status/964177915343724550 | title=Sans\u00f3n y Cuatrero renuncian al Campeonato de Parejas de la Arena Coliseo. | trans-title=Sans\u00f3n and Cuatrero give up the Arena Colise Tag Team Championship |date=February 15, 2018 | accessdate=March 11, 2018 | author=CMLL | publisher=[[Twitter]] | language=Spanish}}</ref> The storyline feud between El Cuatrero and \u00c1ngel de Oro reached its peak at the 2018 ''[[Homenaje a Dos Leyendas (2018)|Homenaje a Dos Leyendas]]'' show, where both competitors put their mask on the line in the main event match of the night. It ended with El Cuatrero defeating \u00c1ngel de Oro two falls to one, forcing \u00c1ngel de Oro to remove his mask as per ''lucha libre'' tradition.<ref name=AngelApuesta/> He would later make his first and second successful defense of the CMLL World Middleweight Championship against \u00c1ngel de Oro.<ref name=CMLLMiddle>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=5&nr=93&page=5&reign=19 | title= CMLL World Middleweight Championship >> Title Reigns >> 19.01.2018 - Today: El Cuatrero| accessdate=March 4, 2020 | work=CageMatch}}</ref> At the [[CMLL 85th Anniversary Show]], the Dinamitas defeated Atlantis, El Soberano Jr., and Mistico as part of CMLL's most important show of the year.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.f4wonline.com/mexico/cmll-85th-aniversario-live-results-hair-vs-hair-tag-team-main-event-265781 | title=CMLL 85. Aniversario live results: hair vs. hair tag team main event | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter|Wrestling Observer Figure Four Online]] | date=September 14, 2018 | accessdate=September 15, 2018 | first=Chris | last=Aiken}}</ref> On November 6, 2018, Cuatrero made his third successful middleweight championship defense as he defeated [[Tit\u00e1n (wrestler)|Tit\u00e1n]].<ref name=CMLLMiddle/>\n\n2019 was the first year that all three members of Nueva Generaci\u00f3n Dinamitas participated in the annual [[Fantastica Mania 2019|Fantastica Mania]] tour of Japan, capping off the tour with a successful championship defense against \u00c1ngel de Oro, Atlantis, and Tit\u00e1n on the last day of the tour.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.f4wonline.com/japan/njpwcmll-fantastica-mania-results-my-dad-heel-wrestler-match-275026 | title=NJPW/CMLL Fantastica Mania results: 'My Dad is a heel wrestler' match | date=January 21, 2019 | accessdate=January 21, 2019 | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]] | first=Ethan | last=Renner}}</ref> 2019 also marked the first year that El Cuatrero participated in the [[CMLL Universal Championship (2019)|Universal Championship]], a tournament where all 16 participants held a championship recognized by CMLL. In the opening round. he defeated perennial rival Soberano Jr. before losing to \u00daltimo Guerrero in the quarterfinals.<ref name=BlockBOvaciones>{{cite web | url=https://ovaciones.com/vence-al-maestro/ | title=\u00a1Vence al maestro! | trans-title=defeating the master | date=February 9, 2019 | accessdate=February 9, 2019 | first=Arturo | last=Rosas Platas | language=Spanish | work=Ovaciones}}</ref><ref name=BlockBMarca>{{cite web | url=https://www.marca.com/claro-mx/otros-deportes/lucha-libre/2019/02/09/5c5e6f62268e3e8f7c8b45a1.html | work=Marca Claro | title=Niebla Roja se impone en la segunda fase del torneo Campe\u00f3n Universal 2019 | trans-title=Niebla Roja looks imposing in the second phase of the 2019 Universal Championship | date=February 9, 2019 | accessdate=February 9, 2019 | language=Spanish}}</ref> For the 2019 ''[[CMLL Torneo Nacional de Parejas Incre\u00edbles (2019)|Torneo Nacional de Parejas Incre\u00edbles]]'' (\"National incredible teams tournament), Cuatrero was paired up with M\u00edstico, as a ''[[Heel (professional wrestling)|rudo]]'' (The \"bad guy\") and a ''[[Face (professional wrestling)|tecnico]]'' (the \"Good guy\") team up for the event. The odd couple defeated [[Hechicero]] and [[Stuka Jr.]], then Atlantis and Negro Casas, before ultimately losing to \u00daltimo Guerrero and Volador Jr. in the semifinals.<ref name=Increibles2019B>{{cite web | url= https://www.20minutos.com.mx/deportes/noticia/ultimo-guerrero-y-volador-jr-van-a-final-de-torneo-increible-505260/0/ | title= \u00daltimo Guerrero y Volador Jr. van a final de \"Torneo incre\u00edble\"|trans-title=\u00daltimo Guerrero and Volador Jr. goes to the finals of the \u201cIncredible Tournament\u201d| language=Spanish | work=20 Minutos | author=Notimex | date=April 20, 2019 | accessdate=May 17, 2019}}</ref><ref name=Ovaciones2019B>{{cite web | url=https://ovaciones.com/volador-y-guerrero-a-la-final/ | title=Volador y Guerrero a la final | trans-title=Volador and Guerrero in the finals | language=Spanish | accessdate=May 17, 2019 | date=April 20, 2019  | work=Ovacones | first=Arturo | last=Rosas Plata}}</ref> As part of the 66th anniversary of Arena Puebla, NGD successfully defended the Mexican National Trios Championship against ''[[Los Ingobernables]]'' ([[El Terrible]], [[La Bestia del Ring]], and [[Rush (wrestler)|Rush]]), in what was their tenth overall championship defense.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=5&nr=532&page=5&reign=41 | title=Mexican National Trios Championship >> 25.07.2017 - today: La Sangre Dinamita (El Cuatrero, Forasteo & Sanson) | work=CageMatch | accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> In December, El Cuatrero made his fourth successful defense of the CMLL World Middleweight Championship as he defeated [[Car\u00edstico]] on December 12.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=250178 | title=CMLL Sabados De Coliseo | date=December 12, 2019 | accessdate=March 31, 2020 | work=CageMatch}}</ref>\n\nThe 2020 ''[[Sin Piedad (2020)|Sin Piedad]]'' show offered Cuatrero the opportunity to become a quadruple champion as he and Sans\u00f3n challenged M\u00edstico and Car\u00edstico for the CMLL World Tag Team Championship, but lost the match.<ref name=SP2020Medio>{{cite web | url=https://www.mediotiempo.com/lucha-libre/cmll/espiritu-negro-fue-desenmascarado-por-principe-diamante | title=Cay\u00f3 la primera m\u00e1scara en el 2020 dentro del CMLL; Esp\u00edritu Negro revel\u00f3 su rostro | trans-title=The first mask loss in CMLL of 2020; Espiritu Negro revealed his face | language=Spanish | date=January 2, 2020 | accessdate=January 2, 2020 | work=MedioTiempo}}</ref> During the 2020 [[Fantastica Mania 2020|Fantastica Mania]] tour, Cuatrero and his brother participated in the [[List of CMLL tag team tournaments#2020 Family tag team tournament|family tag team tournament]], where they ended up defeating ''Los Hermanos Chavez'' (\u00c1ngel de Oro and Niebla Roja) in the finals.<ref name=FM20Jan19>{{cite web | url=https://www.njpw.co.jp/tornament/220096?showResult=1 | title=NJPW presents CMLL Fantastica Mania 2020 | language=Japanese | date=January 17, 2020 | accessdate=January 17, 2020 | work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]}}</ref> On the final day of the tour, January 20, NGD successfully defended the Mexican National Trios Championship against ''Los Hermanos Chavez'' and Tit\u00e1n.<ref name=NJPWFM202Jan20>{{cite web | url=https://www.njpw.co.jp/tornament/220098?showResult=1 | title=NJPW presents CMLL Fantastica Mania 2020 | date=January 20, 2020 | accessdate=January 20, 2020 | work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] | language=Japanese}}</ref> On February 24, 2020, El Cuatrero and Sans\u00f3n won the ''[[#Torneo de parejas familiares|Torneo de parejas familiares]]'' (\"Family team tournament\") as they defeated the uncle/nephew team of Rey Bucanero and [[Drone (wrestler)|Drone]] in the first round, the father/son team of [[Euforia (wrestler)|Euforia]] and Soberano Jr. in the second round, and finally the [[Gran Guerrero]]/\u00daltimo Guerrero brothers in the finals.<ref name=NGDFamiliares/><ref name=LuchaCentral/>\n\n===Independent circuit (2014\u2013current)===\nWhile working for CMLL, Cuatrero, like all CMLL workes, is allowed to take independent circuit bookings on days he is not needed by CMLL or arranged through CMLL. On February 19, 2017, Cuatrero and Sans\u00f3n unsuccessfully challenged Black Terry and Negro Navarro for the CMLL Arena Coliseo Tag Team Championship on a ''Lucha Memes'' show in Puebla.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=173059 | title=Lucha Memes | date=February 19, 2017 | accessdate=February 4, 2020 | work=CageMatch}}</ref> NGD also successfully defended the Mexican National Tag Team Championship against Los Kamikazes del Aire (Alas de Acero, [[Aramis]], and Iron Kid) at a subsequent ''Lucha Memes'' show.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=192320 | title=Lucha Memes Chairo 12 | date=May 2, 2018| accessdate=February 4, 2020 | work=CageMatch}}</ref> \n\nAs part of CMLL's collaboration with [[The Crash Lucha Libre]], Nueva Generaci\u00f3n Dinamitas has performed on several The Crash shows over the years. In their initial appearance for The Crash, Nueva Generaci\u00f3n Dinamitas lost to [[La Rebeli\u00f3n Amarilla]] ([[Bestia 666]], [[Jacob Fatu]] and [[Mecha Wolf 450]]).<ref>{{cite web | url=https://tjsports.com.mx/se-termina-la-rebelion/ |title=\u00a1Se Termina \u2018La Rebeli\u00f3n\u2019! | trans-title=The end of \"The Rebellion\" | date=September 8, 2018 | accessdate=March 3, 2020 | language=Spanish | work=TJ Sports}}</ref> The team returned to The Crash for their [[The Crash VII Aniversario|VII Anniversary Show]] show, where they lost to ''Los Lucha Bros'' ([[Pentag\u00f3n Jr.|Penta El 0M]] and [[F\u00e9nix (wrestler)|The King]]) in a match for [[The Crash Tag Team Championship]] that also included [[Reno Scum]] (Adam Thornstowe and Luster the Legend).<ref name=LuchaCentral>{{cite web | url=https://www.luchacentral.com/resultados-aniversario-vii-the-crash-espanol/ | title=\u00a1Resultados Aniversario VII THE CRASH ! Espanol | trans-title=Results of the Crash VII Anniversary! Spanish | date=November 3, 2018 | accessdate=November 4, 2018 | first=Miguel | last=Pe\u00f1a | work=Lucha Central | language=Spanish}}</ref><ref name=LuchaWorld>{{cite web | url=http://www.luchaworld.com/?p=86983 | title=Lucha Report for 11/4/18 | date=November 4, 2018 | accessdate=November 4, 2018 | first=Alfredo | last=Esparza | work=Lucha World}}</ref> They returned to The Crash in December 2018, losing to Bestia 666 and [[Garza Jr.]] in the main event.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://tjsports.com.mx/garza-jr-y-bestia-666-demostraron-porque-son-la-cara-de-the-crash-lucha-libre/| title=Garza Jr. Y Bestia 666 Demostraron Porque Son La Cara De The Crash Lucha Libre | trans-title=Garza Jr. Y Bestia 666 demonstrate why they are the face of The Crash Lucha Libre | work=TJ Sports | language=Spanish | accessdate=March 4, 2020 | date=December 1, 2018}}</ref> In 2019 Cuatrero and Sans\u00f3n worked an extended storyline against ''[[Los Traumas]]'' ([[Trauma I]] and [[Trauma II]]) in The Crash. In June Sans\u00f3n was forced to team up with Trauma I to face Cuatrero and Trauma I in a ''[[relevos incre\u00edbles]]'' (\"incredible pairs\" match), where the regular partners refused to wrestle against each other. In the end, Sans\u00f3n and Trauma I after Trauma II hit El Cuatrero during the match.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=231526 | title=The Crash | date=June 15, 2019 | accessdate=March 4, 2020 | work=CageMatch}}</ref> This was followed by a tag team match where NGD defeated Los Traumas by disqualification as part of their ongoing storyline.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=233101 | title=FCP Project Mexico| date=September 7, 2019 | accessdate=March 4, 2020 | work=CageMatch}}</ref>\n\nOn June 16, 2019, Cuatrero, Forastero, and Sans\u00f3n appeared at International Wrestling Revolution Group's annual [[Festival de las M\u00e1scaras (2019)|Festival de las M\u00e1scaras]] show. The trio defeated their cousin M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000 Jr., teaming with Capo del Sur and Capo del Norte, who both use ring characters inspired by the original ''Los Dinamitas''<ref name=FdM2019>{{cite web | url=http://www.thegladiatores.com/emotivo-homenaje-a-vampiro-canadiense-en-el-festival-de-mascaras/ | title=Emotivo homenaje a Vampiro Canadiense en el festival de m\u00e1scaras. | trans-title=Emotional homage to Canadian Vampire at the Festival of the Masks| date=June 17, 2019 | accessdate=August 8, 2019 | language=Spanish | work=The Gladiatores | first=Alfonso |last=Lizzaranga}}</ref>\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n*'''[[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]]'''\n:*[[CMLL World Middleweight Championship]] ([[List of CMLL World Middleweight Champions#Title history|1 time]], current)<ref name=CuatreroMiddle>{{cite web | url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/card_result/130117 | title=NJPW presents CMLL Fantastica Mania 2018 CMLL\u4e16\u754c\u30df\u30c9\u30eb\u7d1a\u9078\u624b\u6a29\u8a66\u5408 | trans-title= NJPW Presents CMLL Fanastica Mania 2018 CMLL World Middleweight Championship |publisher=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] | language=Japanese | date=January 19, 2018 | accessdate=January 19, 2018 }}</ref>\n:*[[CMLL Arena Coliseo Tag Team Championship]] ([[CMLL Arena Coliseo Tag Team Championship|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[Sans\u00f3n (wrestler)|Sans\u00f3n]]<ref name=NGD>{{cite web | url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/lucha-libre/2017/07/22/sanson-y-cuatrero-nuevos-campeones-de-la-arena-coliseo | title=Sans\u00f3n y Cuatrero, nuevos campeones de la Arena Coliseo | date=July 22, 2017 | accessdate=July 24, 2017 | work=MedioTiempo | language=Spanish | first=Apolo | last=Vald\u00e9s | trans-title=Sanson and Cuatrero, new champions of Arena Coliseo}}</ref>\n:*[[Mexican National Trios Championship]] ([[List of Mexican National Trios Champions#Title history|1 time]], current) \u2013 with Sans\u00f3n and [[Forastero]]<ref name=NGDTrios>{{cite web | url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/lucha-libre/2017/07/26/sanson-cuatrero-y-forastero-campeones-nacionales-de-tercias | title=Sans\u00f3n, Cuatrero y Forastero, campeones nacionales de tercias | date=July 26, 2017 | accessdate=July 26, 2017 | work=MedioTiempo | language=Spanish | trans-title=Sanson, Cuatrero and Forastero National Trios Champions}}</ref>\n:*Occidente Trios Championship (1 time, current) \u2013 with Sans\u00f3n and Forastero<ref name=DivinasLuchas/><ref name=OCCTrios>{{cite web | title=Occidente Trios Championship | publisher=cagematch |url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=5&nr=2518 | accessdate=January 23, 2020}}</ref>\n:*''La Copa Dinastia'' (2017) \u2013 with Sans\u00f3n and Forastero<ref name=CopaDinastia2017>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=187827 | title=CMLL Super Viernes | date=November 24, 2017 | accessdate=July 29, 2018 | work=CageMatch | language=German}}</ref>\n:*''[[Torneo de parejas familiares]]'' (2020) \u2013 with Sans\u00f3n<ref name=NGDFamiliares>{{cite web | url=https://superluchas.com/cmll-la-ngd-se-lleva-el-torneo-de-parejas-familiares-de-puebla/ | title=CMLL: La NGD se lleva el Torneo de Parejas Familiares de Puebla | author=Dark Angelita | date=February 25, 2020 | accessdate=February 26, 2020 | language=Spanish | work=[[S\u00faper Luchas]] | trans-title=CMLL: The NGD win the Family Tag Team Tournament in Puebla}}</ref>\n\n*'''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n**Ranked #'''322''' of the best 500 singles wrestlers in the [[PWI 500]] in 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=97&nr=230#2018|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated (PWI) 500 for 2018|accessdate=September 14, 2018|work=CageMatch}}</ref>\n\n==''Luchas de Apuestas'' record==\n{{See also|Lucha libre#Luchas de Apuestas|l1=Luchas de Apuestas}}\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=100%  style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=20% scope=\"col\"|Winner (wager)\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=20% scope=\"col\"|Loser (wager)\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=20% scope=\"col\"|Location\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=20% scope=\"col\"|Event\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=15% scope=\"col\"|Date\n!class=\"unsortable\" style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=5% scope=\"col\"|Notes\n|-\n|El Cuatrero and [[Sans\u00f3n (wrestler)|Sans\u00f3n]] (masks) || Los Centellas (I and II) || N/A || Live show || N/A || <ref name=DivinasLuchas/>\n|-\n|El Cuatrero (mask) || [[\u00c1ngel de Oro]] (mask) || [[Arena Mexico]] || ''[[Homenaje a Dos Leyendas (2018)|Homenaje a Dos Leyendas]]'' || {{dts|March 16, 2018}} || <ref name=AngelApuesta>{{cite web |url= https://ovaciones.com/cae-angel-de-oro |title= \u00a1Cae \u00c1ngel de Oro! |first= Arturo |last= Rosas Plata |date= March 17, 2018 |accessdate= June 23, 2018 |language= Spanish |publisher= Ovaciones | trans-title=The fall of \u00c1ngel de Oro!}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre roster}}\n{{CMLL Arena Coliseo Tag Team Championship}}\n{{CMLL World Middleweight Championship}}\n{{Mexican National Trios Championship}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Mexico}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cuatrero, El}}\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Mexican male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Masked wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox professional wrestler\n| name = El Cuatrero\n| image =El Cuatrero.jpg\n| image_size =\n| alt =\n| caption =El Cuatrero holding the [[CMLL World Middleweight Championship]] in the air, November 2018\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = 1996\n| birth_place = Lagos de Moreno, Jalisco, Mexico<ref name=MedioIntro/>\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| resides =\n| spouse =\n| children =\n| family = {{Unbulleted list|[[Cien Caras]] (father)<ref name=MedioIntro/>|[[Sans\u00f3n (wrestler)|Sans\u00f3n]] (brother)<ref name=MedioIntro/>|[[M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000]] (uncle)<ref name=MedioIntro/>|[[Universo 2000]] (uncle)<ref name=MedioIntro/>|[[Forastero]] (cousin)|[[Universo 2000 Jr.]] (cousin)|[[M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000 Jr.]] (cousin)}}\n| alma_mater =\n| names ={{Unbulleted list|'''El Cuatrero'''|M\u00e1scara Universal}}\n| height = {{Convert|185|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}<ref name=DivinasLuchas/><!-- In Mexico they measure height in meters so that should be first -->\n| weight ={{convert|94|kg|lb|abbr=on}}<ref name=DivinasLuchas/><!--In Mexico they measure weight in kilograms so that should be first -->\n| billed =\n| trainer ={{Unbulleted list|[[Universo 2000]]<ref name=Starmedia/>|[[\u00daltimo Guerrero]]|[[Virus (wrestler)|Virus]]|[[Franco Colombo]]}}\n| debut =2010<ref name=MedioIntro/>\n| retired =\n| website =\n}}\n'''''El Cuatrero''''' (born 1996) is a Mexican ''[[Lucha libre|luchador]] enmascarado'', or [[wrestling mask|masked]] [[professional wrestler]] currently working for ''[[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]]'' (CMLL) based in Mexico City. He is the son of ''lucha libre'' legend [[Cien Caras]] and the nephew of [[M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000]] and [[Universo 2000]]. Cuatrero, his brother [[Sans\u00f3n (wrestler)|Sans\u00f3n]] and their cousin [[Forastero]] form a trio known as ''Nueva Generaci\u00f3n Dinamitas'' (\"New Generation Dynamites\"), the successor to ''[[Los Capos|Los Hermanos Dinamita]]'' (Cien Caras, M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000 and Universo 2000). His real name is not a matter of public record, as is often the case with masked wrestlers in Mexico where their private lives are kept a secret from the wrestling fans.<ref name=Mondo>{{cite book | author= Madigan, Dan | title= Mondo Lucha Libre: the bizarre & honorable world of wild Mexican wrestling | publisher= HarperColins Publisher | year= 2007 | chapter = Okay... what is Lucha Libre? | pages = 29\u201340|isbn=978-0-06-085583-3}}</ref> His [[ring name]] is Spanish for \"The Horse thief\" or  \"The [[Cattle Rustler]]\", reflected in the cowboy-inspired ring gear and mask he wears during shows.\n\nEl Cuatrero is the current [[CMLL World Middleweight Champion]] and at one point held four championships simultaneously, which included the [[CMLL Arena Coliseo Tag Team Championship]] (with Sans\u00f3n), the [[Mexican National Trios Championship]] (with Sans\u00f3n and Forastero) and the Occidente Trios Championship (with Sans\u00f3n and Forastero). He won the mask of [[\u00c1ngel de Oro]] in the main event of CMLL's 2018 ''[[Homenaje a Dos Leyendas]]'' show on March&nbsp;16, 2018.\n\n==Personal life==\nEl Cuatrero was born in 1996, a son of [[professional wrestler]] Carmelo Reyes Gonz\u00e1lez, better known under the [[ring name]] [[Cien Caras]] (\"100 Faces\"). His older brother, known under the name [[Sans\u00f3n (wrestler)|Sans\u00f3n]] (\"[[Samson]]\") was born in 1994. His uncles Jes\u00fas (known as [[M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000]]) and Andr\u00e9s ([[Universo 2000]]) were also professional wrestlers.<ref name=MondoFamily/> Several of their sons followed their fathers into professional wrestling, including [[Forastero]], [[Universo 2000 Jr.]] and [[M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000 Jr.]]<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.mediotiempo.com/mas-deportes/lucha-libre/noticias/2012/08/05/wagner-destapo-a-mascara-2000-jr | title= Wagner destap\u00f3 a M\u00e1scara 2000 Jr. | last=Rodr\u00edguez | first=Alejandro | date=August 5, 2012 | accessdate=February 19, 2013 | work=MedioTiempo | language=Spanish | trans-title=Wagner unmasks M\u00e1scara 2000 Jr.}}</ref> Initially, Carmelo Reyes did not want his sons to become professional wrestlers, wanting them to get an education instead. He reluctantly agreed that they could train for ''Lucha Libre'' with their uncle Andr\u00e9s, but only as a hobby. During their training, Carmelo noticed how serious they took it and reluctantly agreed with their choice to become professional wrestlers.<ref name=DivinasLuchas>{{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Uz7nTR_jZSE | title=Divinas de la lucha Cuatrero y Sans\u00f3n | date=March 5, 2017 | accessdate=February 16, 2017 | first=Elisa | last=Tud\u00f3n | work=Divinas de la Luchas | language=Spanish | trans-title=Divine fighters Cuatrero and Sanson}}</ref>\n\nThere is a long tradition of wrestlers paying for the right to use a ring name in Mexican wrestling, including being allowed to portray a second or third-generation wrestler without being related to the originator.<ref name=MondoFamily>{{cite book|author=Madigan, Dan|title=Mondo Lucha a Go Go: the bizarre & honorable world of wild Mexican wrestling|publisher=[[HarperCollins]] Publisher|year=2007|chapter=A family affair|pages = 128\u2013132|isbn=978-0-06-085583-3}}</ref> It has been confirmed that wrestlers [[Cien Caras Jr.]] and [[El Hijo de Cien Caras]] are unrelated to the Reyes family, while it is unclear if [[Hijo de M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000]] is a blood relative or a purely fictional relative.<ref name=Adios>{{cite web|url=http://www.record.com.mx/blog/el-hijo-del-santo/2010-12-02/el-adios-del-hijo-de-cien-caras |title=El adi\u00f3s del Hijo de Cien Caras |authorlink=El Hijo del Santo | first=El | last=Hijo del Santo |date=December 2, 2010 |accessdate=February 19, 2013 |publisher=R\u00e9cord.com |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101204113931/http://www.record.com.mx/blog/el-hijo-del-santo/2010-12-02/el-adios-del-hijo-de-cien-caras |archivedate=December 4, 2010 |trans-title=Goodbye to El Hijo de Cien Caras}}</ref> Reyes later stated that he allowed the \"Cien Caras\" name to be rented by other wrestlers as his sons were very young and might not want to become professional wrestlers.<ref name=MedioIntro/>\n\n==Professional wrestling career==\n[[File:Nueva Generacion Dinamitas.jpg|thumb|left|[[Sans\u00f3n (wrestler)|Sans\u00f3n]], El Cuatrero and [[Forastero]] outside the ring in November 2018]]\nWhile the El Cuatrero name was first used in 2014, Sans\u00f3n stated that they made their in-ring debut around the year 2010 and worked locally in Lagos de Moreno, while finishing school.<ref name=MedioIntro>{{cite web | url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/mas-deportes/lucha-libre/noticias/2015/12/01/herederos-de-cien-caras-cerca-de-debut-en-arena-mexico | title=Herederos de Cien Caras cerca de debut en Arena M\u00e9xico | date=December 1, 2015 | accessdate=February 16, 2018 | language=Spanish | work=MedioTiempo | first=Apolo | last=Vald\u00e9s | trans-title=The successors to Cien Casas make their debut in Arena Mexico}}</ref> In an interview Cuatrero did state that he briefly wrestled as \"M\u00e1scara Universal\", but his father did not like it and instead suggested the name \"El Cuatrero\", Spanish for \"The [[Cattle rustler]], inspired by the cowboy gimmick that his father and his uncles had used.<ref name=Starmedia>{{cite web | url=http://www.starmedia.com/noticias/sanson-cuatrero-reviviran-memoria-cien-caras-en-arena-mexico/ | title=Sans\u00f3n Y Cuatrero Revivir\u00e1n Memoria De Cien Caras En La Arena M\u00e9xico | date=December 28, 2015 | accessdate=February 16, 2018 | work=StarMedia | language=Spanish | trans-title=Sanson and Cuatrero revieve the memory of Cien Caras in Arena Mexico | archivedate=July 31, 2018  | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731125041/https://www.starmedia.com/noticias/sanson-cuatrero-reviviran-memoria-cien-caras-en-arena-mexico}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.elsoldemexico.com.mx/deportes/Sans\u00f3n-y-Cuatrero-los-\u201cNuevos-Dinamita\u201d-198235.html | title=Sans\u00f3n y Cuatrero, los \"Nuevos Dinamita\" | date=October 23, 2015 | accessdate=February 16, 2018 | language=Spanish | work=El Sol del Mexico | first=Armando | last=Isa\u00eds | trans-title=Sanson and Cuatrero, the \"New Dynamites\"}}</ref> During their time working locally in Lagos de Moreno, the duo won their first ''[[Lucha de Apuestas]]'', or bet match, where they defeated Los Centellas (I and II) and unmasked the duo.<ref name=DivinasLuchas/>\n\n===Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre (2014\u2013present)===\nThe Reyes  brothers worked locally until early 2014, when they began working in Guadalajara for the local ''[[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]]'' (CMLL) promoters in Arena Coliseo. They began training at the CMLL wrestling school, receving training from [[\u00daltimo Guerrero]], [[Virus (wrestler)|Virus]] and [[Franco Colombo]].<ref name=Starmedia/> The Reyes brothers made their CMLL debut on March 25, 2014, where they, along with Universo 2000 lost to the trio of [[Blue Panther]], [[Sagrado (wrestler)|Sagrado]], and [[Valiente (wrestler)|Valiente]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=108892 | title=CMLL Guadalajara Martes | date=March 25, 2014 | accessdate=February 18, 2018 | work=CageMatch| language=German}}</ref> While working in Guadalajara, El Cuatrero and Sans\u00f3n competed in a tournament to determine the number one contenders for the local Occidente Tag Team Championship, but the two were eliminated by the team of Flash and Flash II.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=124225 | title=CMLL Guadalajara Viernes | date=January 30, 2015 | accessdate=July 29, 2018 | work=CageMatch| language=German}}</ref> The brothers teamed up with Jocker, with the winners being crowned the new Occidente Trios Champions. The team made it all the way to the final match of the tournament but was defeated by Furia Roja, Mr. Trueno, and Ray Trueno.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=128976 | title=CMLL Guadalajara Domingos | date=March 5, 2015 | accessdate=July 29, 2018 | work=CageMatch| language=German}}</ref> On November 11, 2015, Cuatrero and Sans\u00f3n teamed up with their cousin Forastero and won the Occidente Trios Championship.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=140036 | title=LLE | date=November 11, 2015 | accessdate=July 29, 2018 | work=CageMatch| language=German}}</ref>\n\nOn January 5, 2017, El Cuatrero worked his first CMLL match in Mexico City in the company's main venue. as he participated in the 2017 version of ''[[La Copa Junior]]'' but was eliminated from the tournament before the finals.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/mas-deportes/lucha-libre/noticias/2016/01/06/puma-finalista-de-la-copa-jr-del-cmll | title=Puma, finalista de la Copa Jr. del CMLL | date=January 6, 2015 | accessdate=January 10, 2016 | work=MedioTiempo | language=Spanish | trans-title=Puma finalist in the CMLL La Copa Jr.}}</ref> At that point, the Reyes brothers began being referred to as ''Nueva Generacion Dinamitas'' (Spanish for \"New Generation Dynamites\"; NGD) as a reference to their heritage. On March 18, 2016, ''Nueva Generacion Dinamitas'' worked their first major show for CMLL, defeating [[Soberano Jr.]] and [[Oro Jr.]] in the opening match of that year's ''[[Homenaje a Dos Leyendas (2016)|Homenaje A Dos Leyendas]]'' show.<ref name=DosLeyendas2016SL>{{cite web | url=http://superluchas.com/cmll-homenaje-a-dos-leyendas-cobertura-y-resultados-21032016/ | title=CMLL \"Homenaje a Dos Leyendas\" \u2013 Cobertura y Resultados \u2013 21/03/2016 \u2013 M\u00e1ximo Sexy y Negro Casas, pelones | author=Dark Angelita | date=March 18, 2016 | accessdate=March 19, 2016 | work=[[S\u00faper Luchas]] | language=Spanish | trans-title= CMLL \"Homage to Two Legends \u2013 Coverage and results \u2013 21/02/1016 \u2013 M\u00e1ximo Sexy and Negro Casas bald}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://es-us.deportes.yahoo.com/fotos/homenaje-a-dos-leyendas-lucha-libre-arena-m%C3%A9xico-viernes-18-de-marzo-de-2016-slideshow/ | title=Homenaje a Dos Leyendas, Lucha Libre Arena M\u00e9xico, Viernes 18 de Marzo de 2016 | date=March 19, 2016 | accessdate=March 19, 2016 | publisher=[[Yahoo!]] | work=Yahoo! Deportes | first=Gonzalo | last= L\u00f3pez Peralta}}</ref> CMLL decided to have both El Cuatrero and Sans\u00f3n participate in their annual ''[[Torneo Gran Alternativa (2016)|Torneo Gran Alternativa]]'' (\"Great Alternativa Tournament\") where younger wrestlers team up with established veteran wrestlers. El Cuatrero was paired with [[Rey Bucanero]], but the duo lost to [[Trit\u00f3n (wrestler)|Trit\u00f3n]] and [[M\u00edstico II|M\u00edstico]] in the first round.<ref name=Medio2016BlockA>{{cite web | url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/mas-deportes/lucha-libre/noticias/2016/03/23/rey-escorpion-y-fujin-por-la-gran-alternativa | title=Rey Escorpi\u00f3n y Fuj\u00edn, por la Gran Alternativa | date=March 23, 2016 | accessdate=March 23, 2016 | work=MedioTiempo | language=Spanish | trans-title=Rey Escorpi\u00f3n and Fuj\u00edn go for the Gran Alternativa}}</ref> A year later, El Cuatrero was teamed up with his uncle M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000 for the 2017 version of the ''[[Torneo Gran Alternativa (2017)|Torneo Gran Alternativa]]'',  but like the 2016 tournament, El Cuatrero did not make it past the first round as the team lost to [[Esfinge]] and [[Atlantis (wrestler)|Atlantis]].<ref name=2017BlockAF4W>{{cite web | url=http://www.f4wonline.com/mexico/cmll-arena-mexico-results-la-gran-alternativa-tournament-begins-236681| title=CMLL Arena Mexico Results: La Gran Alternativa tournament begins | date=June 4, 2017 | accessdate=June 11, 2017 | work=Wrestling Observer Figure Four Online | first=Chris | last=Aiken}}</ref> While El Cuatrero's first years on the main roster had seen little success, July 2017 proved a turning point in how ''Nueva Generacion Dinamitas'' was booked as El Cuatrero and Sans\u00f3n defeated [[Black Terry]] and [[Negro Navarro]] to win the [[CMLL Arena Coliseo Tag Team Championship]], CMLL's second-highest ranked tag team championship.<ref name=NGD/> Three days later the trio defeated ''[[Los Hijos del Infierno]]'' ([[Ephesto]], [[Luciferno]], and [[Mephisto (wrestler)|Mephisto]]) to win the [[Mexican National Trios Championship]], making Ephesto a triple championship.<ref name=NGDTrios/> The trio would win CMLL's ''La Copa Dinastia'', defeating the trios of Blue Panther, [[Blue Panther Jr.]], [[The Panther (wrestler)|The Panter]] and then [[Dragon Lee (wrestler)|Dragon Lee]], M\u00edstico, and [[Comandante Pierroth|Pierroth]].<ref name=CopaDinastia2017/> \n\nOn January 19, 2018, as part of the annual [[Fantastica Mania 2018|2018 Fantastica Mania]] tour of Japan, El Cuatrero defeated [[\u00c1ngel de Oro]] to win the [[CMLL World Middleweight Championship]].<ref name=CuatreroMiddle/> The match and championship change was the beginning of a long-running storyline feud between El Cuatrero and \u00c1ngel de Oro, where challenges for a ''Lucha de Apuestas'' match soon followed.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/lucha-libre/2018/02/07/angel-de-oro-y-cuatrero-se-jugaran-las-mascaras-en-homenaje-a-dos-leyendas | language=Spanish | accessdate=July 30, 2018 | date=February 7, 2019 | work=MedioTiempo | title=\u00c1ngel de Oro y Cuatrero se jugaran las mascaras en Homenaje a Dos Leyendas | trans-title=\u00c1ngel de Oro, fighting for the asks at Homage to Two Legends}}</ref> On February 14, 2018, ''Nueva Generacion Dinamitas'' announced they were giving up the CMLL Arena Coliseo Tag Team Championship, with the storyline given that they were focusing on winning the [[CMLL World Tag Team Championship]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://twitter.com/CMLL_OFICIAL/status/964177915343724550 | title=Sans\u00f3n y Cuatrero renuncian al Campeonato de Parejas de la Arena Coliseo. | trans-title=Sans\u00f3n and Cuatrero give up the Arena Colise Tag Team Championship |date=February 15, 2018 | accessdate=March 11, 2018 | author=CMLL | publisher=[[Twitter]] | language=Spanish}}</ref> The storyline feud between El Cuatrero and \u00c1ngel de Oro reached its peak at the 2018 ''[[Homenaje a Dos Leyendas (2018)|Homenaje a Dos Leyendas]]'' show, where both competitors put their mask on the line in the main event match of the night. It ended with El Cuatrero defeating \u00c1ngel de Oro two falls to one, forcing \u00c1ngel de Oro to remove his mask as per ''lucha libre'' tradition.<ref name=AngelApuesta/> He would later make his first and second successful defense of the CMLL World Middleweight Championship against \u00c1ngel de Oro.<ref name=CMLLMiddle>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=5&nr=93&page=5&reign=19 | title= CMLL World Middleweight Championship >> Title Reigns >> 19.01.2018 - Today: El Cuatrero| accessdate=March 4, 2020 | work=CageMatch}}</ref> At the [[CMLL 85th Anniversary Show]], the Dinamitas defeated Atlantis, El Soberano Jr., and Mistico as part of CMLL's most important show of the year.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.f4wonline.com/mexico/cmll-85th-aniversario-live-results-hair-vs-hair-tag-team-main-event-265781 | title=CMLL 85. Aniversario live results: hair vs. hair tag team main event | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter|Wrestling Observer Figure Four Online]] | date=September 14, 2018 | accessdate=September 15, 2018 | first=Chris | last=Aiken}}</ref> On November 6, 2018, Cuatrero made his third successful middleweight championship defense as he defeated [[Tit\u00e1n (wrestler)|Tit\u00e1n]].<ref name=CMLLMiddle/>\n\n2019 was the first year that all three members of Nueva Generaci\u00f3n Dinamitas participated in the annual [[Fantastica Mania 2019|Fantastica Mania]] tour of Japan, capping off the tour with a successful championship defense against \u00c1ngel de Oro, Atlantis, and Tit\u00e1n on the last day of the tour.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.f4wonline.com/japan/njpwcmll-fantastica-mania-results-my-dad-heel-wrestler-match-275026 | title=NJPW/CMLL Fantastica Mania results: 'My Dad is a heel wrestler' match | date=January 21, 2019 | accessdate=January 21, 2019 | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]] | first=Ethan | last=Renner}}</ref> 2019 also marked the first year that El Cuatrero participated in the [[CMLL Universal Championship (2019)|Universal Championship]], a tournament where all 16 participants held a championship recognized by CMLL. In the opening round. he defeated perennial rival Soberano Jr. before losing to \u00daltimo Guerrero in the quarterfinals.<ref name=BlockBOvaciones>{{cite web | url=https://ovaciones.com/vence-al-maestro/ | title=\u00a1Vence al maestro! | trans-title=defeating the master | date=February 9, 2019 | accessdate=February 9, 2019 | first=Arturo | last=Rosas Platas | language=Spanish | work=Ovaciones}}</ref><ref name=BlockBMarca>{{cite web | url=https://www.marca.com/claro-mx/otros-deportes/lucha-libre/2019/02/09/5c5e6f62268e3e8f7c8b45a1.html | work=Marca Claro | title=Niebla Roja se impone en la segunda fase del torneo Campe\u00f3n Universal 2019 | trans-title=Niebla Roja looks imposing in the second phase of the 2019 Universal Championship | date=February 9, 2019 | accessdate=February 9, 2019 | language=Spanish}}</ref> For the 2019 ''[[CMLL Torneo Nacional de Parejas Incre\u00edbles (2019)|Torneo Nacional de Parejas Incre\u00edbles]]'' (\"National incredible teams tournament), Cuatrero was paired up with M\u00edstico, as a ''[[Heel (professional wrestling)|rudo]]'' (The \"bad guy\") and a ''[[Face (professional wrestling)|tecnico]]'' (the \"Good guy\") team up for the event. The odd couple defeated [[Hechicero]] and [[Stuka Jr.]], then Atlantis and Negro Casas, before ultimately losing to \u00daltimo Guerrero and Volador Jr. in the semifinals.<ref name=Increibles2019B>{{cite web | url= https://www.20minutos.com.mx/deportes/noticia/ultimo-guerrero-y-volador-jr-van-a-final-de-torneo-increible-505260/0/ | title= \u00daltimo Guerrero y Volador Jr. van a final de \"Torneo incre\u00edble\"|trans-title=\u00daltimo Guerrero and Volador Jr. goes to the finals of the \u201cIncredible Tournament\u201d| language=Spanish | work=20 Minutos | author=Notimex | date=April 20, 2019 | accessdate=May 17, 2019}}</ref><ref name=Ovaciones2019B>{{cite web | url=https://ovaciones.com/volador-y-guerrero-a-la-final/ | title=Volador y Guerrero a la final | trans-title=Volador and Guerrero in the finals | language=Spanish | accessdate=May 17, 2019 | date=April 20, 2019  | work=Ovacones | first=Arturo | last=Rosas Plata}}</ref> As part of the 66th anniversary of Arena Puebla, NGD successfully defended the Mexican National Trios Championship against ''[[Los Ingobernables]]'' ([[El Terrible]], [[La Bestia del Ring]], and [[Rush (wrestler)|Rush]]), in what was their tenth overall championship defense.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=5&nr=532&page=5&reign=41 | title=Mexican National Trios Championship >> 25.07.2017 - today: La Sangre Dinamita (El Cuatrero, Forasteo & Sanson) | work=CageMatch | accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> In December, El Cuatrero made his fourth successful defense of the CMLL World Middleweight Championship as he defeated [[Car\u00edstico]] on December 12.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=250178 | title=CMLL Sabados De Coliseo | date=December 12, 2019 | accessdate=March 31, 2020 | work=CageMatch}}</ref>\n\nThe 2020 ''[[Sin Piedad (2020)|Sin Piedad]]'' show offered Cuatrero the opportunity to become a quadruple champion as he and Sans\u00f3n challenged M\u00edstico and Car\u00edstico for the CMLL World Tag Team Championship, but lost the match.<ref name=SP2020Medio>{{cite web | url=https://www.mediotiempo.com/lucha-libre/cmll/espiritu-negro-fue-desenmascarado-por-principe-diamante | title=Cay\u00f3 la primera m\u00e1scara en el 2020 dentro del CMLL; Esp\u00edritu Negro revel\u00f3 su rostro | trans-title=The first mask loss in CMLL of 2020; Espiritu Negro revealed his face | language=Spanish | date=January 2, 2020 | accessdate=January 2, 2020 | work=MedioTiempo}}</ref> During the 2020 [[Fantastica Mania 2020|Fantastica Mania]] tour, Cuatrero and his brother participated in the [[List of CMLL tag team tournaments#2020 Family tag team tournament|family tag team tournament]], where they ended up defeating ''Los Hermanos Chavez'' (\u00c1ngel de Oro and Niebla Roja) in the finals.<ref name=FM20Jan19>{{cite web | url=https://www.njpw.co.jp/tornament/220096?showResult=1 | title=NJPW presents CMLL Fantastica Mania 2020 | language=Japanese | date=January 17, 2020 | accessdate=January 17, 2020 | work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]}}</ref> On the final day of the tour, January 20, NGD successfully defended the Mexican National Trios Championship against ''Los Hermanos Chavez'' and Tit\u00e1n.<ref name=NJPWFM202Jan20>{{cite web | url=https://www.njpw.co.jp/tornament/220098?showResult=1 | title=NJPW presents CMLL Fantastica Mania 2020 | date=January 20, 2020 | accessdate=January 20, 2020 | work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] | language=Japanese}}</ref> On February 24, 2020, El Cuatrero and Sans\u00f3n won the ''[[#Torneo de parejas familiares|Torneo de parejas familiares]]'' (\"Family team tournament\") as they defeated the uncle/nephew team of Rey Bucanero and [[Drone (wrestler)|Drone]] in the first round, the father/son team of [[Euforia (wrestler)|Euforia]] and Soberano Jr. in the second round, and finally the [[Gran Guerrero]]/\u00daltimo Guerrero brothers in the finals.<ref name=NGDFamiliares/><ref name=LuchaCentral/>\n\n===Independent circuit (2014\u2013current)===\nWhile working for CMLL, Cuatrero, like all CMLL workes, is allowed to take independent circuit bookings on days he is not needed by CMLL or arranged through CMLL. On February 19, 2017, Cuatrero and Sans\u00f3n unsuccessfully challenged Black Terry and Negro Navarro for the CMLL Arena Coliseo Tag Team Championship on a ''Lucha Memes'' show in Puebla.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=173059 | title=Lucha Memes | date=February 19, 2017 | accessdate=February 4, 2020 | work=CageMatch}}</ref> NGD also successfully defended the Mexican National Tag Team Championship against Los Kamikazes del Aire (Alas de Acero, [[Aramis]], and Iron Kid) at a subsequent ''Lucha Memes'' show.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=192320 | title=Lucha Memes Chairo 12 | date=May 2, 2018| accessdate=February 4, 2020 | work=CageMatch}}</ref> \n\nAs part of CMLL's collaboration with [[The Crash Lucha Libre]], Nueva Generaci\u00f3n Dinamitas has performed on several The Crash shows over the years. In their initial appearance for The Crash, Nueva Generaci\u00f3n Dinamitas lost to [[La Rebeli\u00f3n Amarilla]] ([[Bestia 666]], [[Jacob Fatu]] and [[Mecha Wolf 450]]).<ref>{{cite web | url=https://tjsports.com.mx/se-termina-la-rebelion/ |title=\u00a1Se Termina \u2018La Rebeli\u00f3n\u2019! | trans-title=The end of \"The Rebellion\" | date=September 8, 2018 | accessdate=March 3, 2020 | language=Spanish | work=TJ Sports}}</ref> The team returned to The Crash for their [[The Crash VII Aniversario|VII Anniversary Show]] show, where they lost to ''Los Lucha Bros'' ([[Pentag\u00f3n Jr.|Penta El 0M]] and [[F\u00e9nix (wrestler)|The King]]) in a match for [[The Crash Tag Team Championship]] that also included [[Reno Scum]] (Adam Thornstowe and Luster the Legend).<ref name=LuchaCentral>{{cite web | url=https://www.luchacentral.com/resultados-aniversario-vii-the-crash-espanol/ | title=\u00a1Resultados Aniversario VII THE CRASH ! Espanol | trans-title=Results of the Crash VII Anniversary! Spanish | date=November 3, 2018 | accessdate=November 4, 2018 | first=Miguel | last=Pe\u00f1a | work=Lucha Central | language=Spanish}}</ref><ref name=LuchaWorld>{{cite web | url=http://www.luchaworld.com/?p=86983 | title=Lucha Report for 11/4/18 | date=November 4, 2018 | accessdate=November 4, 2018 | first=Alfredo | last=Esparza | work=Lucha World}}</ref> They returned to The Crash in December 2018, losing to Bestia 666 and [[Garza Jr.]] in the main event.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://tjsports.com.mx/garza-jr-y-bestia-666-demostraron-porque-son-la-cara-de-the-crash-lucha-libre/| title=Garza Jr. Y Bestia 666 Demostraron Porque Son La Cara De The Crash Lucha Libre | trans-title=Garza Jr. Y Bestia 666 demonstrate why they are the face of The Crash Lucha Libre | work=TJ Sports | language=Spanish | accessdate=March 4, 2020 | date=December 1, 2018}}</ref> In 2019 Cuatrero and Sans\u00f3n worked an extended storyline against ''[[Los Traumas]]'' ([[Trauma I]] and [[Trauma II]]) in The Crash. In June Sans\u00f3n was forced to team up with Trauma I to face Cuatrero and Trauma I in a ''[[relevos incre\u00edbles]]'' (\"incredible pairs\" match), where the regular partners refused to wrestle against each other. In the end, Sans\u00f3n and Trauma I after Trauma II hit El Cuatrero during the match.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=231526 | title=The Crash | date=June 15, 2019 | accessdate=March 4, 2020 | work=CageMatch}}</ref> This was followed by a tag team match where NGD defeated Los Traumas by disqualification as part of their ongoing storyline.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=233101 | title=FCP Project Mexico| date=September 7, 2019 | accessdate=March 4, 2020 | work=CageMatch}}</ref>\n\nOn June 16, 2019, Cuatrero, Forastero, and Sans\u00f3n appeared at International Wrestling Revolution Group's annual [[Festival de las M\u00e1scaras (2019)|Festival de las M\u00e1scaras]] show. The trio defeated their cousin M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000 Jr., teaming with Capo del Sur and Capo del Norte, who both use ring characters inspired by the original ''Los Dinamitas''<ref name=FdM2019>{{cite web | url=http://www.thegladiatores.com/emotivo-homenaje-a-vampiro-canadiense-en-el-festival-de-mascaras/ | title=Emotivo homenaje a Vampiro Canadiense en el festival de m\u00e1scaras. | trans-title=Emotional homage to Canadian Vampire at the Festival of the Masks| date=June 17, 2019 | accessdate=August 8, 2019 | language=Spanish | work=The Gladiatores | first=Alfonso |last=Lizzaranga}}</ref>\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n*'''[[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]]'''\n:*[[CMLL World Middleweight Championship]] ([[List of CMLL World Middleweight Champions#Title history|1 time]], current)<ref name=CuatreroMiddle>{{cite web | url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/card_result/130117 | title=NJPW presents CMLL Fantastica Mania 2018 CMLL\u4e16\u754c\u30df\u30c9\u30eb\u7d1a\u9078\u624b\u6a29\u8a66\u5408 | trans-title= NJPW Presents CMLL Fanastica Mania 2018 CMLL World Middleweight Championship |publisher=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] | language=Japanese | date=January 19, 2018 | accessdate=January 19, 2018 }}</ref>\n:*[[CMLL Arena Coliseo Tag Team Championship]] ([[CMLL Arena Coliseo Tag Team Championship|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[Sans\u00f3n (wrestler)|Sans\u00f3n]]<ref name=NGD>{{cite web | url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/lucha-libre/2017/07/22/sanson-y-cuatrero-nuevos-campeones-de-la-arena-coliseo | title=Sans\u00f3n y Cuatrero, nuevos campeones de la Arena Coliseo | date=July 22, 2017 | accessdate=July 24, 2017 | work=MedioTiempo | language=Spanish | first=Apolo | last=Vald\u00e9s | trans-title=Sanson and Cuatrero, new champions of Arena Coliseo}}</ref>\n:*[[Mexican National Trios Championship]] ([[List of Mexican National Trios Champions#Title history|1 time]], current) \u2013 with Sans\u00f3n and [[Forastero]]<ref name=NGDTrios>{{cite web | url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/lucha-libre/2017/07/26/sanson-cuatrero-y-forastero-campeones-nacionales-de-tercias | title=Sans\u00f3n, Cuatrero y Forastero, campeones nacionales de tercias | date=July 26, 2017 | accessdate=July 26, 2017 | work=MedioTiempo | language=Spanish | trans-title=Sanson, Cuatrero and Forastero National Trios Champions}}</ref>\n:*Occidente Trios Championship (1 time, current) \u2013 with Sans\u00f3n and Forastero<ref name=DivinasLuchas/><ref name=OCCTrios>{{cite web | title=Occidente Trios Championship | publisher=cagematch |url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=5&nr=2518 | accessdate=January 23, 2020}}</ref>\n:*''La Copa Dinastia'' (2017) \u2013 with Sans\u00f3n and Forastero<ref name=CopaDinastia2017>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=187827 | title=CMLL Super Viernes | date=November 24, 2017 | accessdate=July 29, 2018 | work=CageMatch | language=German}}</ref>\n:*''[[Torneo de parejas familiares]]'' (2020) \u2013 with Sans\u00f3n<ref name=NGDFamiliares>{{cite web | url=https://superluchas.com/cmll-la-ngd-se-lleva-el-torneo-de-parejas-familiares-de-puebla/ | title=CMLL: La NGD se lleva el Torneo de Parejas Familiares de Puebla | author=Dark Angelita | date=February 25, 2020 | accessdate=February 26, 2020 | language=Spanish | work=[[S\u00faper Luchas]] | trans-title=CMLL: The NGD win the Family Tag Team Tournament in Puebla}}</ref>\n\n*'''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n**Ranked #'''322''' of the best 500 singles wrestlers in the [[PWI 500]] in 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=97&nr=230#2018|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated (PWI) 500 for 2018|accessdate=September 14, 2018|work=CageMatch}}</ref>\n\n==''Luchas de Apuestas'' record==\n{{See also|Lucha libre#Luchas de Apuestas|l1=Luchas de Apuestas}}\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=100%  style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=20% scope=\"col\"|Winner (wager)\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=20% scope=\"col\"|Loser (wager)\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=20% scope=\"col\"|Location\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=20% scope=\"col\"|Event\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=15% scope=\"col\"|Date\n!class=\"unsortable\" style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=5% scope=\"col\"|Notes\n|-\n|El Cuatrero and [[Sans\u00f3n (wrestler)|Sans\u00f3n]] (masks) || Los Centellas (I and II) || N/A || Live show || N/A || <ref name=DivinasLuchas/>\n|-\n|El Cuatrero (mask) || [[\u00c1ngel de Oro]] (mask) || [[Arena Mexico]] || ''[[Homenaje a Dos Leyendas (2018)|Homenaje a Dos Leyendas]]'' || {{dts|March 16, 2018}} || <ref name=AngelApuesta>{{cite web |url= https://ovaciones.com/cae-angel-de-oro |title= \u00a1Cae \u00c1ngel de Oro! |first= Arturo |last= Rosas Plata |date= March 17, 2018 |accessdate= June 23, 2018 |language= Spanish |publisher= Ovaciones | trans-title=The fall of \u00c1ngel de Oro!}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre roster}}\n{{CMLL Arena Coliseo Tag Team Championship}}\n{{CMLL World Middleweight Championship}}\n{{Mexican National Trios Championship}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Mexico}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cuatrero, El}}\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Mexican male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Masked wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Twofingered Typist", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProfessional wrestling career:wording; edit for flow", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/El_Cuatrero"}
{"title_page": "Shehr-e-Zaat (novella)", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=August 2015}}\n{{notable|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox short story | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] -->\n| name              = Shehr-e-Zaat\n|image              = \n| title_orig        =\n| translator        =\n| author            = [[Umera Ahmed]]\n| country           = Pakistan\n| language          = Urdu\n| series            = ''[[Umera Ahmed#Publications|Main Ne Khawabon Ka Shajar Dekha Hai]]''\n| genre             = [[Novella]]\n| published_in      = ''Shuaa Digest''\n| publication_type  = [[Periodical]]<br>[[Book]]\n| publisher         = \n| media_type        = Print\n| pub_date          = \n| english_pub_date  =\n| preceded_by       = \n| followed_by       = \n}}\n\n'''''Shehr-e-Zaat''''' ({{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|'''\u0634\u06c1\u0631\u0630\u0627\u062a'''}}}} ; ''lit: City of Self'' ) is a [[novella]] by Pakistani [[fiction writer]] [[Umera Ahmed]] published in 2002. A blog at the ''[[Express Tribune]]'' describes the story as a fictional story with an elements of spiritualism and philosophy. Story tells the obsession of ones, with worldly life forgetting its creator, a journey from self to subsistence.<ref>{{cite web|title=''Shehr-e-Zaat'' a spiritual Romance|url=http://blogs.tribune.com.pk/story/14184/shehr-e-zaat-a-spiritual-romance/|publisher=[[Express Tribune]]|work=Sadaf Haider|date=12 October 2012|accessdate=21 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n\nStory revolves around an arrogant, class conscious and narcissistic Falak Sher Afgan an only child to very rich parents. She fell in love with Salman after seeing him in her friends wedding ceremony, Falak tries every way to get in touch with Salman. She faked her presence as a coincident at shopping mall while following him and then she started meeting him. Salman couldn't resist her beauty and affection which makes him in love with her from head over heels too. Belonging to the elite class she has always been the center of attention and never been deprived of anything. She never came across through religious brightness and divinity. Falak's mother, Memoona built her subsistence according to the worldly life. Finally, Falak manages to marry Salman, and they live happily together, initially Salmans proves to be a good husband despite his father in law, Sher Afgan's reservations. Life was luxurious and full of joy but destiny decides doom for Falak when Salman falls in love with an uneducated an crass employee Tabinda at his factory with whom he begins an extramarital relationship. Falak decides to meet Tabinda and confront her. Upon seeing her unattractive physical appearance and crassness, she goes in a state of shock and eventually suffers from a major nervous breakdown. She comes back to consciousness with a broken heart and for the first time in life looks at her tragedy from a different perspective. Instead of craving for Salman\u2019s lost love she ponders over the power of destiny. The fact that Salman preferred Tabinda, an ugly looking woman with a loose character over her, forces her to go through a journey of self-discovery. She comes across bitter realities and learns the true purpose of life while receiving Islamic perceptions through ''self to subsistence''. Falak finally adapts simplicity, patience and humbleness, she brought quietness in her life and manages to get rid of unnecessary worldly and hollow pursuits. She eventually accepts Salman back in her life after Tabinda leaves him but without her previous obsession.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shehr e Zaat Story & Details|url=http://www.tv.com.pk/tvshow/Shehr-e-Zaat/81/story|publisher=TV.com|accessdate=21 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Publication==\n\n''Shehr-e-Zaat'' was first published in Shuaa Digest as a story in complete novel section, followed by other six stories unrelated to each other. All the stories were then compile in a form of book called ''Main Ne Khawabon Ka Shajar Dekha Hai'' (English: I have seen the Garden of Dreams). It was also published in one of early published edition of Ahmed book ''Meri Zaat Zarra-e-Benishan'' (English: My subsistence is like nothing but jot).\n\nOther stories were ''Mein Ne Khabon Ka Shajar Dekha Hay'', ''Koi Lamha Khaab Nahi Hota'', ''Koi Baat Hay Teri Baat Me'', ''Muthi Bhar Mitti'' and ''Teri Yaad Khar-e-Gulab Hay''.\n\n==Television adaptation==\n{{main|Shehr-e-Zaat}}\nIn 2012, a television adaption was made by [[Hum TV]] in collaboration with channels production house [[Moomal Productions|MD Productions]] with [[Abdullah Kadwani]] and Asad Qureshi of [[7th Sky Entertainment]]. The drama serial stars [[Mahira Khan]] as Falak, [[Meekal Zulfiqar]] as Salman and [[Nadia Afghan]] as Tabinda. While for the serial two more characters were written by Umera, Hamza (played by [[Mohib Mirza]]) and Nani (played by [[Samina Peerzada]]).<ref>{{cite web|title=Shehr-e-Zaat Hum TV Drama Serial & Umera Ahmed Novel|url=http://www.web.pk/2012/shehr-e-zaat-hum-tv-drama-serial-umera-ahmed-novel/|publisher=|date=September 5, 2012|accessdate=21 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{no footnotes| section|date=August 2015}}\n* [https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.mfsolutions.urdu.novels ''Read Shehr-e-Zaat Novel''] \n* [http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/15778941-shehr-e-zaat ''Shehr-e-Zaat''] on GoodReads\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Umera Ahmad}}\n\n[[Category:Urdu fiction]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Pakistan]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=August 2015}}\n{{notable|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox short story | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] -->\n| name              = Shehr-e-Zaat\n|image              = \n| title_orig        =\n| translator        =\n| author            = [[Umera Ahmed]]\n| country           = Pakistan\n| language          = Urdu\n| series            = ''[[Umera Ahmed#Publications|Main Ne Khawabon Ka Shajar Dekha Hai]]''\n| genre             = [[Novella]]\n| published_in      = ''Shuaa Digest''\n| publication_type  = [[Periodical]]<br>[[Book]]\n| publisher         = \n| media_type        = Print\n| pub_date          = \n| english_pub_date  =\n| preceded_by       = \n| followed_by       = \n}}\n\n'''''Shehr-e-Zaat''''' ({{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|'''\u0634\u06c1\u0631\u0630\u0627\u062a'''}}}} ; ''lit: City of Self'' ) is a [[novella]] by Pakistani [[fiction writer]] [[Umera Ahmed]] published in 2002. A blog at the ''[[Express Tribune]]'' describes the story as a fictional story with an elements of spiritualism and philosophy. Story tells the obsession of ones, with worldly life forgetting its creator, a journey from self to subsistence.<ref>{{cite web|title=''Shehr-e-Zaat'' a spiritual Romance|url=http://blogs.tribune.com.pk/story/14184/shehr-e-zaat-a-spiritual-romance/|publisher=[[Express Tribune]]|work=Sadaf Haider|date=12 October 2012|accessdate=21 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Plot summary==\n\nStory revolves around an arrogant, class conscious and narcissistic Falak Sher Afgan an only child to very rich parents. She fell in love with Salman after seeing him in her friends wedding ceremony, Falak tries every way to get in touch with Salman. She faked her presence as a coincident at shopping mall while following him and then she started meeting him. Salman couldn't resist her beauty and affection which makes him in love with her from head over heels too. Belonging to the elite class she has always been the center of attention and never been deprived of anything. She never came across through religious brightness and divinity. Falak's mother, Memoona built her subsistence according to the worldly life. Finally, Falak manages to get married to Salman, and they live happily together, initially Salmans proves to be a good husband despite his father in law, Sher Afgan's reservations. Life was luxurious and full of joy but destiny decides doom for Falak when Salman falls in love with an uneducated an crass employee Tabinda at his factory with whom he begins an extramarital relationship. Falak decides to meet Tabinda and confront her. Upon seeing her unattractive physical appearance and crassness, she goes in a state of shock and eventually suffers from a major nervous breakdown. She comes back to consciousness with a broken heart and for the first time in life looks at her tragedy from a different perspective. Instead of craving for Salman\u2019s lost love she ponders over the power of destiny. The fact that Salman preferred Tabinda, an ugly looking woman with a loose character over her, forces her to go through a journey of self-discovery. She comes across bitter realities and learns the true purpose of life while receiving Islamic perceptions through ''self to subsistence''. Falak finally adapts simplicity, patience and humbleness, she brought quietness in her life and manages to get rid of unnecessary worldly and hollow pursuits. She eventually accepts Salman back in her life after Tabinda leaves him but without her previous obsession.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shehr e Zaat Story & Details|url=http://www.tv.com.pk/tvshow/Shehr-e-Zaat/81/story|publisher=TV.com|accessdate=21 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Publication==\n\n''Shehr-e-Zaat'' was first published in Shuaa Digest as a story in complete novel section, followed by other six stories unrelated to each other. All the stories were then compile in a form of book called ''Main Ne Khawabon Ka Shajar Dekha Hai'' (English: I have seen the Garden of Dreams). It was also published in one of early published edition of Ahmed book ''Meri Zaat Zarra-e-Benishan'' (English: My subsistence is like nothing but jot).\n\nOther stories were ''Mein Ne Khabon Ka Shajar Dekha Hay'', ''Koi Lamha Khaab Nahi Hota'', ''Koi Baat Hay Teri Baat Me'', ''Muthi Bhar Mitti'' and ''Teri Yaad Khar-e-Gulab Hay''.\n\n==Television adaptation==\n{{main|Shehr-e-Zaat}}\nIn 2012, a television adaption was made by [[Hum TV]] in collaboration with channels production house [[Moomal Productions|MD Productions]] with [[Abdullah Kadwani]] and Asad Qureshi of [[7th Sky Entertainment]]. The drama serial stars [[Mahira Khan]] as Falak, [[Meekal Zulfiqar]] as Salman and [[Nadia Afghan]] as Tabinda. While for the serial two more characters were written by Umera, Hamza (played by [[Mohib Mirza]]) and Nani (played by [[Samina Peerzada]]).<ref>{{cite web|title=Shehr-e-Zaat Hum TV Drama Serial & Umera Ahmed Novel|url=http://www.web.pk/2012/shehr-e-zaat-hum-tv-drama-serial-umera-ahmed-novel/|publisher=|date=September 5, 2012|accessdate=21 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{no footnotes| section|date=August 2015}}\n* [https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.mfsolutions.urdu.novels ''Read Shehr-e-Zaat Novel''] \n* [http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/15778941-shehr-e-zaat ''Shehr-e-Zaat''] on GoodReads\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Umera Ahmad}}\n\n[[Category:Urdu fiction]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Pakistan]]\n", "name_user": "Jellysandwich0", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shehr-e-Zaat_(novella)"}
{"title_page": "Aurat March", "text_new": "The '''Aurat March''' ([[Urdu]]: \u0639\u0648\u0631\u062a \u0645\u0627\u0631\u0686 ) ([[English language|English]]: Women March ) is an annual [[Demonstration (political)|political demonstration]] organized in various cities of [[Pakistan]] including [[Lahore]], [[Hyderabad, Sindh|Hyderabad]], [[Sukkur]], [[Karachi]] and [[Islamabad]] to observe [[International Women's Day|International Women's Day]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Do2ADwAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Feminism, Postfeminism and Legal Theory: Beyond the Gendered Subject?|last=Gozdecka|first=Dorota|last2=Macduff|first2=Anne|date=2019-01-08|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781351040402|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kirmani|first=Nida|last2=Khan|first2=Ayesha|date=2018-11-27|title=Moving Beyond the Binary: Gender-based Activism in Pakistan|url=https://opendocs.ids.ac.uk/opendocs/handle/123456789/14196|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sahar|first=Naila|date=2018-10-02|title=Things She Could Never Have|journal=South Asian Review|volume=39|issue=3\u20134|pages=420\u2013422|doi=10.1080/02759527.2018.1518037|issn=0275-9527}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://images.dawn.com/news/1181993|title=The Aurat March challenges misogyny in our homes, workplaces and society, say organisers ahead of Women's Day|last=Staff|first=Images|date=2019-03-07|website=Images|language=en|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://natcour.com/story/238374/heres-all-you-need-to-know-about-aurat-march-2019/|title=Here's all you need to know about Aurat March 2019|date=2019-02-28|website=NC|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-09}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1468109|title=Aurat March to highlight 'Sisterhood and Solidarity'|last=Reporter|first=The Newspaper's Staff|date=2019-03-07|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1394385|title=Why the Aurat March is a revolutionary feat for Pakistan|last=Shah|first=Zuneera|date=2018-03-12|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2019-03-17}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/mar/15/pakistan-torn-as-womens-day-march-sparks-wave-of-masculine-anxiety|title=Pakistan torn as women's day march sparks wave of 'masculine anxiety'|last=Zahra-Malik|first=Mehreen|date=2019-03-15|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=2019-03-16|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2019/mar/08/women-take-to-the-streets-of-pakistan-to-rewrite-their-place-in-society-international-womens-day |title=Women take to the streets of Pakistan to rewrite their place in society |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=2019-03-08 |accessdate=2019-03-17 |last=Toppa |first=Sabrina}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/stories-47832236|title=The 'womanspreading' placard that caused fury in Pakistan|last=Ebrahim|first=Ammar|date=2019-04-06|access-date=2019-04-13|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@zoya_rehman/aurat-march-and-undisciplined-bodies-f6f23ada0318|title=Aurat March and Undisciplined Bodies:|last=Rehman|first=Zoya|date=2019-07-26|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> The first Aurat March was held on 8 March 2018 in [[Karachi]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/03/pakistani-women-hold-aurat-march-equality-gender-justice-190308115740534.html|title=Pakistani women hold 'aurat march' for equality, gender justice|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2019-03-16}}</ref> In 2019, it was organised in Lahore and Karachi by a women's collective called ''Hum Auratein'' (We the Women), and in other parts of the country, including Islamabad, Hyderabad, Quetta, Mardan, and Faislabad, by [[Women democratic front]] (WDF), Women Action Forum (WAF), and others.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/03/pakistani-women-hold-aurat-march-equality-gender-justice-190308115740534.html|title=Pakistani women hold 'aurat march' for equality, gender justice|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2019-03-16}}</ref>  The march was endorsed by the Lady Health Workers Association, and included representatives from multiple women's-rights organizations.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/magazine/instep-today/290411-aurat-march-2018-freedom-over-fear|title=Aurat March 2018: Freedom over fear|last=Saeed|first=Mehek|website=www.thenews.com.pk|language=en|access-date=2019-03-17}}</ref><ref name=\"dawn\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1470333|website=dawn.com|title=A rising movement|accessdate=2019-04-06|date=2019-03-18}}</ref> The march called for more accountability for violence against women, and to support for women who experience violence and harassment at the hands of security forces, in public spaces, at home, and at the workplace.<ref name=\":0\" /> Reports suggest that more and more women rushed to join the march until the crowd was became scattered. Women (as well as men) carried posters bearing phrases such as 'Ghar ka Kaam, Sab ka Kaam', and 'Women are humans, not honour' became a rallying cry.\n\nWomen dressed in T-shirts that read \u2018my favorite season is the fall (of [[patriarchy]])\u2019<ref name=\":117\">{{Cite web|last=Shahid|first= Atiqa|url=https://www.thewallet.com.pk/blog/a-march-for-rights-against-patriarchy/|title=A march for rights; against patriarchy|date=2020-03-08|website=The Wallet|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> and \u2018girls just want fun-damental human rights\u2019.  Some wore masks of dead social media celebrity [[Qandeel Baloch]] and one group held \u2018patriarchy\u2019s janaza\u2019 (funeral procession of patriarchy) on their shoulders. Participants were from all walks of life and included many eminent people. Social media and YouTube video messages expressed support for those who were marching. [[Nimra Afzal]] claimed in her article, that Aurat March is a women's empowerment movement which is not restricted to just peace rallies, raising awareness placards or sloganeering for women's equality in a patriarchal society. The movement is just not man-hating or elitist but a movement that asks for public spaces, with hashtags like #JaggaDein (Give space).<ref name=\":3\" />\n[[File:Aurat March 2019.jpg|thumb|Aurat March 2019]]\n[[File:Aurat March 2020.jpg|thumb|A mother with her young daughters in Aurat March 2020]]\n\n== Context ==\nAgainst backdrop of deep rooted socio-religio-political patriarchal structures of Pakistan's society and state, [[women in Pakistan]] face many types of social ills, systemic discrimination depriving fundamental rights amounting to sexual [[apartheid]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/574916/social-constructionism-and-women-empowerment-2/|title=Social constructionism and women empowerment|date=2020-03-12|website=Daily Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> including but not limited to forced & early childhood marriage, lack of enough formal public education opportunities, lack of freedom and lack of access to use two wheeler, lack of free & safe access to public spaces, domestic violence, sexual harassment & sexual violence at homes, at public  transport & at work places plus wage gap, over powering of their sexual freedom & right of choice and equality under religious garb and many serious crimes like appropriation of rights & abuse for revenge including but not limited to acid attacks, [[Honour killing in Pakistan|honor killings]]  without being addressed, regularly silenced by society, frequently overlooked by  state<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/opinion/letter-from-pakistan/for-pakistani-men-aurat-march-is-the-real-coronavirus/375862/|title=For Pakistani men, Aurat March is the real coronavirus|last=Inayat|first=Naila|date=2020-03-05|website=ThePrint|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref>; With guidance of [[Feminism in Pakistan|feminist movement]], new generation of women's collective started challenging status quo with help of social media in parallel to [[Me Too movement (Pakistan)|#MeToo movement]] in an effort to take equal rights movement to ordinary women they started organizing annual Aurat March on [[International Women's Day|international women's day]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Anjum|first=Gulnaz|date=2020-02-27|title=Women's Activism in Pakistan: Role of Religious Nationalism and Feminist Ideology Among Self-Identified Conservatives and Liberals|journal=Open Cultural Studies|volume=4|issue=1|pages=Pages 36\u201349|doi=10.1515/culture-2020-0004|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shaheed|first=Farida|title=Maintaining Momentum in Changing Circumstances|date=2019|journal=Journal of International Affairs|volume=72|issue=2|pages=159\u2013172|issn=0022-197X|jstor=26760840}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/574916/social-constructionism-and-women-empowerment-2/|title=Social constructionism and women empowerment|date=2020-03-12|website=Daily Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nIn an article published on 14 February 2016 in ''[[Forbes]]'', journalist Sonya Rehman wrote, \"while the world celebrates [[Valentine's Day in Pakistan|Valentine's Day]], a number of Pakistani women succumb to honor killings by their very own kin\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/sonyarehman/2016/02/14/filmmaker-takes-on-honor-killing-in-pakistan/|title=Filmmaker Takes On Honor Killing in Pakistan|last=Rehman|first=Sonya|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref> An [[honour killing]] is the [[homicide]] of a member of a family or social group by other members, due to the belief the victim has brought [[Honour|dishonour]] upon the family or community.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite book|last=Jafri|first=Amir H.|title=Honour killing: dilemma, ritual, understanding|date=2008|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780195476316|location=Oxford|oclc=180753749}}</ref> The death of the victim is viewed as a way to restore the reputation and honour of the family. Pakistan has world's highest prevalence of honor killings. Pakistan, where 60 percent of the population is below age 30 and half are under 18, are influenced more by global trends than traditions.<ref name=\":03\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-valentines-day-pakistan-idUSKBN1FS1XP|title=Love is in the air, but not on airwaves as Pakistan bans Valentine's Day|date=2018-02-08|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-01-25|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Hadid & Sattar\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/parallels/2018/02/14/585486507/in-pakistan-valentines-day-brings-out-roses-and-culture-wars|title=In Pakistan, Valentine's Day Brings Out Roses And Culture Wars|last=Hadid|first=Diaa|last2=Sattar|first2=Abdul|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>  [[Valentine's Day in Pakistan|Valentine's Day]] serves annually as a flash point of the [[culture war]] in Pakistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2016/02/26/love-and-politics-valentines-day-in-pakistan/|title=Love and Politics: Valentine's Day in Pakistan|last=Nazish|first=Kiran|website=Foreign Policy|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref> Diaa Hadid says that it is a [[cause c\u00e9l\u00e8bre]] for religious hard-liners, affording conservatives a chance assert themselves as the caretakers of Islamic identity.<ref name=\":42\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/parallels/2018/02/14/585486507/in-pakistan-valentines-day-brings-out-roses-and-culture-wars|title=In Pakistan, Valentine's Day Brings Out Roses And Culture Wars|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref>  While many Pakistanis celebrate the Valentine's Day's festivities, '''[[Pakistan]]''' has officially banned Valentine's Day, and the [[Islamism|Islamist]] orthodoxy<ref>{{Cite journal |jstor = 24479574|title = The Popularity of 'Valentine Day': A Sociological Perspective|last1 = Patel|first1 = Pravin J.|journal = Economic and Political Weekly|volume = 49|issue = 19|pages = 19\u201321|year = 2014}}</ref> has taken steps to obstruct celebrations,<ref name=\":04\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-valentines-day-pakistan-idUSKBN1FS1XP|title=Love is in the air, but not on airwaves as Pakistan bans Valentine's Day|date=2018-02-08|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-01-25|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1457860|title=All you need is love|date=2019-01-16|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref> Women's freedom is scorned by conservatives and extremist institutions in Pakistani society.<ref name=\":72\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1457860|title=All you need is love|date=2019-01-16|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref> The focus is not simply to restrict women's free expression on a particular day, but rather to subjugate women to strengthen male dominance through their seclusion from public life. The complex rules of ''[[purdah]]'' (seclusion) which reinforce chastity and family honor, have led to socio-cultural disparities, in every aspect of women's lives. Lacking an understanding of their civil, legal, and political rights, women's opportunities for participation in society are limited and they are left vulnerable to exploitation, oppression, and abusive control by others without adequate recourse.<ref name=\"Riffat\">{{Cite web|url=http://unsworks.unsw.edu.au/fapi/datastream/unsworks:45876/SOURCE01?view=true|title=Purdah of hearts and eyes, Examination of Purdah as an institution in Pakistan|last=Riffat|first=Haque|date=October 2003|website=[unsw.edu.au the University of New South Wales,Australia]|pages=219\u2013223|url-status=live|access-date=27 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1526245|title=FEAR AND THE CITY|last=Khatri|first=Sadia|date=2020-01-05|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref> Technically, love is not ''[[haram]]'' (forbidden) in Islam, but gender segregation and gender mixing prohibitions stifle the freedom of Muslim women.<ref name=\":43\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/parallels/2018/02/14/585486507/in-pakistan-valentines-day-brings-out-roses-and-culture-wars|title=In Pakistan, Valentine's Day Brings Out Roses And Culture Wars|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref> Access to public spaces for women is severely constrained<ref name=\":92\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1526245|title=FEAR AND THE CITY|last=Khatri|first=Sadia|date=2020-01-05|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref> and conservative, rigid interpretations of Islam create limits on women's behavior. In the conservative view, women are not allowed to show their faces, not allowed to talk to unrelated men unless the communication is essential, and are unable to choose their own life partner, as that is a decision made by the head of the family.<ref name=\":52\">{{Cite book|last=Yasmeen|first=Samina|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=Y5RODwAAQBAJ&lpg=PA156&dq=Valentine's%20Day%20in%20Pakistan&pg=PA157#v=onepage&q=Valentine's%20Day%20in%20Pakistan&f=true|title=Jihad and Dawah: Evolving Narratives of Lashkar-e-Taiba and Jamat ud Dawah|date=2017-10-01|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-1-84904-974-0|pages=156\u2013158|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Human Rights Commission of Pakistan]] lists 460 cases of reported honour killings in 2017, with 194 males and 376 females as victims. Of these killings, 253 were sparked by disapproval of illicit relations and 73 by disapproval of marriage choice. Additionally, out of the known suspect relationship with victims, over 93% were family relationships.<ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=http://hrcpmonitor.org/search/?id=5|title=HRCP Archive {{!}} Search News|website=hrcpmonitor.org|language=en|access-date=2018-05-02}}</ref> Although these are most likely only a sample of the actual honour killings that were completed during 2017, it still gives a glimpse into characteristics of honour killings in Pakistan. Sources disagree as to the exact number by year, but according to [[Human Rights Watch]], NGOs/INGOs in the area estimate that around 1000 honour killings are carried out each year in Pakistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/08/23/pakistan-should-not-again-fail-honor-killing-victim|title=Pakistan Should Not Again Fail 'Honor Killing' Victim|last=Ijaz|first=Saroop|date=22 August 2019|website=Human Rights Watch|location=New York, New York|access-date=February 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWith such horrific background of fundamental human right violations of women of Pakistan, millennial young adults started  demanding access to public spaces with movements like [[Girls at Dhabas]] which gained significant traction from women across South Asia since 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tns.thenews.com.pk/girls-at-dhabas-much-needed-campaign/|title=Girls at Dhabas: A much-needed campaign|last1=Editor|first1=T. N. S.|date=13 September 2015|website=TNS - The News on Sunday}}</ref> and so also new generation of feminist thought started breaking the silence around issues like sexual autonomy and agency  as soon as they did get opportunity to express through some of placards of Aurat March, says Zoya Rehman.<ref name=\":8\" /> That is how the March which was primarily intended for gender equity in multiple range of issues also came to explore construction of narratives relating to socio religio political exploitation of women sexuality in Pakistan and challenge posed to sexual injustices through Aurat March by new generation feminist  became part of Pakistan's national debate.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n== Manifesto ==\nManifesto demands economic justice, including implementation of labour rights, the Sexual Harassment Against Women in the Workplace Act 2010, recognition of women's input to the \u2018care economy\u2019 as unpaid labour, and provision of maternity leaves and day care centres to ensure women's inclusion in the labour force. Among other things, it also demands access to safe drinking water and air, protection of animals and wildlife, recognition of women's participation in production of food and cash crops, access to a fair justice system, inclusion of women with disabilities as well as the transgender community, reproductive justice, access to public spaces inclusion in educational institutions, rights of religious minorities, promotion of an anti-war agenda, end to police brutality and enforced disappearances.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Themes ==\nAccording to Zuneera Shah, while etymology of word 'Aurat' (Woman) indicates being misogynistic Since Western supremacy over feminist movements feeds into a distaste towards feminism in countries such as Pakistan. Localization of the struggle for women's rights has importance among South Asian activists and feminists the way to relate the feminist movement.<ref name=\":5\" /> Shah says With the Aurat March, terms such as 'pidar shahi' (patriarchy) and 'aurat march' are being circulated and created.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nTheme for 2018 march was 'Equality\u2019 whereas theme for 2019 march is 'Sisterhood and Solidarity'.<ref name=\":0\" /> Nighat Dad explains in her article that \"The agenda of this march was to demand resources and dignity for women, for transgender community, for religious minorities and for those on the economic margins but more importantly to acknowledge that women\u2019s emancipation is inherently linked with the improvement of all mistreated groups and minorities.As per Leena Ghani theme for 2020 Aurat March is Khudmukhtari (autonomy) and violence, both sexual and economic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2020/03/pakistani-women-are-ready-for-another-aurat-march-is-pakistan/|title=Pakistani Women Are Ready for Another Aurat March. Is Pakistan?|website=thediplomat.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n\n== Women's March 2019 ==\n\n[[File:Mera Jism Meri Marzi (My Body, My Choice).jpg|thumb|Mera Jism Meri Marzi ([[My body, my choice|My Body, My Choice]])]]\n[[File:Placards displayed by Marchers during Aurat March 2019.jpg|thumb|Placards displayed by Marchers during Aurat March 2019]]\n[[File:Women displaying placards during Aurat March 2019.jpg|thumb|Women displaying placards during Aurat March 2019]]\n[[File:Marchers holding placards during Aurat March 2020.jpg|thumb|Marchers holding placards during Aurat March 2020]]\n[[File:Farhan Wilayat (Philanthropist and Social Activist) during Aurat March 2020.jpg|thumb|Farhan Wilayat ([[Philanthropist]] and [[Social Activist]]) during Aurat March 2020 outside [[Lahore Press Club]]]]\n[[File:Aurat March 2020 e.jpg|thumb|Zahra Khan Farooqi, a blogger, stood for the women who weren't allowed to join the march.]]\n[[File:Aurat March 2020 d.jpg|thumb|Nisha Khawaja, a marcher, bringing attention to the harassment cases at work and elsewhere]]\n\n===Posters Slogans and Media Debates===\nThe hundreds of posters featured at women's day march across Pakistan highlighted [[fundamental rights]] issues such as access to education and employment.<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Mera Jism Meri Marzi]] (My body, my choice) became a main and most talked slogan of Aurat March with a lot of debates, discussions in country over the years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thefeministani.com/2019/11/29/mera-jism-meri-marzi/|title=Mera jism meri marzi|last=Shah|first=Bina|date=29 November 2019|website=The Feministani|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref> This led to slogans like 'Why are you afraid of my self determination', 'A womxn's right to autonomy on her own body'''<nowiki/>'''', 'In fact, everyone should get to decide what happens to their body, for themselves'<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mangobaaz.com/38-of-the-most-powerful-aurat-march-2020-posters-that-you-absolutely-have-to-see|title=38 Of The Most Powerful Aurat March 2020 Posters That You Absolutely Have To See|last=Noor|date=2020-03-09|website=MangoBaaz|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> Some of March 2018 posters included slogans like \"[[Women's rights|Our rights]] are not for grab neither are we\", \"Girls just wanna have Fundamental human rights\", [[Trans woman|'Transwomen]] are women shut up', \"Tu kare tou Stud, Mai Karun tou [[Slut-shaming|Slut]] (If you do it then Stud but If I do it then Slut)\", \"Safe street program for women\", \"Stop being [[Menstrual cycle|Menstrual]] phobic\", \"[[Consent]] ki [[Tasbih|Tasbeeh]] Rozana Parhen (Ask for consent every time)\", \"[[Paratha]] Rolls Not [[Gender role|Gender Roles]].\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Staff |first1=Images |title=These posters from the Aurat March say everything you wish you could |url=https://images.dawn.com/news/1179620 |work=Images |date=9 March 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Javaid, Maham |first1=T. N. S. |title=Paratha rolls, not gender roles |url=http://tns.thenews.com.pk/paratha-rolls-gender-roles/#.XaQFd3RrzIU |work=TNS - The News on Sunday |date=11 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, some posters also appeared saying \"Man of quality will never be afraid of equality, \"Jab tak aurat tang rahay gi, jang rahay gi, jang rahay gi\",<ref>{{cite news |last1= Javaid, Maham |first1=T. N. S. |title=Paratha rolls, not gender roles |url=http://tns.thenews.com.pk/paratha-rolls-gender-roles/#.XaRNF3RrzIV |work=TNS - The News on Sunday |date=11 March 2018}}</ref> and \"Keep your dick pics to yourself\". Another had a drawing of a [[vagina]] and two [[Ovary|ovaries]] and the words: \"Grow a pair!\" Another poster said, \"If you like the headscarf so much, tie it around your eyes\", one depicting a girl sitting with her legs spread out, ''Lo Beth Gayi Sahi Se'' or the irreverent ''Akeli Awara Azaad'' \"Nazar teri gandi aur purdah mein keroun\" (Why do I adopt veil cause of your bad habit of ogling) \"Aaj waqai maa behn ek ho rahi hai\"<ref>{{cite news |title='Maa Behen Ek Ho Rahi Hy' And Other Aurat March Signs, Explained |url=https://auratnow.com/2019/03/09/aurat-march-2019-international-womens-day-placards-slogans-signs/ |work=Aurat Now |date=9 March 2019}}</ref> depicts all women coming together without differences. One poster read that maybe we haven't seen any woman as independent as a '[[Tawaif|tawaaif]]', so this is the reason we (some of our society) consider every independent woman a 'tawaaif', another \"My shirt is not short, it's your mindset that is narrow\", and posters like \"these are my streets too\" claimed public spaces.\n\nAilia Zehra deconstructs a poster in her article that says \"If Cynthia does it, she\u2019s applauded. If I do it, I\u2019m the villain\". For those who do not know, Cynthia Ritchie is an American social media influencer facilitated by Pakistan establishment's [[Whitewashing (censorship)|whitewash]] for state propaganda. This woman rode a bicycle somewhere in Pakistan and tweeted her picture in a bid to bring down local feminists by implying that they lie when they say women cannot freely access public spaces. This placard admirably summarizes what is wrong with an American woman lecturing Pakistani women on freedom and mobility. Ailia Zehra regrets double standards saying Yes, Pakistani men are fine with women riding bicycles on the roads \u2013 as long as the women are white.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zehra |first1=Ailia |title=How Aurat March Challenged The Deeply Ingrained Toxic Masculinity |url=https://nayadaur.tv/2019/03/how-aurat-march-challenged-the-deeply-ingrained-toxic-masculinity/ |work=Naya Daur |date=9 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Nighat Dad]] who organized the women's march in [[Lahore]], said people were angry over the posters because most Pakistanis, especially men were not yet ready to allow them [[Freedom of choice|free choice]]. As per Nighat Dad, restricted topics like women's rights to their own bodies, their sexuality, are being discussed for the first time was an immense success of the march. Dad complained, \"Online harassments has gone too far in terms of death and rape threats to the organizers and also to the marchers.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Aurat March organisers receive online death threats |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1470144 |work=DAWN.COM |date=17 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Pakistan's Women Marched for Their Rights. Then the Backlash Came. |url=https://thediplomat.com/2019/03/pakistans-women-marched-for-their-rights-then-the-backlash-came/ |work=thediplomat.com}}</ref>\n\nMany grumbled that the marchers were \"[[Vulgarity|vulgar]]\" opportunists who had transgressed on conservative values in the Muslim-majority country and \"undermined\" a legitimate fight for rights with a [[Liberalism|liberal]], anti-Islamic agenda.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> Feminist writer [[Sadia Khatri]] exposes this built up of narrative in her article, \"Should feminists claim Aurat March's Vulgar Posters? Ye s absolutely.\" Khatri says people have been posting photographs showing the posters that didn't get as much air-time, posters addressing the range of 'important' causes that news anchors have accused the March of ignoring, like education, inheritance and marital rights. By bringing up the manifesto to defend the posters, for instance, Pakistan Feminists isolated themselves from the supposedly provocative posters, and in fact confirm their 'vulgarity'. It implies that Pakistani feminists agree that feminism should operate within the bounds of 'respectability'. According to her accepting narratives prescribing boundaries of respectability are traps that needs to be avoided by feminists and not to be allowed to be cemented in any social discourse. Feminism with conditions is no feminism. It maintains the division between what is \u2018acceptable\u2019 and what is 'immodest', what is 'public' and 'private', allowed and not. It pits the two against each other, rewarding the feminists who rally for legal rights and work-life balance and slut-shaming those who reclaim gendered slurs and carry the posters they did at the March. She questions whether feminism to allow discriminate and gatekeeping, and this gatekeeping is patriarchy's way of bolstering the binary of purpose vs pleasure, where the feminism of purpose (health, education, marital rights) is 'good' feminism, and the feminism of pleasure (sexual politics, bodily autonomy, agency over time and leisure) is 'bad' feminism, 'immoral' and 'frivolous'. She explains as feminists use the language of real and serious, end up creating a distinction between 'actual' issues and 'pretended' ones and rush to clarify that feminists have included 'important' causes in our demands, end up suggesting that other causes are unimportant.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Khatri |first1=Sadia |title=Should feminists claim Aurat March\u2019s 'vulgar' posters? Yes, absolutely |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1469815 |work=DAWN.COM |date=15 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn an article \"Womansplaining the Aurat March: Dear men, here\u2019s why Pakistan\u2019s women are asserting their rights\" writer Rimmel Mohydin handles misogynist objections to the Women's march slogans in a different way.<ref name=\"womansxplain\">{{cite news |last1=Mohydin |first1=Rimmel |title=Let me womansplain the Aurat March to you |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1469183 |work=DAWN.COM |date=12 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Rimmel Mohydin suggests those men to \"smile, you'll look prettier that way.\" Ms. Mohydin humorously questions Women can be the subject of many sexist jokes, but if the women crack a joke on what ground that wit is considered offensive?<ref name=\"womansxplain\" /> She says Every wisecrack, every sassy one-liner, every appealing slogan masked years and years of invisible pain that women have suffered.<ref name=\"womansxplain\" /> A Woman can tell men through their placards that she won't warm his bed if he doesn't warm his food, but what really gets misogynist mind hot and troubled is that she, a woman, could laugh at his expense.<ref name=\"womansxplain\" />\n\nOn an effort of misogynist parliamentarian's effort or agenda finding conspiracy theory behind women's march Ms. Mohydin sarcastically quips, \"It is difficult to know where to place your feet when you find that the backs that you have been walking on are now standing up. That's why the author's compassion is with misogynist politicians\". Referring poster slogan \"Keep your dick pics to yourself.\" Ms. Mohydin says What seems to have affronted the male collective the most is the shattering of a fantasy world where women enjoy being subjected to unrequested pictures of male genitals. Poster slogan has hit them hard. It has upset them. And now, they are angry and trying to speak to us in a language that they think we'll understand. They tell us this is not feminism but fail to explain how. They tell us it's about sex, and as 'respectful' women, how dare we utter of it.<ref name=\"womansxplain\" /> \"When women make demands about their personal lives, their bodies, their sexuality, that's when people feel threatened,\" Dad said. \u201cSo it\u2019s OK to ask the government for the right to education but you can't say you are happily divorced because the breakdown of a matrimony is a shameful thing, a woman\u2019s failure, and you can\u2019t say 'don't send me dick pics' because so-called decent women don't use expressions like dick.\u201d Nobody seems to say anything to the sender, but the reluctant receiver is apparently the problem. Either she likes it (which, to them, makes her a 'slut') or she doesn't (which offends them). So as usual, women cannot win Ms. Mohydin says. Remaining on the same issue Ms. Mohydin strongly questions \"Are they unsettled at the loss of this opportunity to titillate women with their phallus? Why are they all shriveling up? Have protesting women given them performance anxiety or what.<ref name=\"womansxplain\" />\n\nContinuing her strong denunciation Ms. Mohydin says, \"The placards were a mirror and instead of taking this moment as an opportunity to introspect, they have decided to beat their chest instead. Not their slain bodies, not their acid-burnt faces, not their immobility, not their lack of representation, not the dearth of affordable housing, not the moral policing their choices and bodies are subjected to, not the denial of female education, not the constant threat of sexual harassment and onslaught, not the social structures that cut women\u2019s potential in half, not the exploitation, not the objectification, not the fact that for many, women are still not human. It seems to me that for them, the problem is women themselves, Ms. Mohydin rues.<ref name=\"womansxplain\" />\n\n[[Shaan Shahid]], arguably Pakistan\u2019s well-known film star, wrote on [[Twitter]] he thought the posters did not \"represent our culture, our values\". He was criticized in return for his films that blatantly sexualize women and reduce their existence to a mere prop to exert the \u2018masculinity\u2019 of his character. He defends his position as freedom of expression, but when women call out this misogynistic culture with his hypocrisy he looks down freedom of expression by women.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pakistani women lash out at Shaan over his criticism on Aurat March |url=https://www.natcour.com/news/2019/03/pakistani-women-lash-out-at-shaan-over-his/ |work=National Courier |date=12 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nVeena Malik, a popular actor who caused an uproar in 2012 when she appeared with scantily dressed on the cover of an Indian men's magazine, posted that the march had \"brought humiliation to women of Pakistan\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Veena Malik Gets Called Out After Saying that Aurat March Was 'Humiliating for Women' |url=https://propakistani.pk/lens/veena-malik-gets-called-out-after-saying-that-aurat-march-was-humiliating-for-women/ |work=Lens |date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Twitter users were prompt to remind Veena that \"the same women you are calling out for 'humiliating' Pakistani femininities were standing by you as mullahs imposed fatwas on you.\"\n\n[[Kishwar Naheed]], a poet best cherished for a poem called \"Us sinful women\", was seen in a video saying: \"The next time you make such slogans, remember your culture, your traditions.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Kishwar Naheed rejects certain slogans of Aurat March, receives backlash |url=https://en.dailypakistan.com.pk/lifestyle/kishwar-naheed-rejects-certain-slogans-of-aurat-march-receives-backlash/ |work=Daily Pakistan Global}}</ref> Sadia Khatri a feminist writer, replies back through her column in Dawn saying someone should remind  Naheed, that it is specifically culture and tradition; that keeps the frivolous and the silly relegating women to private spaces where women court the greatest risks, where the threat of assault is most prevalent, and where, when women are harmed, the walls around womanhood remind women to stay silent, like \u2018good\u2019, \u2018honourable\u2019 women those culture and tradition are what upturned when thousands of women come out into the streets, dancing and laughing with exhilaration.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Khatri |first1=Sadia |title=Should feminists claim Aurat March\u2019s 'vulgar' posters? Yes, absolutely |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1469815 |work=DAWN.COM |date=15 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Guardian journalist Mehreen Zahra-Malik, some of the profanity-filled tirades were frightening. A film student posted screenshots of a group of boys [[Sexual harassment|sexually harassing]] her 16-year-old younger sister online and threatening her with [[rape]] for posting on [[Instagram]] in support of the march.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zahra-Malik |first1=Mehreen |title=Pakistan torn as women\u2019s day march sparks wave of 'masculine anxiety' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/mar/15/pakistan-torn-as-womens-day-march-sparks-wave-of-masculine-anxiety |work=The Guardian |date=15 March 2019}}</ref> Pakistan is a conservative society, activists sporting simple posters like \"You can\u2019t say you are happily divorced' also received messages filled with sexual innuendo and threats of sexual violence. Women participating in Aurat March had received threats of physical and sexual violence from social media users after posting photographs of the posters. In Pakistan, the threats of violence are not hollow. According to the [[Human Rights Commission of Pakistan]], roughly 500 women are killed each year by family members who believe their honour has been damaged.\n\nOn 20 March 2019, [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]] Assembly held a protest in the reaction of the Aurat March. Rehana Ismail of the Muttahida Majlis-i-Amal (MMA), presented the resolution, saying that women participating in the march were holding \"obscene\" placards and raising slogans. The resolution said that the demands made at the march about women empowerment were \"un-Islamic and shameful\".<ref>{{cite news |title=KP Assembly demands action against \u2018shameless slogans\u2019 at Aurat March, passes resolution |url=https://en.dailypakistan.com.pk/lifestyle/kp-assembly-demands-action-against-shameless-slogans-at-aurat-march-passes-resolution/ |work=Daily Pakistan Global}}</ref>\n\nOne popular poster called for men to warm their own food; another asked them to find their own socks. And one read, \"I'll warm your food but you warm your own bed.\" As per [[Nida Kirmani]], a feminist sociologist at the [[Lahore University of Management Sciences]] such posters got the most vitriolic responses because those challenged the intimate relations of power within the household. In a nytimes article Mohammed Hanif says the men in Pakistan who profess to guard women, in real sense only guard for their own selfish interests. Hanif says They don't want to look for their own socks, and they don't want to control that manly urge to take selfies of their private parts and send them to random women.Hanif questions how it is okay asking young woman to stop to holding up a placard and how it can be seen as a threat to the national moral order?<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hanif|first=Mohammed|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/07/opinion/international-womens-day-pakistan.html|title=Opinion {{!}} \u2018How Do I Know Where Your Socks Are?\u2019|date=2020-03-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-08|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> As per Sabahat Zakariya, a newspaper editor these kinds of slogans have unleashed a wave of [[Misogyny|masculine anxiety]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zahra-Malik |first1=Mehreen |title=Pakistan torn as women\u2019s day march sparks wave of \u2018masculine anxiety\u2019 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/mar/15/pakistan-torn-as-womens-day-march-sparks-wave-of-masculine-anxiety |work=The Guardian |date=15 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Social media hashtag ==\nOne of the hashtag at 2018 rally was #KhaanaKhudGaramKarLo (heat your own meal). Whereas in 2019 it transformed to 'Ghar ka Kam, Sab ka Kam' (House work is everyone's responsibility) slogan'\n\n2019 March '#WhyIMarch' became the social media hashtag and slogan for the event,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thequint.com/neon/social-buzz/art-and-beyond-why-aurat-march-2020-pakistan-will-not-be-silence|title=Art & Beyond: Why Pakistan\u2019s #AuratMarch Will Not Be Silenced|date=2020-03-02|website=The Quint|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> with many celebrities, human rights activists, and locals sharing their stories of why they marched #HumAurtein #auratmarch #AuratMarch2019 #JaggaDein.\n\nAhead of Aurat March 2020 hashtags like #AuratMarch2020 and #MeraJismMeriMarzi are run on various platforms.\n\n==Women's March 2020==\n\nAurat march was held in Karachi, Hyderabad, Lahore and Quetta whereas Aurat Azadi March was held in Islamabad, Sukkur and Multan.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hasnain |first1=Alefyah |title=Aurat March 2020 Pakistan: Here's How This Year's March Stood Out From Last Year's! |url=https://www.brandsynario.com/aurat-march-2020-vs-2019/ |work=Brandsynario |date=9 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=\u2018Aurat March\u2019 held in Quetta |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2172005/1-aurat-march-held-quetta/ |work=The Express Tribune |date=9 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title='Aurat March' 2020 being held across nationwide to mark International Women's Day |url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/572275/aurat-march-2020-being-held-across-nationwide-to-mark-international-womens-day/ |work=Daily Times |date=8 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Aurat March 2020: Nationwide demonstrations held to celebrate womanhood, demand equality |url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/276214-aurat-march-being-held-nationwide |work=www.geo.tv}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The aesthetics of Aurat March 2020 |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2172813/4-aesthetics-aurat-march-2020/ |newspaper=The Express Tribune |date=March 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title='Aurat March' to include laborers, farmers, fringe communities, say organizers |url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1638161/pakistan |work=Arab News |date=7 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Aurat March: Thousands hit streets for gender equality |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2171752/1-aurat-march-held-across-pakistan-mark-international-womens-day/ |work=The Express Tribune |date=8 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Pakistan marks Women\u2019s Day with \u2018Aurat March\u2019 |url=https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/pakistan/pakistan-marks-womens-day-with-aurat-march-1.70236576 |work=gulfnews.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title='Aurat March' held nationwide to mark International Women's Day |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1539318 |work=DAWN.COM |date=8 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n \n=== Aurat March Lahore===\nArtist Shehzil Malik started collecting poster design submissions for Aurat March of 8 March 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2145791/4-artist-shehzil-malik-calls-aurat-march-poster-design-submissions/|title=Artist Shehzil Malik calls for Aurat March poster design submissions|last=Tribune|first=The Express|date=28 January 2020|work=The Express Tribune Pakistan|access-date=4 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  Participants of the March created a Mural of posters submitted by Volunteers in Hussain Chowk of Lahore which was ransacked within hours in a [[hate crime]] attack.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://images.dawn.com/news/1184719|title=Women peacefully put up Aurat March posters, men violently tore them down|last=Staff|first=Images|date=2020-02-24|website=Images|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.samaa.tv/news/pakistan/2020/02/aurat-march-2020-mural-vandalised-in-lahore/|title=Aurat March 2020 mural vandalised in Lahore {{!}} SAMAA|website=Samaa TV|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oyeyeah.com/events/aurat-march-posters-vandalized-by-angry-mob/|title=Aurat March Posters Vandalized by Angry Mob|last=Arshad|first=Aisha|date=2020-02-25|website=Oyeyeah|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref> Janita Tahir says participants in the March are being threatened by orthodox men and need to be taken seriously before any untoward incidence could take place and government need to do needful for protection of participating women.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mangobaaz.com/ghairat-ke-thaykedaar-are-issuing-threats-to-aurat-march-no-ones-stopping-them|title=Ghairat Ke Thaykedaar Are Issuing Threats To Aurat March & No One's Stopping Them|last=Tahir|first=Janita|date=2020-02-26|website=MangoBaaz|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/620253-threats-to-sukkur-organisers-of-aurat-march-condemned|title=Threats to Sukkur organisers of Aurat March condemned|website=www.thenews.com.pk|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Men also present in support of the Aurat March 2020.jpg|thumb|Men also joined Aurat March 2020 outside [[Lahore Press Club]] to support women's rights]]\nA petition was filed in the Lahore High Court by the Judicial Activism Council Chairman to stop Aurat March 2020, calling it \"against the very norms of Islam\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Bilal|first=Rana|url=http://www.dawn.com|title=LHC to hear arguments on petition against holding of Aurat March|date=February 24, 2020|work=Dawn|access-date=February 28, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  This petition was rejected by the Lahore High Court Chief Justice who underscored that freedom of expression could not be banned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/274596-aurat-march-in-lhc-chief-justice-says-cannot-ban-freedom-of-expression|title=Aurat March 2020: LHC Chief Justice says cannot ban freedom of expression|last=Riaz|first=Shakir|date=Feb 27, 2020|website=Geo TV|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=Feb 28, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":6\" />\n\nIn Lahore, marchers gathered outside the Press Club and passed through Egerton Road to culminate outside Aiwan-e-Iqbal. Participants were holding a plethora of placards. Despite the social media storm before the march, men were present in large numbers in support of the Aurat March. The participants delivered speeches and held placards and banners displaying thought-provoking slogans to raise the pressing issues of gender-based violence including sexual harassment and assault in the workplace, deep-rooted misogyny and the patriarchal mindset prevalent in the society. A resolution was submitted in Punjab Assembly by Kanwal Liaquat (MPA-PMLN), demanding an end to gender discrimination. The resolution condemned under-age marriages and demanded that women be granted legal, social and economic protection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2020/03/08/aurat-march-women-reclaim-public-spaces-on-their-day/|title=Aurat March: Women reclaim public spaces on their day|date=2019-03-09|website=Pakistan Today|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref>\n\n===Aurat Azadi March Islamabad===\nA petition was also filed in the Islamabad High Court to stop Aurat Azadi March 2020 which was rejected by Chief justice [[Athar Minallah]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Referring to religion, culture, Islamabad High Court tells us why Aurat March is necessary |url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/276002-referring-to-religion-culture-islamabad-high-court-tells-us-why-aurat-march-is-necessary |work=www.geo.tv}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ali |first1=Arshad |title=IHC reserves verdict on petition seeking stoppage of Aurat March |url=https://khybernews.tv/ihc-reserves-verdict-on-petition-seeking-stoppage-of-aurat-march/ |work=Khyber News -Official Website |date=6 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Islamabad High Court dismisses petition to stop Aurat March {{!}} SAMAA |url=https://www.samaa.tv/news/pakistan/2020/03/aurat-march-only-asks-for-rights-guaranteed-in-islam-court/ |work=Samaa TV}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Asad |first1=Malik |title=IHC rejects petitions seeking restrictions on Aurat March |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1538963 |work=DAWN.COM |date=7 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=IHC throws out petition seeking to stop Aurat March |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1538855 |work=DAWN.COM |date=6 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> On March 3, extremist mob vandalised, mural of two women painted by organizers of Aurat Azadi March Islamabad.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mahmood |first1=Aisha |title=Extremist mob vandalises mural of two women painted by Aurat March organizers |url=https://www.brecorder.com/2020/03/04/576922/lal-masjid-clerics-vandalise-mural-of-two-women-painted-by-aurat-march-organizers/ |work=Business Recorder |date=4 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Sirur |first1=Simrin |title=Pakistan prepares for Aurat Azadi March but Lal Masjid clerics call it obscene |url=https://theprint.in/go-to-pakistan/pakistan-prepares-for-aurat-azadi-march-but-lal-masjid-clerics-call-it-obscene/376073/ |work=ThePrint |date=5 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ali |first1=Kalbe |title=Jamia Hafsa students claim responsibility for defacing feminist mural in Islamabad |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1538478 |work=DAWN.COM |date=5 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Staff |first1=Images |title=Aurat March\u2019s beautiful mural was vandalised in Islamabad. Are men really that afraid? |url=https://images.dawn.com/news/1184784 |work=Images |date=5 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The organizers of march were given the no-objection certificate (NOC) after many days of negotiations and a range of unnecessarily strict conditions were applied in NOC.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Daur |first1=Naya |title=Aurat March Islamabad's NOC Comes With Strict Conditions |url=https://nayadaur.tv/2020/03/aurat-march-islamabads-noc-comes-with-strict-conditions/ |work=Naya Daur |date=7 March 2020}}</ref> On March 8, 2020, the Aurat March procession in Pakistan's capital Islamabad was attacked by religious extremists who were holding a counter-march to celebrate ''Haya'' or modesty. It was attended by women from the Jamaat-e-Islami, JUI-F, Lal Masjid, and female students of different seminaries including Jamiat Hafsa, staged as Haya March. Bricks, stones, shoes and sticks were hurled at the peaceful marchers on the Aurat March side, leaving several people injured.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.capradio.org/news/npr/story?storyid=813443312|title=International Women's Day: With Shoes And Stones, Islamists Disrupt Pakistan Rally|last=Javed|first=Diaa Hadid,Hina|website=www.capradio.org|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wkms.org/post/international-womens-day-rallies-see-some-violence|title=International Women&#039;s Day Rallies See Some Violence|website=www.wkms.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Staff |first1=Scroll |title=Watch: Protestors throw stones, sticks at the participants of Pakistan\u2019s 2020 \u2018Aurat March\u2019 |url=https://scroll.in/video/955596/watch-protestors-throw-stones-sticks-at-the-participants-of-pakistans-2020-aurat-march |work=Scroll.in}}</ref> Earlier even before the March, a van carrying newly-printed banners of Aurat March was stopped and driver beaten.<ref name=\":13\" /> During the March The BBC correspondent Irfana Yasser and her children were assaulted with chilli powder which temporarily blinded them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1539954|title=Aurat March organisers demand judicial probe into Islamabad stone pelting incident|last=Yasin|first=Aamir|date=2020-03-11|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> At least one media camera person hospitalized.<ref name=\":13\" /> Subsequently, the attack was stopped by the police authorities that were present, and the March continued forward despite the opposition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2020/03/08/religious-party-attacks-aurat-march-in-capital-several-injured/|title=Aurat March attacked with bricks, sticks in Islamabad| website=www.pakistantoday.com.pk|language=en|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweekpakistan.com/readying-for-the-aftermath/|title=Readying for the Aftermath|date=2020-03-11|website=Newsweek Pakistan|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> An FIR was registered against the men who attacked the march participants.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u0639\u0648\u0631\u062a \u0645\u0627\u0631\u0686: \u0627\u06cc\u0641 \u0622\u0626\u06cc \u0622\u0631 \u062f\u0631\u062c\u060c \u067e\u062a\u06be\u0631\u0627\u0624 \u06a9\u0627 \u0630\u06a9\u0631 \u0646\u06c1\u06cc\u06ba |url=https://www.bbc.com/urdu/pakistan-51797397 |work=BBC News \u0627\u0631\u062f\u0648 |date=9 March 2020 |language=ur}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Case registered against men who attacked Islamabad Aurat March {{!}} SAMAA |url=https://www.samaa.tv/news/pakistan/2020/03/case-registered-against-men-who-attacked-islamabad-aurat-march/ |work=Samaa TV}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Reporter |first1=The Newspaper's Staff |title=35 booked for trying to disrupt Aurat Azadi March |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1539738 |work=DAWN.COM |date=10 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Aurat Azadi March Quetta ===\n2020 Aurat Azadi March in Quetta  Balochistan began from and returned to the Quetta press club, was organized  by the Women's Alliance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2020/03/08/aurat-march-women-reclaim-public-spaces-on-their-day/|title=Aurat March: Women reclaim public spaces on their day - Pakistan Today|website=www.pakistantoday.com.pk|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2172005/1-aurat-march-held-quetta/|title=\u2018Aurat March\u2019 held in Quetta|last=Tribune.com.pk|date=2020-03-09|website=The Express Tribune|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>Along with rest of social discrimination issues, end of previous year i.e. 2019 was noted with exposing of security establishment and University administration officials of  Balochistan University had secretly installed cameras in washrooms and student meeting areas and blackmailing students for years together.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesofbalochistan.com/baloch-women-and-aurat-march/|title=Baloch Women and Aurat March|date=2020-03-05|website=Times Of Balochistan|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1513829|title=Balochistan University scandal: Students demand removal of FC posts, restoration of union|last=Nihad|first=Ghalib|date=2019-10-30|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2019/11/19/balochistan-university-scandal-underlines-marginalisation-of-the-province/|title=Balochistan University scandal underlines marginalisation of province - Pakistan Today|website=www.pakistantoday.com.pk|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n===Women's Day Songs===\n\n[[File:Aurat March 2020 a.jpg|thumb|Women dance to Laal Meri at the Aurat March, Karachi]]\n\nAs preparation of upcoming 8 March 2020 Aurat March, released and subsequently performed<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/576223/when-you-have-to-stone-us-into-submission/|title=When you have to stone us into submission|date=2020-03-14|website=Daily Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> at the march a song 'tum ho rapist' an Urdu version of the feminist anthem 'Un Violador en Tu Camino' \u2014 or '[[A Rapist in Your Path]]'. While 'A Rapist in Your Path' is based on Argentinian [[Anthropology|anthropologist]] Rita Laura Segato's work and created by Valparaiso feminist collective, Las Tesis, [[Chile]]; Urdu version has been localized with  relevant issues of Pakistan by mentioning [[Feudalism in Pakistan|feudalism]] as part of the Pakistani [[patriarchy]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/270338-aurat-march-drops-urdu-version-of-anti-rape-anthem-ahead-of-2020-rally|title=Aurat March drops Urdu version of anti-rape anthem ahead of 2020 rally|website=www.geo.tv|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/608036-aurat-march-releases-urdu-version-of-chilean-protest-song|title=Aurat March releases Urdu version of Chilean protest song|website=www.thenews.com.pk|language=en|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref> Aurat March  also released & sung one more anthem song \"Hum Inquilab Hain\" (We are Revolution)<ref name=\":13\" /> Song \"Hum Inquilab Hain\" is written by  [[Ismat Shahjahan]], composed by [[Ammar Rashid]] song is sung in chorus by &nbsp; Areej Hussain, [[Ammar Rashid]], Huda Bhurgri, [[Ismat Shahjahan]], Ayesha Khan, and Shahzadi Hussain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dnd.com.pk/international-womens-day-hum-inquilab-hain-we-are-revolution/183551|title=International Women's Day: HUM INQUILAB HAIN--- We are Revolution|last=Desk|first=Central News|date=2020-03-07|website=Dispatch News Desk|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> A Canadian-Pakistani singer Sophia Jamil (pseudonym:Fifi) too released her song 'Mera Jism Meri Marzi' (My body My Choice) on YouTube.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/282583-young-singer-talks-womens-rights-in-new-song-mera-jism-meri-marzi|title=Young singer talks women's rights in new song 'Mera Jism Meri Marzi'|website=www.geo.tv|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bolnews.com/entertainment/2020/03/artist-highlights-womens-issues-by-her-song-mera-jism-meri-marzi/|title=Artist highlights women's issues by her song Mera Jism Meri Marzi|date=2020-03-13|website=BOL News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2176711/4-female-rapper-releases-song-mera-jism-meri-marzi-clarify-really-means/|title=Female rapper releases song 'Mera Jism Meri Marzi' to clarify what it really means|last=Tribune.com.pk|date=2020-03-15|website=The Express Tribune|language=en|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\n===Propaganda against women march===\n[[File:Aurat March 2020 b.jpg|thumb| Meri Zindagi Mera Haq, Meri Zindagi Mera Ikhtiyar (My life is my right and I should have the power to make decisions about my life)]]\n\nAs International Women's Day came nearer the hard line conservatives in Pakistan increasingly got impatient and intolerant, and took to mainstream media and online social media alleging Pakistani feminists of encouraging unIslamic vulgarity by raising slogans that hinted that a woman had the right to do as she pleased. Conservatives further threatened participants when feminists clarified that they would rightfully own up and support pro-rights, pro-choice slogan [[Mera Jism Meri Marzi]] (My body my choice). Aurat March participants insisted that there is nothing vulgar in asking their rights; besides it is societal duplicity in Pakistan that besides open display of sexual harassment of women, adverts of 'Mardana Kamzori' (discussing masculine sexuality) are openly displayed, sexualized abusive linguistic commonly used, online search histories of many men would show wide porn consumption, word 'Aurat' itself originally talks of women body in wide use; but when it comes to better awareness and women's rights their slogans are thought to be inappropriate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/626184-haya-march-to-counter-aurat-march-in-pakistan-women-march-for-rights-all-over-the-world|title=Haya march to counter Aurat march in Pakistan: Women march for rights all over the world|website=www.thenews.com.pk|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Aurat March 2020 c.jpg|thumb|Two marchers holding placards \"Meray Paas Mein Hoon\" (I am with myself) and Inquilab bhi Aurat ka kaam hay (Making revolution is women's task)]]\nAs pro-Aurat March hashtags trended on Twitter, including that of Mera Jism Meri Marzi (My body my choice), cultural and intellectual clashes happened in mainstream media.<ref>{{cite news |title=Aurat March placards turn up the heat against Khalilur Rehman |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2172262/4-aurat-march-placards-turn-heat-khalilur-rehman/ |newspaper=The Express Tribune |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> Online social media eventually did show off-line impact.<ref name=\":13\" /> In an analysis of opposing Twitter trends by ''Rizvan Saeed'' it emerged that #WeRejectMeraJismMeriMarzi and #HayaMarch were most likely organic few other hashtags which were trended on Twitter like #AmirLiaqat_Laanti #\u0627\u06cc\u06a9\u0633\u067e\u0627\u0626\u0631_\u06a9\u06be\u0633\u0631\u06d2 (roughly translates into \"expired eunuchs.\")\n\n<nowiki>#</nowiki>\u0641\u062d\u0627\u0634\u06cc_\u0645\u0627\u0631\u0686_\u0646\u0627\u0645\u0646\u0638\u0648\u0631 (Roughly translated as \"Vulgar March Unacceptable\") were inorganically propagated by limited number of individual groups of vested conservative interests including groups affiliated with ultra conservative Tehreek-e-Labaik Pakistan to trend anti-Aurat March memes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.samaa.tv/opinion/2020/03/was-opposition-to-aurat-march-real-or-manufactured/|title=Was opposition to Aurat March real or manufactured? {{!}} SAMAA|website=Samaa TV|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\nIn the run up to 2020 march, polity in Pakistan started drawing subtle political lines either favoring or distancing from the march in various degrees. Ultra-conservatives claimed Islam is already the most feminist religion and has secured all the rights to women, so they need not have any more demands, but need to go back and adopt more of the modest culture expected of [[Muslim women]]. These people arranged counter 'Haya' (modesty) marches to stop Aurat March with the slogan \"Our bodies, Allah's choice\".<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/626184-haya-march-to-counter-aurat-march-in-pakistan-women-march-for-rights-all-over-the-world|title=Haya march to counter Aurat march in Pakistan: Women march for rights all over the world|website=www.thenews.com.pk|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> Erstwhile Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif's Muslim league party (PML-N),  while it did not oppose Aurat March openly, cautioned marchers not to cross Islamic cultural markers. Contemporary Prime Minister [[Imran Khan]]'s government, ruled by his Pakistan Tekreek-i-Insaf (which had buckled under pressure to the ultra-conservative groups a month earlier which created violent ruckus while opposing Aurat March in Islamabad) while formally supporting march connected religio-cultural appropriateness of slogans of the march with national honor. Subsequently, after the Aurat March took place, Prime Minister Imran Khan expressed criticism of the lack of uniform education which would have educated marchers better.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweekpakistan.com/imran-khan-blames-education-system-for-aurat-march-culture/|title=Imran Khan Blames Education System for Aurat March \u2018Culture\u2019|date=2020-03-12|website=Newsweek Pakistan|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> The left-of-center Pakistan Peoples Party was more welcoming of Aurat March. Mustafa Nawaz Khokhar, the Senator representing PPP, criticized Prime Minister Imran Khan and his party to be favoring ultra-conservative and PML-N and PTI positions as an undeclared anti-women alliance. PPP were replied back opponents by pointing out lacuna on their side.<ref name=\":11\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1538978|title=Govt to support Aurat March with strings attached|last=Reporter|first=The Newspaper's Staff|date=2020-03-07|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> Janita Tahir noted that participants of Aurat March are questioning Imran Khan while he speaks so much for human rights for minorities world over, is he doing enough for human rights of half the population of Pakistan which finds itself in weaker position?<ref name=\":12\" /> Farzana Rasheed further asks in her article that why Pakistan can't be Islamic republic & free at the same time? She further questions contradictions of Imran Khan & Pakistan's conservative polity that instigates and condones extremist violence same time claiming to be democratic and peaceful and that they do not support violence but understand sentiment behind it, as usual victim blaming non violent women's protest for the violence committed on them.<ref name=\":13\" />\n\n=== Posters & slogans 2020 ===\n[[File:Aurat March 2020 d.jpg|thumb]]\nThe  8 March 2020's slogans also included slogans like, \"Saying [[Mashallah]] does not make your [[harassment]] [[halal]]\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stepfeed.com/this-arab-girl-shut-down-halal-harassment-in-the-most-savage-way-1194|title=This Arab girl shut down 'halal harassment' in the most savage way|last=Khalife|first=Leyal|date=2017-10-05|website=StepFeed|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\":14\" />, \"Domestic violence kills more than [[Coronavirus disease 2019|corona]]\", \"I march so one day my daughters won't have to\", \"IMAGINE Not Loving The Women in your Life Enough To Advocate For Their Rights\"<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/276444-the-men-of-aurat-march-and-their-posters|title=The men of Aurat March (and their posters)|website=www.geo.tv|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/626541-these-posters-made-by-male-allies-will-get-you-thinking-about-aurat-march-demands|title=Men of Aurat March and their plea for us to think|website=www.thenews.com.pk|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nSupportive gents did hold placards like, \"I am surrounded by the opposite gender and I feel safe. 'I want same for them'\", \"Proud husband of a feminist, proud father of a feminist, proud feminist\", \"I will be a proud 'jorru ka ghulam\" (I will be proud, being called 'wife's slave' - south Asian misogynist patriarchal culture frequently uses the [[pejorative]] term 'jorru ka ghulam\"- wife's slave- to men who give an ear to their spouse) <ref name=\":14\" /><ref name=\":15\" />\n\n== See also ==\n{{div col}}\n* [[All Pakistan Women's Association]]\n* [[Aurat Foundation]]\n* [[Blue Veins (Pakistan)|Blue Veins]]\n* [[Feminism in Pakistan]]\n* [[Girls at Dhabas]]\n* [[Me Too movement (Pakistan)]]\n* [[Mera Jism Meri Marzi]]\n* [[Pakistan Federation of Business And Professional Women]]\n* [[Rape in Pakistan]]\n* [[Violence against women in Pakistan]]\n* [[Women in Islam]]\n* [[Women in Pakistan]]\n* [[Women's Action Forum]]\n* [[Women's Protection Bill]]\n* [[Women's rights]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline}}\n*{{official|https://auratmarch.com/ }}\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sJ7WgoLNIXU Hum Inquilab Hain] - Feminist Anthem  (YouTube link)\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pOavNaBX4NU&feature=emb_logo Mera Jism Meri Marzi]  Feminist song  (YouTube link)\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sJ7WgoLNIXU Aur Woh Rapist Ho Tum] - Chile Feminist Anthem in Urdu language (YouTube link)\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n\n\n[[Category:Women's movements based in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Women's rights in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Feminism in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Feminist movements and ideologies]]\n[[Category:Socialism in Pakistan| ]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Aurat March''' ([[Urdu]]: \u0639\u0648\u0631\u062a \u0645\u0627\u0631\u0686 ) ([[English language|English]]: Women March ) is an annual [[Demonstration (political)|political demonstration]] organized in various cities of [[Pakistan]] including [[Lahore]], [[Hyderabad, Sindh|Hyderabad]], [[Sukkur]], [[Karachi]] and [[Islamabad]] to observe [[International Women's Day|International Women's Day]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Do2ADwAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Feminism, Postfeminism and Legal Theory: Beyond the Gendered Subject?|last=Gozdecka|first=Dorota|last2=Macduff|first2=Anne|date=2019-01-08|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781351040402|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kirmani|first=Nida|last2=Khan|first2=Ayesha|date=2018-11-27|title=Moving Beyond the Binary: Gender-based Activism in Pakistan|url=https://opendocs.ids.ac.uk/opendocs/handle/123456789/14196|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sahar|first=Naila|date=2018-10-02|title=Things She Could Never Have|journal=South Asian Review|volume=39|issue=3\u20134|pages=420\u2013422|doi=10.1080/02759527.2018.1518037|issn=0275-9527}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://images.dawn.com/news/1181993|title=The Aurat March challenges misogyny in our homes, workplaces and society, say organisers ahead of Women's Day|last=Staff|first=Images|date=2019-03-07|website=Images|language=en|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://natcour.com/story/238374/heres-all-you-need-to-know-about-aurat-march-2019/|title=Here's all you need to know about Aurat March 2019|date=2019-02-28|website=NC|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-09}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1468109|title=Aurat March to highlight 'Sisterhood and Solidarity'|last=Reporter|first=The Newspaper's Staff|date=2019-03-07|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1394385|title=Why the Aurat March is a revolutionary feat for Pakistan|last=Shah|first=Zuneera|date=2018-03-12|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2019-03-17}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/mar/15/pakistan-torn-as-womens-day-march-sparks-wave-of-masculine-anxiety|title=Pakistan torn as women's day march sparks wave of 'masculine anxiety'|last=Zahra-Malik|first=Mehreen|date=2019-03-15|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=2019-03-16|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2019/mar/08/women-take-to-the-streets-of-pakistan-to-rewrite-their-place-in-society-international-womens-day |title=Women take to the streets of Pakistan to rewrite their place in society |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=2019-03-08 |accessdate=2019-03-17 |last=Toppa |first=Sabrina}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/stories-47832236|title=The 'womanspreading' placard that caused fury in Pakistan|last=Ebrahim|first=Ammar|date=2019-04-06|access-date=2019-04-13|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@zoya_rehman/aurat-march-and-undisciplined-bodies-f6f23ada0318|title=Aurat March and Undisciplined Bodies:|last=Rehman|first=Zoya|date=2019-07-26|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> The first Aurat March was held on 8 March 2018 in [[Karachi]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/03/pakistani-women-hold-aurat-march-equality-gender-justice-190308115740534.html|title=Pakistani women hold 'aurat march' for equality, gender justice|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2019-03-16}}</ref> In 2019, it was organised in Lahore and Karachi by a women's collective called ''Hum Auratein'' (We the Women), and in other parts of the country, including Islamabad, Hyderabad, Quetta, Mardan, and Faislabad, by [[Women democratic front]] (WDF), Women Action Forum (WAF), and others.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/03/pakistani-women-hold-aurat-march-equality-gender-justice-190308115740534.html|title=Pakistani women hold 'aurat march' for equality, gender justice|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2019-03-16}}</ref>  The march was endorsed by the Lady Health Workers Association, and included representatives from multiple women's-rights organizations.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/magazine/instep-today/290411-aurat-march-2018-freedom-over-fear|title=Aurat March 2018: Freedom over fear|last=Saeed|first=Mehek|website=www.thenews.com.pk|language=en|access-date=2019-03-17}}</ref><ref name=\"dawn\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1470333|website=dawn.com|title=A rising movement|accessdate=2019-04-06|date=2019-03-18}}</ref> The march called for more accountability for violence against women, and to support for women who experience violence and harassment at the hands of security forces, in public spaces, at home, and at the workplace.<ref name=\":0\" /> Reports suggest that more and more women rushed to join the march until the crowd was became scattered. Women (as well as men) carried posters bearing phrases such as 'Ghar ka Kaam, Sab ka Kaam', and 'Women are humans, not honour' became a rallying cry.\n\nWomen dressed in T-shirts that read \u2018my favorite season is the fall (of [[patriarchy]])\u2019<ref name=\":117\">{{Cite web|last=Shahid|first= Atiqa|url=https://www.thewallet.com.pk/blog/a-march-for-rights-against-patriarchy/|title=A march for rights; against patriarchy|date=2020-03-08|website=The Wallet|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> and \u2018girls just want fun-damental human rights\u2019.  Some wore masks of dead social media celebrity [[Qandeel Baloch]] and one group held \u2018patriarchy\u2019s janaza\u2019 (funeral procession of patriarchy) on their shoulders. Participants were from all walks of life and included many eminent people. Social media and YouTube video messages expressed support for those who were marching. [[Nimra Afzal]] claimed in her article, that Aurat March is a women's empowerment movement which is not restricted to just peace rallies, raising awareness placards or sloganeering for women's equality in a patriarchal society. The movement is just not man-hating or elitist but a movement that asks for public spaces, with hashtags like #JaggaDein (Give space).<ref name=\":3\" />\n[[File:Aurat March 2019.jpg|thumb|Aurat March 2019]]\n[[File:Aurat March 2020.jpg|thumb|A mother with her young daughters in Aurat March 2020]]\n\n== Context ==\nAgainst backdrop of deep rooted socio-religio-political patriarchal structures of Pakistan's society and state, [[women in Pakistan]] face many types of social ills, systemic discrimination depriving fundamental rights amounting to sexual [[apartheid]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/574916/social-constructionism-and-women-empowerment-2/|title=Social constructionism and women empowerment|date=2020-03-12|website=Daily Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> including but not limited to forced & early childhood marriage, lack of enough formal public education opportunities, lack of freedom and lack of access to use two wheeler, lack of free & safe access to public spaces, domestic violence, sexual harassment & sexual violence at homes, at public  transport & at work places plus wage gap, over powering of their sexual freedom & right of choice and equality under religious garb and many serious crimes like appropriation of rights & abuse for revenge including but not limited to acid attacks, [[Honour killing in Pakistan|honor killings]]  without being addressed, regularly silenced by society, frequently overlooked by  state<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/opinion/letter-from-pakistan/for-pakistani-men-aurat-march-is-the-real-coronavirus/375862/|title=For Pakistani men, Aurat March is the real coronavirus|last=Inayat|first=Naila|date=2020-03-05|website=ThePrint|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref>; With guidance of [[Feminism in Pakistan|feminist movement]], new generation of women's collective started challenging status quo with help of social media in parallel to [[Me Too movement (Pakistan)|#MeToo movement]] in an effort to take equal rights movement to ordinary women they started organizing annual Aurat March on [[International Women's Day|international women's day]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Anjum|first=Gulnaz|date=2020-02-27|title=Women's Activism in Pakistan: Role of Religious Nationalism and Feminist Ideology Among Self-Identified Conservatives and Liberals|journal=Open Cultural Studies|volume=4|issue=1|pages=Pages 36\u201349|doi=10.1515/culture-2020-0004|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shaheed|first=Farida|title=Maintaining Momentum in Changing Circumstances|date=2019|journal=Journal of International Affairs|volume=72|issue=2|pages=159\u2013172|issn=0022-197X|jstor=26760840}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/574916/social-constructionism-and-women-empowerment-2/|title=Social constructionism and women empowerment|date=2020-03-12|website=Daily Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nIn an article published on 14 February 2016 in ''[[Forbes]]'', journalist Sonya Rehman wrote, \"while the world celebrates [[Valentine's Day in Pakistan|Valentine's Day]], a number of Pakistani women succumb to honor killings by their very own kin\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/sonyarehman/2016/02/14/filmmaker-takes-on-honor-killing-in-pakistan/|title=Filmmaker Takes On Honor Killing in Pakistan|last=Rehman|first=Sonya|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref> An [[honour killing]] is the [[homicide]] of a member of a family or social group by other members, due to the belief the victim has brought [[Honour|dishonour]] upon the family or community.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite book|last=Jafri|first=Amir H.|title=Honour killing: dilemma, ritual, understanding|date=2008|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780195476316|location=Oxford|oclc=180753749}}</ref> The death of the victim is viewed as a way to restore the reputation and honour of the family. Pakistan has world's highest prevalence of honor killings. Pakistan, where 60 percent of the population is below age 30 and half are under 18, are influenced more by global trends than traditions.<ref name=\":03\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-valentines-day-pakistan-idUSKBN1FS1XP|title=Love is in the air, but not on airwaves as Pakistan bans Valentine's Day|date=2018-02-08|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-01-25|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Hadid & Sattar\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/parallels/2018/02/14/585486507/in-pakistan-valentines-day-brings-out-roses-and-culture-wars|title=In Pakistan, Valentine's Day Brings Out Roses And Culture Wars|last=Hadid|first=Diaa|last2=Sattar|first2=Abdul|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>  [[Valentine's Day in Pakistan|Valentine's Day]] serves annually as a flash point of the [[culture war]] in Pakistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2016/02/26/love-and-politics-valentines-day-in-pakistan/|title=Love and Politics: Valentine's Day in Pakistan|last=Nazish|first=Kiran|website=Foreign Policy|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref> Diaa Hadid says that it is a [[cause c\u00e9l\u00e8bre]] for religious hard-liners, affording conservatives a chance assert themselves as the caretakers of Islamic identity.<ref name=\":42\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/parallels/2018/02/14/585486507/in-pakistan-valentines-day-brings-out-roses-and-culture-wars|title=In Pakistan, Valentine's Day Brings Out Roses And Culture Wars|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref>  While many Pakistanis celebrate the Valentine's Day's festivities, '''[[Pakistan]]''' has officially banned Valentine's Day, and the [[Islamism|Islamist]] orthodoxy<ref>{{Cite journal |jstor = 24479574|title = The Popularity of 'Valentine Day': A Sociological Perspective|last1 = Patel|first1 = Pravin J.|journal = Economic and Political Weekly|volume = 49|issue = 19|pages = 19\u201321|year = 2014}}</ref> has taken steps to obstruct celebrations,<ref name=\":04\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-valentines-day-pakistan-idUSKBN1FS1XP|title=Love is in the air, but not on airwaves as Pakistan bans Valentine's Day|date=2018-02-08|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-01-25|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1457860|title=All you need is love|date=2019-01-16|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref> Women's freedom is scorned by conservatives and extremist institutions in Pakistani society.<ref name=\":72\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1457860|title=All you need is love|date=2019-01-16|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref> The focus is not simply to restrict women's free expression on a particular day, but rather to subjugate women to strengthen male dominance through their seclusion from public life. The complex rules of ''[[purdah]]'' (seclusion) which reinforce chastity and family honor, have led to socio-cultural disparities, in every aspect of women's lives. Lacking an understanding of their civil, legal, and political rights, women's opportunities for participation in society are limited and they are left vulnerable to exploitation, oppression, and abusive control by others without adequate recourse.<ref name=\"Riffat\">{{Cite web|url=http://unsworks.unsw.edu.au/fapi/datastream/unsworks:45876/SOURCE01?view=true|title=Purdah of hearts and eyes, Examination of Purdah as an institution in Pakistan|last=Riffat|first=Haque|date=October 2003|website=[unsw.edu.au the University of New South Wales,Australia]|pages=219\u2013223|url-status=live|access-date=27 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1526245|title=FEAR AND THE CITY|last=Khatri|first=Sadia|date=2020-01-05|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref> Technically, love is not ''[[haram]]'' (forbidden) in Islam, but gender segregation and gender mixing prohibitions stifle the freedom of Muslim women.<ref name=\":43\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/parallels/2018/02/14/585486507/in-pakistan-valentines-day-brings-out-roses-and-culture-wars|title=In Pakistan, Valentine's Day Brings Out Roses And Culture Wars|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref> Access to public spaces for women is severely constrained<ref name=\":92\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1526245|title=FEAR AND THE CITY|last=Khatri|first=Sadia|date=2020-01-05|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref> and conservative, rigid interpretations of Islam create limits on women's behavior. In the conservative view, women are not allowed to show their faces, not allowed to talk to unrelated men unless the communication is essential, and are unable to choose their own life partner, as that is a decision made by the head of the family.<ref name=\":52\">{{Cite book|last=Yasmeen|first=Samina|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=Y5RODwAAQBAJ&lpg=PA156&dq=Valentine's%20Day%20in%20Pakistan&pg=PA157#v=onepage&q=Valentine's%20Day%20in%20Pakistan&f=true|title=Jihad and Dawah: Evolving Narratives of Lashkar-e-Taiba and Jamat ud Dawah|date=2017-10-01|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-1-84904-974-0|pages=156\u2013158|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Human Rights Commission of Pakistan]] lists 460 cases of reported honour killings in 2017, with 194 males and 376 females as victims. Of these killings, 253 were sparked by disapproval of illicit relations and 73 by disapproval of marriage choice. Additionally, out of the known suspect relationship with victims, over 93% were family relationships.<ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=http://hrcpmonitor.org/search/?id=5|title=HRCP Archive {{!}} Search News|website=hrcpmonitor.org|language=en|access-date=2018-05-02}}</ref> Although these are most likely only a sample of the actual honour killings that were completed during 2017, it still gives a glimpse into characteristics of honour killings in Pakistan. Sources disagree as to the exact number by year, but according to [[Human Rights Watch]], NGOs/INGOs in the area estimate that around 1000 honour killings are carried out each year in Pakistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/08/23/pakistan-should-not-again-fail-honor-killing-victim|title=Pakistan Should Not Again Fail 'Honor Killing' Victim|last=Ijaz|first=Saroop|date=22 August 2019|website=Human Rights Watch|location=New York, New York|access-date=February 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWith such horrific background of fundamental human right violations of women of Pakistan, millennial young adults started  demanding access to public spaces with movements like [[Girls at Dhabas]] which gained significant traction from women across South Asia since 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tns.thenews.com.pk/girls-at-dhabas-much-needed-campaign/|title=Girls at Dhabas: A much-needed campaign|last1=Editor|first1=T. N. S.|date=13 September 2015|website=TNS - The News on Sunday}}</ref> and so also new generation of feminist thought started breaking the silence around issues like sexual autonomy and agency  as soon as they did get opportunity to express through some of placards of Aurat March, says Zoya Rehman.<ref name=\":8\" /> That is how the March which was primarily intended for gender equity in multiple range of issues also came to explore construction of narratives relating to socio religio political exploitation of women sexuality in Pakistan and challenge posed to sexual injustices through Aurat March by new generation feminist  became part of Pakistan's national debate.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n== Manifesto ==\nManifesto demands economic justice, including implementation of labour rights, the Sexual Harassment Against Women in the Workplace Act 2010, recognition of women's input to the \u2018care economy\u2019 as unpaid labour, and provision of maternity leaves and day care centres to ensure women's inclusion in the labour force. Among other things, it also demands access to safe drinking water and air, protection of animals and wildlife, recognition of women's participation in production of food and cash crops, access to a fair justice system, inclusion of women with disabilities as well as the transgender community, reproductive justice, access to public spaces inclusion in educational institutions, rights of religious minorities, promotion of an anti-war agenda, end to police brutality and enforced disappearances.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Themes ==\nAccording to Zuneera Shah, while etymology of word 'Aurat' (Woman) indicates being misogynistic Since Western supremacy over feminist movements feeds into a distaste towards feminism in countries such as Pakistan. Localization of the struggle for women's rights has importance among South Asian activists and feminists the way to relate the feminist movement.<ref name=\":5\" /> Shah says With the Aurat March, terms such as 'pidar shahi' (patriarchy) and 'aurat march' are being circulated and created.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nTheme for 2018 march was 'Equality\u2019 whereas theme for 2019 march is 'Sisterhood and Solidarity'.<ref name=\":0\" /> Nighat Dad explains in her article that \"The agenda of this march was to demand resources and dignity for women, for transgender community, for religious minorities and for those on the economic margins but more importantly to acknowledge that women\u2019s emancipation is inherently linked with the improvement of all mistreated groups and minorities.As per Leena Ghani theme for 2020 Aurat March is Khudmukhtari (autonomy) and violence, both sexual and economic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2020/03/pakistani-women-are-ready-for-another-aurat-march-is-pakistan/|title=Pakistani Women Are Ready for Another Aurat March. Is Pakistan?|website=thediplomat.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n\n== Women's March 2019 ==\n\n[[File:Mera Jism Meri Marzi (My Body, My Choice).jpg|thumb|Mera Jism Meri Marzi (My Body, My Choice)]]\n[[File:Placards displayed by Marchers during Aurat March 2019.jpg|thumb|Placards displayed by Marchers during Aurat March 2019]]\n[[File:Women displaying placards during Aurat March 2019.jpg|thumb|Women displaying placards during Aurat March 2019]]\n[[File:Marchers holding placards during Aurat March 2020.jpg|thumb|Marchers holding placards during Aurat March 2020]]\n[[File:Farhan Wilayat (Philanthropist and Social Activist) during Aurat March 2020.jpg|thumb|Farhan Wilayat ([[Philanthropist]] and [[Social Activist]]) during Aurat March 2020 outside [[Lahore Press Club]]]]\n[[File:Aurat March 2020 e.jpg|thumb|Zahra Khan Farooqi, a blogger, stood for the women who weren't allowed to join the march.]]\n[[File:Aurat March 2020 d.jpg|thumb|Nisha Khawaja, a marcher, bringing attention to the harassment cases at work and elsewhere]]\n\n===Posters Slogans and Media Debates===\nThe hundreds of posters featured at women's day march across Pakistan highlighted [[fundamental rights]] issues such as access to education and employment.<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Mera Jism Meri Marzi]] (My body, my choice) became a main and most talked slogan of Aurat March with a lot of debates, discussions in country over the years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thefeministani.com/2019/11/29/mera-jism-meri-marzi/|title=Mera jism meri marzi|last=Shah|first=Bina|date=29 November 2019|website=The Feministani|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref> This led to slogans like 'Why are you afraid of my self determination', 'A womxn's right to autonomy on her own body'''<nowiki/>'''', 'In fact, everyone should get to decide what happens to their body, for themselves'<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mangobaaz.com/38-of-the-most-powerful-aurat-march-2020-posters-that-you-absolutely-have-to-see|title=38 Of The Most Powerful Aurat March 2020 Posters That You Absolutely Have To See|last=Noor|date=2020-03-09|website=MangoBaaz|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> Some of March 2018 posters included slogans like \"[[Women's rights|Our rights]] are not for grab neither are we\", \"Girls just wanna have Fundamental human rights\", [[Trans woman|'Transwomen]] are women shut up', \"Tu kare tou Stud, Mai Karun tou [[Slut-shaming|Slut]] (If you do it then Stud but If I do it then Slut)\", \"Safe street program for women\", \"Stop being [[Menstrual cycle|Menstrual]] phobic\", \"[[Consent]] ki [[Tasbih|Tasbeeh]] Rozana Parhen (Ask for consent every time)\", \"[[Paratha]] Rolls Not [[Gender role|Gender Roles]].\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Staff |first1=Images |title=These posters from the Aurat March say everything you wish you could |url=https://images.dawn.com/news/1179620 |work=Images |date=9 March 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Javaid, Maham |first1=T. N. S. |title=Paratha rolls, not gender roles |url=http://tns.thenews.com.pk/paratha-rolls-gender-roles/#.XaQFd3RrzIU |work=TNS - The News on Sunday |date=11 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, some posters also appeared saying \"Man of quality will never be afraid of equality, \"Jab tak aurat tang rahay gi, jang rahay gi, jang rahay gi\",<ref>{{cite news |last1= Javaid, Maham |first1=T. N. S. |title=Paratha rolls, not gender roles |url=http://tns.thenews.com.pk/paratha-rolls-gender-roles/#.XaRNF3RrzIV |work=TNS - The News on Sunday |date=11 March 2018}}</ref> and \"Keep your dick pics to yourself\". Another had a drawing of a [[vagina]] and two [[Ovary|ovaries]] and the words: \"Grow a pair!\" Another poster said, \"If you like the headscarf so much, tie it around your eyes\", one depicting a girl sitting with her legs spread out, ''Lo Beth Gayi Sahi Se'' or the irreverent ''Akeli Awara Azaad'' \"Nazar teri gandi aur purdah mein keroun\" (Why do I adopt veil cause of your bad habit of ogling) \"Aaj waqai maa behn ek ho rahi hai\"<ref>{{cite news |title='Maa Behen Ek Ho Rahi Hy' And Other Aurat March Signs, Explained |url=https://auratnow.com/2019/03/09/aurat-march-2019-international-womens-day-placards-slogans-signs/ |work=Aurat Now |date=9 March 2019}}</ref> depicts all women coming together without differences. One poster read that maybe we haven't seen any woman as independent as a '[[Tawaif|tawaaif]]', so this is the reason we (some of our society) consider every independent woman a 'tawaaif', another \"My shirt is not short, it's your mindset that is narrow\", and posters like \"these are my streets too\" claimed public spaces.\n\nAilia Zehra deconstructs a poster in her article that says \"If Cynthia does it, she\u2019s applauded. If I do it, I\u2019m the villain\". For those who do not know, Cynthia Ritchie is an American social media influencer facilitated by Pakistan establishment's [[Whitewashing (censorship)|whitewash]] for state propaganda. This woman rode a bicycle somewhere in Pakistan and tweeted her picture in a bid to bring down local feminists by implying that they lie when they say women cannot freely access public spaces. This placard admirably summarizes what is wrong with an American woman lecturing Pakistani women on freedom and mobility. Ailia Zehra regrets double standards saying Yes, Pakistani men are fine with women riding bicycles on the roads \u2013 as long as the women are white.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zehra |first1=Ailia |title=How Aurat March Challenged The Deeply Ingrained Toxic Masculinity |url=https://nayadaur.tv/2019/03/how-aurat-march-challenged-the-deeply-ingrained-toxic-masculinity/ |work=Naya Daur |date=9 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Nighat Dad]] who organized the women's march in [[Lahore]], said people were angry over the posters because most Pakistanis, especially men were not yet ready to allow them [[Freedom of choice|free choice]]. As per Nighat Dad, restricted topics like women's rights to their own bodies, their sexuality, are being discussed for the first time was an immense success of the march. Dad complained, \"Online harassments has gone too far in terms of death and rape threats to the organizers and also to the marchers.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Aurat March organisers receive online death threats |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1470144 |work=DAWN.COM |date=17 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Pakistan's Women Marched for Their Rights. Then the Backlash Came. |url=https://thediplomat.com/2019/03/pakistans-women-marched-for-their-rights-then-the-backlash-came/ |work=thediplomat.com}}</ref>\n\nMany grumbled that the marchers were \"[[Vulgarity|vulgar]]\" opportunists who had transgressed on conservative values in the Muslim-majority country and \"undermined\" a legitimate fight for rights with a [[Liberalism|liberal]], anti-Islamic agenda.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> Feminist writer [[Sadia Khatri]] exposes this built up of narrative in her article, \"Should feminists claim Aurat March's Vulgar Posters? Ye s absolutely.\" Khatri says people have been posting photographs showing the posters that didn't get as much air-time, posters addressing the range of 'important' causes that news anchors have accused the March of ignoring, like education, inheritance and marital rights. By bringing up the manifesto to defend the posters, for instance, Pakistan Feminists isolated themselves from the supposedly provocative posters, and in fact confirm their 'vulgarity'. It implies that Pakistani feminists agree that feminism should operate within the bounds of 'respectability'. According to her accepting narratives prescribing boundaries of respectability are traps that needs to be avoided by feminists and not to be allowed to be cemented in any social discourse. Feminism with conditions is no feminism. It maintains the division between what is \u2018acceptable\u2019 and what is 'immodest', what is 'public' and 'private', allowed and not. It pits the two against each other, rewarding the feminists who rally for legal rights and work-life balance and slut-shaming those who reclaim gendered slurs and carry the posters they did at the March. She questions whether feminism to allow discriminate and gatekeeping, and this gatekeeping is patriarchy's way of bolstering the binary of purpose vs pleasure, where the feminism of purpose (health, education, marital rights) is 'good' feminism, and the feminism of pleasure (sexual politics, bodily autonomy, agency over time and leisure) is 'bad' feminism, 'immoral' and 'frivolous'. She explains as feminists use the language of real and serious, end up creating a distinction between 'actual' issues and 'pretended' ones and rush to clarify that feminists have included 'important' causes in our demands, end up suggesting that other causes are unimportant.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Khatri |first1=Sadia |title=Should feminists claim Aurat March\u2019s 'vulgar' posters? Yes, absolutely |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1469815 |work=DAWN.COM |date=15 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn an article \"Womansplaining the Aurat March: Dear men, here\u2019s why Pakistan\u2019s women are asserting their rights\" writer Rimmel Mohydin handles misogynist objections to the Women's march slogans in a different way.<ref name=\"womansxplain\">{{cite news |last1=Mohydin |first1=Rimmel |title=Let me womansplain the Aurat March to you |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1469183 |work=DAWN.COM |date=12 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Rimmel Mohydin suggests those men to \"smile, you'll look prettier that way.\" Ms. Mohydin humorously questions Women can be the subject of many sexist jokes, but if the women crack a joke on what ground that wit is considered offensive?<ref name=\"womansxplain\" /> She says Every wisecrack, every sassy one-liner, every appealing slogan masked years and years of invisible pain that women have suffered.<ref name=\"womansxplain\" /> A Woman can tell men through their placards that she won't warm his bed if he doesn't warm his food, but what really gets misogynist mind hot and troubled is that she, a woman, could laugh at his expense.<ref name=\"womansxplain\" />\n\nOn an effort of misogynist parliamentarian's effort or agenda finding conspiracy theory behind women's march Ms. Mohydin sarcastically quips, \"It is difficult to know where to place your feet when you find that the backs that you have been walking on are now standing up. That's why the author's compassion is with misogynist politicians\". Referring poster slogan \"Keep your dick pics to yourself.\" Ms. Mohydin says What seems to have affronted the male collective the most is the shattering of a fantasy world where women enjoy being subjected to unrequested pictures of male genitals. Poster slogan has hit them hard. It has upset them. And now, they are angry and trying to speak to us in a language that they think we'll understand. They tell us this is not feminism but fail to explain how. They tell us it's about sex, and as 'respectful' women, how dare we utter of it.<ref name=\"womansxplain\" /> \"When women make demands about their personal lives, their bodies, their sexuality, that's when people feel threatened,\" Dad said. \u201cSo it\u2019s OK to ask the government for the right to education but you can't say you are happily divorced because the breakdown of a matrimony is a shameful thing, a woman\u2019s failure, and you can\u2019t say 'don't send me dick pics' because so-called decent women don't use expressions like dick.\u201d Nobody seems to say anything to the sender, but the reluctant receiver is apparently the problem. Either she likes it (which, to them, makes her a 'slut') or she doesn't (which offends them). So as usual, women cannot win Ms. Mohydin says. Remaining on the same issue Ms. Mohydin strongly questions \"Are they unsettled at the loss of this opportunity to titillate women with their phallus? Why are they all shriveling up? Have protesting women given them performance anxiety or what.<ref name=\"womansxplain\" />\n\nContinuing her strong denunciation Ms. Mohydin says, \"The placards were a mirror and instead of taking this moment as an opportunity to introspect, they have decided to beat their chest instead. Not their slain bodies, not their acid-burnt faces, not their immobility, not their lack of representation, not the dearth of affordable housing, not the moral policing their choices and bodies are subjected to, not the denial of female education, not the constant threat of sexual harassment and onslaught, not the social structures that cut women\u2019s potential in half, not the exploitation, not the objectification, not the fact that for many, women are still not human. It seems to me that for them, the problem is women themselves, Ms. Mohydin rues.<ref name=\"womansxplain\" />\n\n[[Shaan Shahid]], arguably Pakistan\u2019s well-known film star, wrote on [[Twitter]] he thought the posters did not \"represent our culture, our values\". He was criticized in return for his films that blatantly sexualize women and reduce their existence to a mere prop to exert the \u2018masculinity\u2019 of his character. He defends his position as freedom of expression, but when women call out this misogynistic culture with his hypocrisy he looks down freedom of expression by women.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pakistani women lash out at Shaan over his criticism on Aurat March |url=https://www.natcour.com/news/2019/03/pakistani-women-lash-out-at-shaan-over-his/ |work=National Courier |date=12 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nVeena Malik, a popular actor who caused an uproar in 2012 when she appeared with scantily dressed on the cover of an Indian men's magazine, posted that the march had \"brought humiliation to women of Pakistan\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Veena Malik Gets Called Out After Saying that Aurat March Was 'Humiliating for Women' |url=https://propakistani.pk/lens/veena-malik-gets-called-out-after-saying-that-aurat-march-was-humiliating-for-women/ |work=Lens |date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Twitter users were prompt to remind Veena that \"the same women you are calling out for 'humiliating' Pakistani femininities were standing by you as mullahs imposed fatwas on you.\"\n\n[[Kishwar Naheed]], a poet best cherished for a poem called \"Us sinful women\", was seen in a video saying: \"The next time you make such slogans, remember your culture, your traditions.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Kishwar Naheed rejects certain slogans of Aurat March, receives backlash |url=https://en.dailypakistan.com.pk/lifestyle/kishwar-naheed-rejects-certain-slogans-of-aurat-march-receives-backlash/ |work=Daily Pakistan Global}}</ref> Sadia Khatri a feminist writer, replies back through her column in Dawn saying someone should remind  Naheed, that it is specifically culture and tradition; that keeps the frivolous and the silly relegating women to private spaces where women court the greatest risks, where the threat of assault is most prevalent, and where, when women are harmed, the walls around womanhood remind women to stay silent, like \u2018good\u2019, \u2018honourable\u2019 women those culture and tradition are what upturned when thousands of women come out into the streets, dancing and laughing with exhilaration.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Khatri |first1=Sadia |title=Should feminists claim Aurat March\u2019s 'vulgar' posters? Yes, absolutely |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1469815 |work=DAWN.COM |date=15 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Guardian journalist Mehreen Zahra-Malik, some of the profanity-filled tirades were frightening. A film student posted screenshots of a group of boys [[Sexual harassment|sexually harassing]] her 16-year-old younger sister online and threatening her with [[rape]] for posting on [[Instagram]] in support of the march.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zahra-Malik |first1=Mehreen |title=Pakistan torn as women\u2019s day march sparks wave of 'masculine anxiety' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/mar/15/pakistan-torn-as-womens-day-march-sparks-wave-of-masculine-anxiety |work=The Guardian |date=15 March 2019}}</ref> Pakistan is a conservative society, activists sporting simple posters like \"You can\u2019t say you are happily divorced' also received messages filled with sexual innuendo and threats of sexual violence. Women participating in Aurat March had received threats of physical and sexual violence from social media users after posting photographs of the posters. In Pakistan, the threats of violence are not hollow. According to the [[Human Rights Commission of Pakistan]], roughly 500 women are killed each year by family members who believe their honour has been damaged.\n\nOn 20 March 2019, [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]] Assembly held a protest in the reaction of the Aurat March. Rehana Ismail of the Muttahida Majlis-i-Amal (MMA), presented the resolution, saying that women participating in the march were holding \"obscene\" placards and raising slogans. The resolution said that the demands made at the march about women empowerment were \"un-Islamic and shameful\".<ref>{{cite news |title=KP Assembly demands action against \u2018shameless slogans\u2019 at Aurat March, passes resolution |url=https://en.dailypakistan.com.pk/lifestyle/kp-assembly-demands-action-against-shameless-slogans-at-aurat-march-passes-resolution/ |work=Daily Pakistan Global}}</ref>\n\nOne popular poster called for men to warm their own food; another asked them to find their own socks. And one read, \"I'll warm your food but you warm your own bed.\" As per [[Nida Kirmani]], a feminist sociologist at the [[Lahore University of Management Sciences]] such posters got the most vitriolic responses because those challenged the intimate relations of power within the household. In a nytimes article Mohammed Hanif says the men in Pakistan who profess to guard women, in real sense only guard for their own selfish interests. Hanif says They don't want to look for their own socks, and they don't want to control that manly urge to take selfies of their private parts and send them to random women.Hanif questions how it is okay asking young woman to stop to holding up a placard and how it can be seen as a threat to the national moral order?<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hanif|first=Mohammed|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/07/opinion/international-womens-day-pakistan.html|title=Opinion {{!}} \u2018How Do I Know Where Your Socks Are?\u2019|date=2020-03-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-08|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> As per Sabahat Zakariya, a newspaper editor these kinds of slogans have unleashed a wave of [[Misogyny|masculine anxiety]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zahra-Malik |first1=Mehreen |title=Pakistan torn as women\u2019s day march sparks wave of \u2018masculine anxiety\u2019 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/mar/15/pakistan-torn-as-womens-day-march-sparks-wave-of-masculine-anxiety |work=The Guardian |date=15 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Social media hashtag ==\nOne of the hashtag at 2018 rally was #KhaanaKhudGaramKarLo (heat your own meal). Whereas in 2019 it transformed to 'Ghar ka Kam, Sab ka Kam' (House work is everyone's responsibility) slogan'\n\n2019 March '#WhyIMarch' became the social media hashtag and slogan for the event,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thequint.com/neon/social-buzz/art-and-beyond-why-aurat-march-2020-pakistan-will-not-be-silence|title=Art & Beyond: Why Pakistan\u2019s #AuratMarch Will Not Be Silenced|date=2020-03-02|website=The Quint|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> with many celebrities, human rights activists, and locals sharing their stories of why they marched #HumAurtein #auratmarch #AuratMarch2019 #JaggaDein.\n\nAhead of Aurat March 2020 hashtags like #AuratMarch2020 and #MeraJismMeriMarzi are run on various platforms.\n\n==Women's March 2020==\n\nAurat march was held in Karachi, Hyderabad, Lahore and Quetta whereas Aurat Azadi March was held in Islamabad, Sukkur and Multan.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hasnain |first1=Alefyah |title=Aurat March 2020 Pakistan: Here's How This Year's March Stood Out From Last Year's! |url=https://www.brandsynario.com/aurat-march-2020-vs-2019/ |work=Brandsynario |date=9 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=\u2018Aurat March\u2019 held in Quetta |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2172005/1-aurat-march-held-quetta/ |work=The Express Tribune |date=9 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title='Aurat March' 2020 being held across nationwide to mark International Women's Day |url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/572275/aurat-march-2020-being-held-across-nationwide-to-mark-international-womens-day/ |work=Daily Times |date=8 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Aurat March 2020: Nationwide demonstrations held to celebrate womanhood, demand equality |url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/276214-aurat-march-being-held-nationwide |work=www.geo.tv}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The aesthetics of Aurat March 2020 |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2172813/4-aesthetics-aurat-march-2020/ |newspaper=The Express Tribune |date=March 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title='Aurat March' to include laborers, farmers, fringe communities, say organizers |url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1638161/pakistan |work=Arab News |date=7 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Aurat March: Thousands hit streets for gender equality |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2171752/1-aurat-march-held-across-pakistan-mark-international-womens-day/ |work=The Express Tribune |date=8 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Pakistan marks Women\u2019s Day with \u2018Aurat March\u2019 |url=https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/pakistan/pakistan-marks-womens-day-with-aurat-march-1.70236576 |work=gulfnews.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title='Aurat March' held nationwide to mark International Women's Day |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1539318 |work=DAWN.COM |date=8 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n \n=== Aurat March Lahore===\nArtist Shehzil Malik started collecting poster design submissions for Aurat March of 8 March 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2145791/4-artist-shehzil-malik-calls-aurat-march-poster-design-submissions/|title=Artist Shehzil Malik calls for Aurat March poster design submissions|last=Tribune|first=The Express|date=28 January 2020|work=The Express Tribune Pakistan|access-date=4 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  Participants of the March created a Mural of posters submitted by Volunteers in Hussain Chowk of Lahore which was ransacked within hours in a [[hate crime]] attack.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://images.dawn.com/news/1184719|title=Women peacefully put up Aurat March posters, men violently tore them down|last=Staff|first=Images|date=2020-02-24|website=Images|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.samaa.tv/news/pakistan/2020/02/aurat-march-2020-mural-vandalised-in-lahore/|title=Aurat March 2020 mural vandalised in Lahore {{!}} SAMAA|website=Samaa TV|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oyeyeah.com/events/aurat-march-posters-vandalized-by-angry-mob/|title=Aurat March Posters Vandalized by Angry Mob|last=Arshad|first=Aisha|date=2020-02-25|website=Oyeyeah|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref> Janita Tahir says participants in the March are being threatened by orthodox men and need to be taken seriously before any untoward incidence could take place and government need to do needful for protection of participating women.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mangobaaz.com/ghairat-ke-thaykedaar-are-issuing-threats-to-aurat-march-no-ones-stopping-them|title=Ghairat Ke Thaykedaar Are Issuing Threats To Aurat March & No One's Stopping Them|last=Tahir|first=Janita|date=2020-02-26|website=MangoBaaz|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/620253-threats-to-sukkur-organisers-of-aurat-march-condemned|title=Threats to Sukkur organisers of Aurat March condemned|website=www.thenews.com.pk|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Men also present in support of the Aurat March 2020.jpg|thumb|Men also joined Aurat March 2020 outside [[Lahore Press Club]] to support women's rights]]\nA petition was filed in the Lahore High Court by the Judicial Activism Council Chairman to stop Aurat March 2020, calling it \"against the very norms of Islam\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Bilal|first=Rana|url=http://www.dawn.com|title=LHC to hear arguments on petition against holding of Aurat March|date=February 24, 2020|work=Dawn|access-date=February 28, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  This petition was rejected by the Lahore High Court Chief Justice who underscored that freedom of expression could not be banned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/274596-aurat-march-in-lhc-chief-justice-says-cannot-ban-freedom-of-expression|title=Aurat March 2020: LHC Chief Justice says cannot ban freedom of expression|last=Riaz|first=Shakir|date=Feb 27, 2020|website=Geo TV|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=Feb 28, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":6\" />\n\nIn Lahore, marchers gathered outside the Press Club and passed through Egerton Road to culminate outside Aiwan-e-Iqbal. Participants were holding a plethora of placards. Despite the social media storm before the march, men were present in large numbers in support of the Aurat March. The participants delivered speeches and held placards and banners displaying thought-provoking slogans to raise the pressing issues of gender-based violence including sexual harassment and assault in the workplace, deep-rooted misogyny and the patriarchal mindset prevalent in the society. A resolution was submitted in Punjab Assembly by Kanwal Liaquat (MPA-PMLN), demanding an end to gender discrimination. The resolution condemned under-age marriages and demanded that women be granted legal, social and economic protection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2020/03/08/aurat-march-women-reclaim-public-spaces-on-their-day/|title=Aurat March: Women reclaim public spaces on their day|date=2019-03-09|website=Pakistan Today|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref>\n\n===Aurat Azadi March Islamabad===\nA petition was also filed in the Islamabad High Court to stop Aurat Azadi March 2020 which was rejected by Chief justice [[Athar Minallah]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Referring to religion, culture, Islamabad High Court tells us why Aurat March is necessary |url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/276002-referring-to-religion-culture-islamabad-high-court-tells-us-why-aurat-march-is-necessary |work=www.geo.tv}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ali |first1=Arshad |title=IHC reserves verdict on petition seeking stoppage of Aurat March |url=https://khybernews.tv/ihc-reserves-verdict-on-petition-seeking-stoppage-of-aurat-march/ |work=Khyber News -Official Website |date=6 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Islamabad High Court dismisses petition to stop Aurat March {{!}} SAMAA |url=https://www.samaa.tv/news/pakistan/2020/03/aurat-march-only-asks-for-rights-guaranteed-in-islam-court/ |work=Samaa TV}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Asad |first1=Malik |title=IHC rejects petitions seeking restrictions on Aurat March |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1538963 |work=DAWN.COM |date=7 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=IHC throws out petition seeking to stop Aurat March |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1538855 |work=DAWN.COM |date=6 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> On March 3, extremist mob vandalised, mural of two women painted by organizers of Aurat Azadi March Islamabad.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mahmood |first1=Aisha |title=Extremist mob vandalises mural of two women painted by Aurat March organizers |url=https://www.brecorder.com/2020/03/04/576922/lal-masjid-clerics-vandalise-mural-of-two-women-painted-by-aurat-march-organizers/ |work=Business Recorder |date=4 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Sirur |first1=Simrin |title=Pakistan prepares for Aurat Azadi March but Lal Masjid clerics call it obscene |url=https://theprint.in/go-to-pakistan/pakistan-prepares-for-aurat-azadi-march-but-lal-masjid-clerics-call-it-obscene/376073/ |work=ThePrint |date=5 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ali |first1=Kalbe |title=Jamia Hafsa students claim responsibility for defacing feminist mural in Islamabad |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1538478 |work=DAWN.COM |date=5 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Staff |first1=Images |title=Aurat March\u2019s beautiful mural was vandalised in Islamabad. Are men really that afraid? |url=https://images.dawn.com/news/1184784 |work=Images |date=5 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The organizers of march were given the no-objection certificate (NOC) after many days of negotiations and a range of unnecessarily strict conditions were applied in NOC.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Daur |first1=Naya |title=Aurat March Islamabad's NOC Comes With Strict Conditions |url=https://nayadaur.tv/2020/03/aurat-march-islamabads-noc-comes-with-strict-conditions/ |work=Naya Daur |date=7 March 2020}}</ref> On March 8, 2020, the Aurat March procession in Pakistan's capital Islamabad was attacked by religious extremists who were holding a counter-march to celebrate ''Haya'' or modesty. It was attended by women from the Jamaat-e-Islami, JUI-F, Lal Masjid, and female students of different seminaries including Jamiat Hafsa, staged as Haya March. Bricks, stones, shoes and sticks were hurled at the peaceful marchers on the Aurat March side, leaving several people injured.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.capradio.org/news/npr/story?storyid=813443312|title=International Women's Day: With Shoes And Stones, Islamists Disrupt Pakistan Rally|last=Javed|first=Diaa Hadid,Hina|website=www.capradio.org|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wkms.org/post/international-womens-day-rallies-see-some-violence|title=International Women&#039;s Day Rallies See Some Violence|website=www.wkms.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Staff |first1=Scroll |title=Watch: Protestors throw stones, sticks at the participants of Pakistan\u2019s 2020 \u2018Aurat March\u2019 |url=https://scroll.in/video/955596/watch-protestors-throw-stones-sticks-at-the-participants-of-pakistans-2020-aurat-march |work=Scroll.in}}</ref> Earlier even before the March, a van carrying newly-printed banners of Aurat March was stopped and driver beaten.<ref name=\":13\" /> During the March The BBC correspondent Irfana Yasser and her children were assaulted with chilli powder which temporarily blinded them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1539954|title=Aurat March organisers demand judicial probe into Islamabad stone pelting incident|last=Yasin|first=Aamir|date=2020-03-11|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> At least one media camera person hospitalized.<ref name=\":13\" /> Subsequently, the attack was stopped by the police authorities that were present, and the March continued forward despite the opposition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2020/03/08/religious-party-attacks-aurat-march-in-capital-several-injured/|title=Aurat March attacked with bricks, sticks in Islamabad| website=www.pakistantoday.com.pk|language=en|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweekpakistan.com/readying-for-the-aftermath/|title=Readying for the Aftermath|date=2020-03-11|website=Newsweek Pakistan|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> An FIR was registered against the men who attacked the march participants.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u0639\u0648\u0631\u062a \u0645\u0627\u0631\u0686: \u0627\u06cc\u0641 \u0622\u0626\u06cc \u0622\u0631 \u062f\u0631\u062c\u060c \u067e\u062a\u06be\u0631\u0627\u0624 \u06a9\u0627 \u0630\u06a9\u0631 \u0646\u06c1\u06cc\u06ba |url=https://www.bbc.com/urdu/pakistan-51797397 |work=BBC News \u0627\u0631\u062f\u0648 |date=9 March 2020 |language=ur}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Case registered against men who attacked Islamabad Aurat March {{!}} SAMAA |url=https://www.samaa.tv/news/pakistan/2020/03/case-registered-against-men-who-attacked-islamabad-aurat-march/ |work=Samaa TV}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Reporter |first1=The Newspaper's Staff |title=35 booked for trying to disrupt Aurat Azadi March |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1539738 |work=DAWN.COM |date=10 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Aurat Azadi March Quetta ===\n2020 Aurat Azadi March in Quetta  Balochistan began from and returned to the Quetta press club, was organized  by the Women's Alliance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2020/03/08/aurat-march-women-reclaim-public-spaces-on-their-day/|title=Aurat March: Women reclaim public spaces on their day - Pakistan Today|website=www.pakistantoday.com.pk|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2172005/1-aurat-march-held-quetta/|title=\u2018Aurat March\u2019 held in Quetta|last=Tribune.com.pk|date=2020-03-09|website=The Express Tribune|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>Along with rest of social discrimination issues, end of previous year i.e. 2019 was noted with exposing of security establishment and University administration officials of  Balochistan University had secretly installed cameras in washrooms and student meeting areas and blackmailing students for years together.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesofbalochistan.com/baloch-women-and-aurat-march/|title=Baloch Women and Aurat March|date=2020-03-05|website=Times Of Balochistan|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1513829|title=Balochistan University scandal: Students demand removal of FC posts, restoration of union|last=Nihad|first=Ghalib|date=2019-10-30|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2019/11/19/balochistan-university-scandal-underlines-marginalisation-of-the-province/|title=Balochistan University scandal underlines marginalisation of province - Pakistan Today|website=www.pakistantoday.com.pk|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n===Women's Day Songs===\n\n[[File:Aurat March 2020 a.jpg|thumb|Women dance to Laal Meri at the Aurat March, Karachi]]\n\nAs preparation of upcoming 8 March 2020 Aurat March, released and subsequently performed<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/576223/when-you-have-to-stone-us-into-submission/|title=When you have to stone us into submission|date=2020-03-14|website=Daily Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> at the march a song 'tum ho rapist' an Urdu version of the feminist anthem 'Un Violador en Tu Camino' \u2014 or '[[A Rapist in Your Path]]'. While 'A Rapist in Your Path' is based on Argentinian [[Anthropology|anthropologist]] Rita Laura Segato's work and created by Valparaiso feminist collective, Las Tesis, [[Chile]]; Urdu version has been localized with  relevant issues of Pakistan by mentioning [[Feudalism in Pakistan|feudalism]] as part of the Pakistani [[patriarchy]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/270338-aurat-march-drops-urdu-version-of-anti-rape-anthem-ahead-of-2020-rally|title=Aurat March drops Urdu version of anti-rape anthem ahead of 2020 rally|website=www.geo.tv|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/608036-aurat-march-releases-urdu-version-of-chilean-protest-song|title=Aurat March releases Urdu version of Chilean protest song|website=www.thenews.com.pk|language=en|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref> Aurat March  also released & sung one more anthem song \"Hum Inquilab Hain\" (We are Revolution)<ref name=\":13\" /> Song \"Hum Inquilab Hain\" is written by  [[Ismat Shahjahan]], composed by [[Ammar Rashid]] song is sung in chorus by &nbsp; Areej Hussain, [[Ammar Rashid]], Huda Bhurgri, [[Ismat Shahjahan]], Ayesha Khan, and Shahzadi Hussain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dnd.com.pk/international-womens-day-hum-inquilab-hain-we-are-revolution/183551|title=International Women's Day: HUM INQUILAB HAIN--- We are Revolution|last=Desk|first=Central News|date=2020-03-07|website=Dispatch News Desk|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> A Canadian-Pakistani singer Sophia Jamil (pseudonym:Fifi) too released her song 'Mera Jism Meri Marzi' (My body My Choice) on YouTube.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/282583-young-singer-talks-womens-rights-in-new-song-mera-jism-meri-marzi|title=Young singer talks women's rights in new song 'Mera Jism Meri Marzi'|website=www.geo.tv|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bolnews.com/entertainment/2020/03/artist-highlights-womens-issues-by-her-song-mera-jism-meri-marzi/|title=Artist highlights women's issues by her song Mera Jism Meri Marzi|date=2020-03-13|website=BOL News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2176711/4-female-rapper-releases-song-mera-jism-meri-marzi-clarify-really-means/|title=Female rapper releases song 'Mera Jism Meri Marzi' to clarify what it really means|last=Tribune.com.pk|date=2020-03-15|website=The Express Tribune|language=en|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\n===Propaganda against women march===\n[[File:Aurat March 2020 b.jpg|thumb| Meri Zindagi Mera Haq, Meri Zindagi Mera Ikhtiyar (My life is my right and I should have the power to make decisions about my life)]]\n\nAs International Women's Day came nearer the hard line conservatives in Pakistan increasingly got impatient and intolerant, and took to mainstream media and online social media alleging Pakistani feminists of encouraging unIslamic vulgarity by raising slogans that hinted that a woman had the right to do as she pleased. Conservatives further threatened participants when feminists clarified that they would rightfully own up and support pro-rights, pro-choice slogan [[Mera Jism Meri Marzi]] (My body my choice). Aurat March participants insisted that there is nothing vulgar in asking their rights; besides it is societal duplicity in Pakistan that besides open display of sexual harassment of women, adverts of 'Mardana Kamzori' (discussing masculine sexuality) are openly displayed, sexualized abusive linguistic commonly used, online search histories of many men would show wide porn consumption, word 'Aurat' itself originally talks of women body in wide use; but when it comes to better awareness and women's rights their slogans are thought to be inappropriate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/626184-haya-march-to-counter-aurat-march-in-pakistan-women-march-for-rights-all-over-the-world|title=Haya march to counter Aurat march in Pakistan: Women march for rights all over the world|website=www.thenews.com.pk|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Aurat March 2020 c.jpg|thumb|Two marchers holding placards \"Meray Paas Mein Hoon\" (I am with myself) and Inquilab bhi Aurat ka kaam hay (Making revolution is women's task)]]\nAs pro-Aurat March hashtags trended on Twitter, including that of Mera Jism Meri Marzi (My body my choice), cultural and intellectual clashes happened in mainstream media.<ref>{{cite news |title=Aurat March placards turn up the heat against Khalilur Rehman |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2172262/4-aurat-march-placards-turn-heat-khalilur-rehman/ |newspaper=The Express Tribune |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> Online social media eventually did show off-line impact.<ref name=\":13\" /> In an analysis of opposing Twitter trends by ''Rizvan Saeed'' it emerged that #WeRejectMeraJismMeriMarzi and #HayaMarch were most likely organic few other hashtags which were trended on Twitter like #AmirLiaqat_Laanti #\u0627\u06cc\u06a9\u0633\u067e\u0627\u0626\u0631_\u06a9\u06be\u0633\u0631\u06d2 (roughly translates into \"expired eunuchs.\")\n\n<nowiki>#</nowiki>\u0641\u062d\u0627\u0634\u06cc_\u0645\u0627\u0631\u0686_\u0646\u0627\u0645\u0646\u0638\u0648\u0631 (Roughly translated as \"Vulgar March Unacceptable\") were inorganically propagated by limited number of individual groups of vested conservative interests including groups affiliated with ultra conservative Tehreek-e-Labaik Pakistan to trend anti-Aurat March memes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.samaa.tv/opinion/2020/03/was-opposition-to-aurat-march-real-or-manufactured/|title=Was opposition to Aurat March real or manufactured? {{!}} SAMAA|website=Samaa TV|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\nIn the run up to 2020 march, polity in Pakistan started drawing subtle political lines either favoring or distancing from the march in various degrees. Ultra-conservatives claimed Islam is already the most feminist religion and has secured all the rights to women, so they need not have any more demands, but need to go back and adopt more of the modest culture expected of [[Muslim women]]. These people arranged counter 'Haya' (modesty) marches to stop Aurat March with the slogan \"Our bodies, Allah's choice\".<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/626184-haya-march-to-counter-aurat-march-in-pakistan-women-march-for-rights-all-over-the-world|title=Haya march to counter Aurat march in Pakistan: Women march for rights all over the world|website=www.thenews.com.pk|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> Erstwhile Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif's Muslim league party (PML-N),  while it did not oppose Aurat March openly, cautioned marchers not to cross Islamic cultural markers. Contemporary Prime Minister [[Imran Khan]]'s government, ruled by his Pakistan Tekreek-i-Insaf (which had buckled under pressure to the ultra-conservative groups a month earlier which created violent ruckus while opposing Aurat March in Islamabad) while formally supporting march connected religio-cultural appropriateness of slogans of the march with national honor. Subsequently, after the Aurat March took place, Prime Minister Imran Khan expressed criticism of the lack of uniform education which would have educated marchers better.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweekpakistan.com/imran-khan-blames-education-system-for-aurat-march-culture/|title=Imran Khan Blames Education System for Aurat March \u2018Culture\u2019|date=2020-03-12|website=Newsweek Pakistan|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> The left-of-center Pakistan Peoples Party was more welcoming of Aurat March. Mustafa Nawaz Khokhar, the Senator representing PPP, criticized Prime Minister Imran Khan and his party to be favoring ultra-conservative and PML-N and PTI positions as an undeclared anti-women alliance. PPP were replied back opponents by pointing out lacuna on their side.<ref name=\":11\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1538978|title=Govt to support Aurat March with strings attached|last=Reporter|first=The Newspaper's Staff|date=2020-03-07|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> Janita Tahir noted that participants of Aurat March are questioning Imran Khan while he speaks so much for human rights for minorities world over, is he doing enough for human rights of half the population of Pakistan which finds itself in weaker position?<ref name=\":12\" /> Farzana Rasheed further asks in her article that why Pakistan can't be Islamic republic & free at the same time? She further questions contradictions of Imran Khan & Pakistan's conservative polity that instigates and condones extremist violence same time claiming to be democratic and peaceful and that they do not support violence but understand sentiment behind it, as usual victim blaming non violent women's protest for the violence committed on them.<ref name=\":13\" />\n\n=== Posters & slogans 2020 ===\n[[File:Aurat March 2020 d.jpg|thumb]]\nThe  8 March 2020's slogans also included slogans like, \"Saying [[Mashallah]] does not make your [[harassment]] [[halal]]\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stepfeed.com/this-arab-girl-shut-down-halal-harassment-in-the-most-savage-way-1194|title=This Arab girl shut down 'halal harassment' in the most savage way|last=Khalife|first=Leyal|date=2017-10-05|website=StepFeed|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\":14\" />, \"Domestic violence kills more than [[Coronavirus disease 2019|corona]]\", \"I march so one day my daughters won't have to\", \"IMAGINE Not Loving The Women in your Life Enough To Advocate For Their Rights\"<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/276444-the-men-of-aurat-march-and-their-posters|title=The men of Aurat March (and their posters)|website=www.geo.tv|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/626541-these-posters-made-by-male-allies-will-get-you-thinking-about-aurat-march-demands|title=Men of Aurat March and their plea for us to think|website=www.thenews.com.pk|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nSupportive gents did hold placards like, \"I am surrounded by the opposite gender and I feel safe. 'I want same for them'\", \"Proud husband of a feminist, proud father of a feminist, proud feminist\", \"I will be a proud 'jorru ka ghulam\" (I will be proud, being called 'wife's slave' - south Asian misogynist patriarchal culture frequently uses the [[pejorative]] term 'jorru ka ghulam\"- wife's slave- to men who give an ear to their spouse) <ref name=\":14\" /><ref name=\":15\" />\n\n== See also ==\n{{div col}}\n* [[All Pakistan Women's Association]]\n* [[Aurat Foundation]]\n* [[Blue Veins (Pakistan)|Blue Veins]]\n* [[Feminism in Pakistan]]\n* [[Girls at Dhabas]]\n* [[Me Too movement (Pakistan)]]\n* [[Mera Jism Meri Marzi]]\n* [[Pakistan Federation of Business And Professional Women]]\n* [[Rape in Pakistan]]\n* [[Violence against women in Pakistan]]\n* [[Women in Islam]]\n* [[Women in Pakistan]]\n* [[Women's Action Forum]]\n* [[Women's Protection Bill]]\n* [[Women's rights]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline}}\n*{{official|https://auratmarch.com/ }}\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sJ7WgoLNIXU Hum Inquilab Hain] - Feminist Anthem  (YouTube link)\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pOavNaBX4NU&feature=emb_logo Mera Jism Meri Marzi]  Feminist song  (YouTube link)\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sJ7WgoLNIXU Aur Woh Rapist Ho Tum] - Chile Feminist Anthem in Urdu language (YouTube link)\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n\n\n[[Category:Women's movements based in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Women's rights in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Feminism in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Feminist movements and ideologies]]\n[[Category:Socialism in Pakistan| ]]\n", "name_user": "Bookku", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWomen's March 2019:Internal links [[]]", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aurat_March"}
