{"title_page": "Rayleigh, Essex", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{infobox UK place\n| country = England\n| official_name= Rayleigh\n| static_image_name= High st from church.jpg\n| static_image_caption=Rayleigh High Street as seen from the top of Holy Trinity Church, 2003\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.5864|0.6049|display=inline,title}}\n| os_grid_reference = TQ805907\n| population = 32,150\n| population_ref = ''(2011)''<ref name=ONS/>\n| civil_parish = Rayleigh  <ref>http://www.rayleightowncouncil.gov.uk/</ref>\n| shire_district = [[Rochford (district)|Rochford]]\n| shire_county = [[Essex]]\n| region = East of England\n| constituency_westminster = [[Rayleigh and Wickford (UK Parliament constituency)|Rayleigh and Wickford]]\n| post_town = RAYLEIGH\n| postcode_district = SS6\n| postcode_area = SS\n| dial_code = 01268\n}}\n'''Rayleigh''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|r|e\u026a|l|i\u02d0}} is a market town and [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] in the [[Rochford (district)|District of Rochford]] in Essex, England, located between [[Chelmsford, Essex|Chelmsford]] and [[Southend-on-Sea]]. It lies {{convert|32|mi|km}} to the east of central London. It had a population of 30,196 in 2001,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/viewFullDataset.do?instanceSelection=03070&productId=779&$ph=60_61&datasetInstanceId=3070&startColumn=1&numberOfColumns=8&containerAreaId=790394 |title=Census 2001 |publisher=Neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref> increasing to 32,150 at the census 2011.<ref name=ONS>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11127854&c=Rayleigh&d=16&e=62&g=6425548&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1443020385069&enc=1|title=Town population 2015|accessdate=23 September 2015|publisher=Office for National Statistics| work=Neighbourhood Statistics}}</ref>\n\n==Toponymy==\nThe name ''Rayleigh'' is [[Old English]] in origin deriving from ''r\u01e3ge'' ('female roe-deer or she-goat') and ''l\u0113ah'' ('clearing'). Therefore, the name means overall 'wood or clearing of the wild she-goats or roe-deer\".<ref>''The Cambridge Dictionary of English Place Names'', ed. by Victor Watts (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2004).</ref><ref>[[#refRcshistory|Rayleigh Civic Society 2006]]</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Prehistoric and Roman times===\nThere has been a scattering of stray finds around the town from Prehistoric and Roman times, including some Roman roof and [[hypocaust]] tiles found within the fabric of Rayleigh Church. This suggests that there was a Roman habitation site within the area. However, there is little evidence of any density of population here during this period.<ref>[[#refHistoricassess|Historic Town Assessment Report for Rayleigh, 1999]], pages 3 and 7.</ref>\n\n===Saxon era===\nOne significant archaeological find was in the early 2000s at the western edge of Rayleigh, at the site of the former Park School in Rawreth Lane. An early Saxon cemetery site was discovered here, with 144 cremation burials and evidence of just one high-status female inhumation burial.<ref>Essex County Council [http://unlockingessex.essexcc.gov.uk/uep/custom_pages/monument_detail.asp?content_page_id=68&previous_page_id=48&monument_id=1035613 Unlocking Essex's Past]. SMR Number 45134.</ref>\n\nBy the end of the Saxon period, there was definitely a village here, as it is recorded in the [[Domesday Book]], when it was held by Swein of Essex, the son of [[Robert FitzWimarc]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://opendomesday.org/place/TQ8090/Rayleigh/ |title=RAYLEIGH |publisher=OPEN DOMESDAY |date= |accessdate=2019-01-09}}</ref>\n\nThe most significant historic monument in Rayleigh is the great medieval mound of [[Rayleigh Castle]]. This was an early Norman [[motte and bailey]] castle, of which only the motte and its surrounding embankments remain. Despite the loss of its timber superstructure and later stone buildings, its height and bulk mean that it still dominates the town centre.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/rayleigh-mount/features/the-castle-at-rayleigh-mount |title=The castle at Rayleigh Mount |publisher=National Trust |date= |accessdate=9 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Later medieval period (1154\u20131485)===\nA [[courthouse]] was erected in Rayleigh in 1338. This was apparently resented by the townspeople, who turned out in force to destroy it, with 20 [[Leadership|ringleaders]] later arrested and tried.<ref>[[#refBurrows1909|Burrows 1909]], p.31.</ref>\n\nThe forests around Rayleigh were royal hunting grounds. It is recorded that [[Henry III of England|King Henry III]] hunted here in 1222, and three King Edwards also visited.<ref>[[#refBurrows1909|Burrows 1909]], p.27.</ref>\n\nOne of the oldest secular building in Rayleigh is 91 High Street which houses Pizza Express downstairs and [[Rayleigh Town Museum]] upstairs. The Regal Room in the museum is dated circa 1350. It is suspected that some of Rayleigh's older Brick build buildings may contain portions older than this.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rochford.gov.uk/sites/default/files/planning_historic_environment_rayleigh_town_assess.pdf |title=Rayleigh Historic Town Project Assessment Report |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=9 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nRayleigh Castle gradually fell into disuse, and in 1394 [[King Richard II]] gave permission for the townspeople of Rayleigh to use the foundations as a source of stone. By this time, the site was in royal ownership and used for pasture:\n: know all men of special grace who have the will to repair certain Chapel in the said town and to build a new a certain [[Bell tower|belfry]] we have granted them the foundations and to take away and use any stones found theren\".<ref>[[#refRcschurch|Rayleigh Civic Society 2006]], Holy Trinity Church</ref>\n\n===Tudors and Stuarts===\nRecords indicate that the church was rich in plate, vestments and [[stained glass]], but these were disposed of:\n: \"No church within the hundred was more splendidly adorned; none were so richly furnished with plate, vestments and other accessories for the celebration of the divine service; none were so rich in painted glass; none have been more mercilessly despoiled\"<ref>[[#refBurrows1909|Burrows 1909]], p.303.</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Burrows|first=John William|url=http://archive.org/details/southendonseadis00burriala|title=Southend-on-Sea and district: historical notes ..|date=1909|publisher=Southend-on-Sea : J.H. Burrows|others=University of California Libraries}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[Henry VIII]]'s reign, deer were constantly taken from here to replenish the herds in [[Greenwich Park]].<ref>[[#refBurrows1909|Burrows 1909]], pp. 28 58.</ref>\n\n===Modern===\n[[Image:Rayleigh sign.gif|thumb|right|Rayleigh Sign]]\nDuring the 1990s many new housing estates appeared on formerly greenfield areas of the town, with the [[East of England]] region currently pushing for even more homes to be built in the area. This has caused some controversy locally, with residents of Rayleigh feeling that the areas surrounding the town should be preserved with more care.<ref>[[#refPercival|Overwhelming objections to homes plan]], 2007, Southend Echo.</ref>\n\n==Governance==\n\nThe civil parish of Rayleigh became part of [[Rochford Rural District]] in 1894.  In 1929 it was combined with [[Rawreth]] to form the Urban District of Rayleigh, which was abolished in 1974 when the area became part of the District of Rochford.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10245692 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20121224061101/http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10245692 |url-status=dead |archive-date=24 December 2012 |title=A Vision of Britain Through Time : Rayleigh Civil Parish |publisher=Visionofbritain.org.uk |accessdate=13 August 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe constituency of [[Rayleigh and Wickford (UK Parliament constituency)|Rayleigh and Wickford]] is represented in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] by the Member of Parliament [[Mark Francois]] of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]].<ref>[https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/mark-francois/1444 \"Rt Hon Mark Francois MP], Parliament.uk, accessed 8 January 2018.</ref>\n\nIn 2018 Rochford District Council has 25 Conservative members, 3 Liberal Democrats, 3 Green Party, 2 Labour, 4 independents and 4 members from Rochford Residents Party sitting on the council.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/topics/cz3nmpgw3zgt/rochford-district-council |title=Rochford District Council |publisher=BBC |date= |accessdate=2019-01-09}}</ref>\n\nRayleigh Town council is also Conservative controlled, comprising 18 Conservatives, 4 Liberal Democrats, and 1 independent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rayleightowncouncil.gov.uk/upload/files/Councillors/new%20version%20for%20ward%20councillors%20-photos%20and%20information.pdf|title=Rayleigh Town Council}}</ref>\n\nRayleigh Town Council have major responsibilities which include:\n*Consultee on Planning applications in Rayleigh.\n*Christmas Lights and organisation of switch-on event in Town Centre, King George V Playing Field in Eastwood Road, floral displays in Town Centre and entry to Annual [[Anglia in Bloom]] competition, [[CCTV]] in Town Centre, benches, salt bins, litter bins, bus shelters, some street lighting, heritage and memorial plaques, and the Town Centre clock.\n*Four Allotment sites within Rayleigh with over 100 plots\n*Consultee on crime & disorder reduction strategy within Rochford District Member of Rayleigh Windmill management committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.essexinfo.net/rayleightowncouncil/ |title=Rayleigh Town Council |publisher=Essexinfo.net |date= |accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Civic Suite and Information Centre includes the Council Chamber, Committee Rooms, Transportation and Hackney Carriage Office and is located on Hockley Road.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rochford.gov.uk/contact-us-3 |title=contact us |publisher=Rochford Council |accessdate=2019-01-09}}</ref>  The Citizens Advice Bureau and Registrar's Office are also located here.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.citizensadvicerochford.org.uk/our-offices.html |title=our offices |publisher=CAB |accessdate=2019-01-09}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nRayleigh is served by two prominent modes of public transport; bus and train. The bus services are run by [[Arriva Southend]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arrivabus.co.uk/southend |title=Arriva Southend |publisher=Arriva |accessdate=2019-01-09}}</ref> and [[First Essex]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bustimes.org/operators/first-in-essex|title=Bus Times |publisher=First |accessdate=2019-01-09}}</ref> and usually terminate at [[Rayleigh railway station]]. [[Greater Anglia]] run the rail line which leads from [[Southend Victoria railway station|Southend Victoria]] to [[Liverpool Street railway station|London Liverpool Street]], stopping at Rayleigh, running every 10 minutes during rush hour.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.greateranglia.co.uk|title=Great Anglia |publisher=Great Anglia |accessdate=2019-01-09}}</ref> First Essex also operate an hourly coach service to [[Stansted Airport]], numbered X30, which makes a stop at Rayleigh railway station.<ref>https://www.firstgroup.com/essex/airport-services/x30</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstgroup.com/essex/airport-services/x30|title=X30 |publisher=first group |accessdate=2019-01-09}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n[[Image:Rayleigh High Street.JPG|thumb|right|Looking up the High Street towards the church.]]\n\nRayleigh has two secondary schools: [[Sweyne Park School]], formed by the amalgamation of the Sweyne and Park schools, and [[FitzWimarc School]]. It also has seven primary schools \u2013 Down Hall, Edward Francis, Grove Wood, Our Lady of Ransom (Catholic), Rayleigh Primary and Wyburns. The seventh, Glebe Primary School with UHI, was created in September 2014 through the amalgamation\nof Glebe Infant and Nursery School and Glebe Junior School.<ref>{{cite web|title=Glebe Primary Prospectus|url=http://www.glebeprimary.essex.sch.uk/prospectus/|accessdate=30 October 2014}}</ref> In addition, St Nicholas C of E Primary School, a long-established school for the adjoining village of Rawreth, moved in 2006 to a new building just on the Rayleigh side of the parish boundary.<ref>http://www.st-nicholassch.co.uk/the-history-of-our-school/</ref>\n\n==Sports and recreation==\nRayleigh has a golf club on the outskirts of the town; Rayleigh Club (previously Lords Golf & Country Club) is situated on Hullbridge Road to the north of the town.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/589832 |title=photo |publisher=Geograph.org.uk |date= |accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Parks/playing fields===\n\nRayleigh has a number of parks and playing fields.\n\n====King George V Playing Field====\n\nLocated next to Bull Lane, Hockley Road and Websters Way.<ref>http://www.rayleightowncouncil.gov.uk/king-george-v-playing-field/</ref>\n\nIt contains a snack bar and pavilion. As well as a \"Teen\" shelter\n\nIts two grass football pitches are used by Rayleigh FC, Chronicles FC and Ralee FC. It also has a skate park<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rayleightowncouncil.ultx.ovh/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/King%20George%20V%20Playing%20Field%20Management%20Plan.pdf/ |title=King George V Playing Field page 7 |publisher=Rayleigh Town Council |date= |accessdate=2019-01-10}}</ref> and a children's playground, containing a variety of play equipment. The park is also home to Rayleigh Bowls Club (who lease the use of the Pavilion).\n\nRayleigh Lions holds an annual fireworks display on the playing field.<ref>http://www.leightimes.co.uk/article.cfm?id=119719&headline=Rayleigh%20Lions%20Fireworks&sectionIs=news&searchyear=2018</ref>\n\n====Sweyne Park====\n[[Image:Sweyne park sign.jpg|thumb]]\n\nSweyne Park is controlled by Rochford District Council. It is situated north of Sweyne Park School and can be accessed in several ways. The entrance in Downhall Park Way has a small car park, and there is a play area. It has another smaller entrance in Downhall Park Way, adjacent to Canterbury Close. It can also be accessed from Victoria Avenue. In 2008 an entrance was established from Priory Chase. The park has a pond.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/585025 |title=Sweyne Park Pond:: OS grid TQ7991 :: Geograph Britain and Ireland \u2013 photograph every grid square! |publisher=Geograph.org.uk |date=15 October 2007 |accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref> It has a [[bridleway]] running round its perimeter of about {{convert|2|km|mi|abbr=on}}.\n\n* Fairview Playing Field, Victoria Road TQ814914\n* Grove Playing Field, Grove Road TQ825904\n* John Fisher Playing Field (Little Wheatleys Chase, Rayleigh) TQ789914\n\nKingley Wood stands on a steep hill slope beside the A127 and is visible as you approach Rayleigh from London. The small wood is the only surviving ancient wood in Rayleigh, but it has rich and varied [[wildlife]] and a well-documented history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rochford.gov.uk/leisure_and_tourism/woodlands_and_parks/kingley_woods.aspx  |title=Woodlands, Parks and Open Spaces &#124; Kingley Woods |publisher=Rochford.gov.uk |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724164610/http://www.rochford.gov.uk/leisure_and_tourism/woodlands_and_parks/kingley_woods.aspx |archivedate=24 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/598305 |title=Kingley Wood photo |publisher=Geograph.org.uk |date= |accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n====Wheatley Wood====\nThis is a {{convert|64|acre|ha|adj=on}} broadleaved wood established in the late 1990s.\nThe wood was designed and planted by a partnership of Local people and the [[Woodland Trust]].\nThere is a car park at the Grange Community Centre in Little Wheatley Chase, and access to the wood is across the playing fields.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/601857 |title=photo |publisher=Geograph.org.uk |date= |accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Greyhounds and speedway===\nAt least two [[Greyhound racing in the United Kingdom|greyhound racing]] tracks existed in the town. The main venue was the [[Rayleigh Weir Stadium]] which also hosted [[Motorcycle speedway|speedway]] and traded from 1948-1974.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.old-maps.co.uk/#/Map/580650/189412/12/100954|title=OS Plan 1955|publisher=old-maps.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nA smaller short lived track at O'Tooles Meadow, Wickford Road, off the Down Hall Road also hosted greyhound racing and dirt track speedway. The racing was independent (not affiliated to the sports governing body the [[National Greyhound Racing Club]]) and was known as a flapping track, which was the nickname given to independent tracks.<ref>{{cite book|last=Barnes|first=Julia|title=Daily Mirror Greyhound Fact File, page 419|year=1988|publisher=Ringpress Books|isbn=0-948955-15-5}}</ref> The track opened in 1932 but the date of closure is not known<ref>{{cite web|url=https://greyhoundracingtimes.co.uk/2019/04/28/rayleigh-otooles/|title=Rayleigh O'Tooles|publisher=Greyhound Racing Times}}</ref> and it is possible that it may have been the same venue known as the Rayleigh Sports Stadium although it is also possible that the Rayleigh Sports Stadium may have been a third separate venue.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://greyhoundracingtimes.co.uk/2019/04/28/rayleigh-sports-stadium/|title=Rayleigh Sports Stadium|publisher=Greyhound Racing Times}}</ref>\n\n==Public facilities==\n[[Image:Post Office, Rayleigh.jpg|thumb|left|Former Post Office in Rayleigh.]] [[Image:Rayleigh Windmill at night.jpg|thumb|left|[[Rayleigh Windmill]]]]\n\nThere is a small outdoor market on Wednesdays. Until 2011 it was located next to Rayleigh Civic Suite and Information Centre, opposite Holy Trinity Church. In 2011 it moved to the taxi rank in the town's High Street (outside Boots).\nThe market dates back to before 1181 when it was inscribed in the Exchequer Records of Henry II.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rochford.gov.uk/leisure__tourism/district_tour/rayleigh.aspx |title=Rayleigh |work=Rochford District Council |accessdate=9 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615130432/http://www.rochford.gov.uk/leisure__tourism/district_tour/rayleigh.aspx |archivedate=15 June 2011  }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Dutch Cottage]], the smallest and oldest council house in the United Kingdom, can be visited on Wednesdays by prior appointment.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news | last = | first = | author2 = | title = Smallest council house for rent | work = | pages = | language = | publisher = BBC News | date = 14 July 2008 | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/go/homepage/d/int/news/top/8/-/news/1/hi/uk/7504801.stm | accessdate = }}</ref>\n\n[[Rayleigh Windmill]] has been renovated, including a structural renovation of the 19th century brick built building has now been completed. The basic external brickwork has been repaired and the interior has been transformed to provide four storeys of modern display facilities which has turned the windmill into a major tourist and educational attraction in the county. The changes to the windmill allow the public to view the interior and to exploit this local historic amenity for cultural, educational and tourism use.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rochford.gov.uk/leisure__tourism/events_and_attractions/rayleigh_windmill.aspx |title=Rayleigh Windmill |work=Rochford District Council |accessdate=9 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100819100655/http://www.rochford.gov.uk/leisure__tourism/events_and_attractions/rayleigh_windmill.aspx |archivedate=19 August 2010  }}</ref>\n\nRayleigh Mount, a National Trust property adjacent to Rayleigh Windmill, is the site of a Domesday castle erected by Sweyn of Essex with distinctive [[motte-and-bailey]] defences. From its summit it offers sweeping views across the Crouch Valley.<ref>{{cite web |author=ser |url=http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-vh/w-visits/w-findaplace/w-rayleighmount/ |title=Rayleigh Mount |publisher=National Trust |date=17 November 2005 |accessdate=13 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629041245/http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-vh/w-visits/w-findaplace/w-rayleighmount/ |archivedate=29 June 2011  }}</ref>\n\n===Rayleigh Town Museum===\n[[Rayleigh Town Museum]] occupies the  1st floor at 91 High Street and contains many artifacts telling the history of Rayleigh.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.echo-news.co.uk/news/14251208.rayleigh-historical-museum-to-open-in-april/|title=Rayleigh historical museum to open in April|last=Drake|first=Kristina|date=4 February 2016|website=Echo|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Religion==\n[[Image:Holy Trinity Church Rayleigh.jpg|thumb|right|Holy Trinity parish church]]\nThe [[Church of England parish church]] of the [[Trinity|Holy Trinity]] is at the top of the High Street.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parishofrayleigh.org.uk |title=Parish of Rayleigh Website |publisher=Parishofrayleigh.org.uk |date= |accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref> A church existed on the site in Saxon times and the present building has a [[Norman architecture|Norman]] [[chancel]]. The [[bell tower]] was built in the 15th century and includes stone taken from the castle when that fell into disuse. The church has an impressive [[Tudor architecture|Tudor]] brick porch. The [[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic Revival architect]] [[Clapton Crabb Rolfe|C.C. Rolfe]] restored the chancel in 1873.<ref>Saint, 1970</ref>\n\nThe parish church of [[Michael (archangel)|Saint Michael]] and All Angels is in Sir Walter Raleigh Drive near Sweyne School. It was built in the 1950s when Rayleigh expanded considerably. It has a multi-purpose building which is used by other local groups as well as the church.<ref>Our Lady of Ransom Catholic Church</ref>\n\nOur Lady of Ransom Catholic Church is on London Hill.<ref>http://www.olorchurch.org.uk/home/index.html</ref>\n\nThe United Reformed Church is on Crown Hill.<ref>https://www.christchurchrayleigh.org.uk/</ref>\n\nThe Baptist Church is in the High Street. The building opened for worship on 25 March 1799, shortly before the first Pastor, Rev James Pilkington, was inducted in June 1799. In June 1979, work started on a church extension. This added significantly more seating and completed some much needed repairs.<ref>http://www.rayleighbaptist.org.uk/</ref>\n\n[[Image:RayleighMethodistChurch.jpg|thumb|right|Rayleigh Methodist Church]]\nThe Methodist Church is on Eastwood Road. (Moved from the High Street in 1934).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rayleighmethodistchurch.org.uk |title=Rayleigh Methodist church Website |publisher=rayleighmethodistchurch.org.uk |date= |accessdate=21 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nGrange Free Church is on London Road, at the junction with Langdon Road.<ref>http://rayleighchurches.org.uk/grange-free-church/</ref>\n\nThe Salvation Army are located on the corner of the High Street and Love Lane. The building was the original 1884 Methodist Church, which was sold to the Salvation Army in 1934 when the Methodist Church moved to a larger site in Eastwood Road.<ref>https://www.salvationarmy.org.uk/rayleigh</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:Rayleigh hs 100209.jpg|Rayleigh High Street looking towards Holy Trinity Church.\nImage:Rayleigh sign 1.jpg|Rayleigh sign outside Rayleigh Lanes Indoor Market.\nImage:Map rayleigh.jpg|Map of Rayleigh Town Centre. Found on wall near the Millennium Clock.\nImage:Millennium clock rayleigh.jpg|Side of the Millennium Clock looking towards the Police Station.\nImage:Ye olde crown rayleigh.jpg|Ye Olde Crown.\nImage:Spread rayleigh.jpg|Spread Eagle.\nImage:White horse rayleigh.jpg|Old White Horse.\nImage:RayleighMethodistChurch.jpg|Rayleigh Methodist church from Eastwood Road.\nImage:Rayleigh Town Museum 190916.jpg|91 High Street in Rayleigh.\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* <cite id=refBurrows1909>Burrows, John William. (1909). ''Southend on Sea and District: Historical Notes''. {{ISBN|0-85409-642-6}}.</cite>\n* <cite id=refEpns>English Place-Name Society. (2008). [http://www.nottingham.ac.uk/english/ins/kepn/detailpop.php?placeno=12321 ''The Survey of English Place-Names: Rayleigh'']. Institute for Name-Studies. Retrieved 2008-06-28.</cite>\n* <cite id=refHistoricassess>Essex County Council. (1999). [http://www.essexcc.gov.uk/vip8/ecc/ECCWebsite/content/binaries/documents/Planning396/rayleigh_1999_historic_towns_assessment_report.pdf ''Historic Town Assessment Report for Rayleigh'']. Retrieved 2008-06-28</cite>\n* <cite id=refPercival>Percival, Geoff. (2007-06-05). [http://www.echo-news.co.uk/search/display.var.1523045.0.overwhelming_objections_to_homes_plan.php work= ''Overwhelming objections to homes plan'']. Southend Echo. Retrieved 2008-06-28.</cite>\n*{{Cite book |author=Pevsner, Nikolaus |authorlink=Nikolaus Pevsner |author2= |title=[[The Buildings of England]]: Essex |year=1965 |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |location=Harmondsworth |isbn= |pages=}}\n* <cite id=refRcshistory>Rayleigh Civic Society. (2006). [https://web.archive.org/web/20080509065035/http://www.rayleighbusiness.co.uk/history.asp ''History of Rayleigh'']. Rayleigh Chamber of Trade and Commerce. Retrieved 2008-06-28.</cite>\n* <cite id=refRcschurch>Rayleigh Civic Society. (2006). [https://web.archive.org/web/20080517120459/http://www.rayleighbusiness.co.uk/holytrinitychurch.asp ''Holy Trinity Church'']. Rayleigh Chamber of Trade and Commerce. Retrieved 2008-06-28.</cite>\n*{{cite journal |last=Saint |first=Andrew |year=1970 |title=Three Oxford Architects |journal=Oxoniensia |publisher=[[Oxfordshire Architectural and Historical Society]] |volume=XXXV |pages=53 ff |url=http://www.oahs.org.uk/oxo/vol%2035/Saint.doc |accessdate=3 November 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928030922/http://www.oahs.org.uk/oxo/vol%2035/Saint.doc |archive-date=28 September 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.rayleightownmuseum.co.uk Rayleigh Town Museum]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080509065035/http://www.rayleighbusiness.co.uk/history.asp Rayleigh Chamber of Trade- Section on Rayleigh's history]\n*[http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/rayleigh-mount/ National Trust \u2013 Rayleigh Mount]\n\n{{Essex}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rayleigh, Essex| ]]\n[[Category:Market towns in Essex]]\n[[Category:Rochford District]]\n[[Category:Towns in Essex]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{infobox UK place\n| country = England\n| official_name= Rayleigh\n| static_image_name= High st from church.jpg\n| static_image_caption=Rayleigh High Street as seen from the top of Holy Trinity Church, 2003\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.5864|0.6049|display=inline,title}}\n| os_grid_reference = TQ805907\n| population = 32,150\n| population_ref = ''(2011)''<ref name=ONS/>\n| civil_parish = Rayleigh  <ref>http://www.rayleightowncouncil.gov.uk/</ref>\n| shire_district = [[Rochford (district)|Rochford]]\n| shire_county = [[Essex]]\n| region = East of England\n| constituency_westminster = [[Rayleigh and Wickford (UK Parliament constituency)|Rayleigh and Wickford]]\n| post_town = RAYLEIGH\n| postcode_district = SS6\n| postcode_area = SS\n| dial_code = 01268\n}}\n'''Rayleigh''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|r|e\u026a|l|i\u02d0}} is a market town and [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] in the [[Rochford (district)|District of Rochford]] in Essex, England, located between [[Chelmsford, Essex|Chelmsford]] and [[Southend-on-Sea]]. It lies {{convert|32|mi|km}} to the east of central London. It had a population of 30,196 in 2001,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/viewFullDataset.do?instanceSelection=03070&productId=779&$ph=60_61&datasetInstanceId=3070&startColumn=1&numberOfColumns=8&containerAreaId=790394 |title=Census 2001 |publisher=Neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref> increasing to 32,150 at the census 2011.<ref name=ONS>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11127854&c=Rayleigh&d=16&e=62&g=6425548&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1443020385069&enc=1|title=Town population 2015|accessdate=23 September 2015|publisher=Office for National Statistics| work=Neighbourhood Statistics}}</ref>\n\n==Toponymy==\nThe name ''Rayleigh'' is [[Old English]] in origin deriving from ''r\u01e3ge'' ('female roe-deer or she-goat') and ''l\u0113ah'' ('clearing'). Therefore, the name means overall 'wood or clearing of the wild she-goats or roe-deer\".<ref>''The Cambridge Dictionary of English Place Names'', ed. by Victor Watts (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2004).</ref><ref>[[#refRcshistory|Rayleigh Civic Society 2006]]</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Prehistoric and Roman times===\nThere has been a scattering of stray finds around the town from Prehistoric and Roman times, including some Roman roof and [[hypocaust]] tiles found within the fabric of Rayleigh Church. This suggests that there was a Roman habitation site within the area. However, there is little evidence of any density of population here during this period.<ref>[[#refHistoricassess|Historic Town Assessment Report for Rayleigh, 1999]], pages 3 and 7.</ref>\n\n===Saxon era===\nOne significant archaeological find was in the early 2000s at the western edge of Rayleigh, at the site of the former Park School in Rawreth Lane. An early Saxon cemetery site was discovered here, with 144 cremation burials and evidence of just one high-status female inhumation burial.<ref>Essex County Council [http://unlockingessex.essexcc.gov.uk/uep/custom_pages/monument_detail.asp?content_page_id=68&previous_page_id=48&monument_id=1035613 Unlocking Essex's Past]. SMR Number 45134.</ref>\n\nBy the end of the Saxon period, there was definitely a village here, as it is recorded in the [[Domesday Book]], when it was held by Swein of Essex, the son of [[Robert FitzWimarc]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://opendomesday.org/place/TQ8090/Rayleigh/ |title=RAYLEIGH |publisher=OPEN DOMESDAY |date= |accessdate=2019-01-09}}</ref>\n\nThe most significant historic monument in Rayleigh is the great medieval mound of [[Rayleigh Castle]]. This was an early Norman [[motte and bailey]] castle, of which only the motte and its surrounding embankments remain. Despite the loss of its timber superstructure and later stone buildings, its height and bulk mean that it still dominates the town centre.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/rayleigh-mount/features/the-castle-at-rayleigh-mount |title=The castle at Rayleigh Mount |publisher=National Trust |date= |accessdate=9 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Later medieval period (1154\u20131485)===\nA [[courthouse]] was erected in Rayleigh in 1338. This was apparently resented by the townspeople, who turned out in force to destroy it, with 20 [[Leadership|ringleaders]] later arrested and tried.<ref>[[#refBurrows1909|Burrows 1909]], p.31.</ref>\n\nThe forests around Rayleigh were royal hunting grounds. It is recorded that [[Henry III of England|King Henry III]] hunted here in 1222, and three King Edwards also visited.<ref>[[#refBurrows1909|Burrows 1909]], p.27.</ref>\n\nOne of the oldest secular building in Rayleigh is 91 High Street which houses Pizza Express downstairs and [[Rayleigh Town Museum]] upstairs. The Regal Room in the museum is dated circa 1350. It is suspected that some of Rayleigh's older Brick build buildings may contain portions older than this.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rochford.gov.uk/sites/default/files/planning_historic_environment_rayleigh_town_assess.pdf |title=Rayleigh Historic Town Project Assessment Report |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=9 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nRayleigh Castle gradually fell into disuse, and in 1394 [[King Richard II]] gave permission for the townspeople of Rayleigh to use the foundations as a source of stone. By this time, the site was in royal ownership and used for pasture:\n: know all men of special grace who have the will to repair certain Chapel in the said town and to build a new a certain [[Bell tower|belfry]] we have granted them the foundations and to take away and use any stones found theren\".<ref>[[#refRcschurch|Rayleigh Civic Society 2006]], Holy Trinity Church</ref>\n\n===Tudors and Stuarts===\nRecords indicate that the church was rich in plate, vestments and [[stained glass]], but these were disposed of:\n: \"No church within the hundred was more splendidly adorned; none were so richly furnished with plate, vestments and other accessories for the celebration of the divine service; none were so rich in painted glass; none have been more mercilessly despoiled\"<ref>[[#refBurrows1909|Burrows 1909]], p.303.</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Burrows|first=John William|url=http://archive.org/details/southendonseadis00burriala|title=Southend-on-Sea and district: historical notes ..|date=1909|publisher=Southend-on-Sea : J.H. Burrows|others=University of California Libraries}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[Henry VIII]]'s reign, deer were constantly taken from here to replenish the herds in [[Greenwich Park]].<ref>[[#refBurrows1909|Burrows 1909]], pp. 28 58.</ref>\n\n===Modern===\n[[Image:Rayleigh sign.gif|thumb|right|Rayleigh Sign]]\nDuring the 1990s many new housing estates appeared on formerly greenfield areas of the town, with the [[East of England]] region currently pushing for even more homes to be built in the area. This has caused some controversy locally, with residents of Rayleigh feeling that the areas surrounding the town should be preserved with more care.<ref>[[#refPercival|Overwhelming objections to homes plan]], 2007, Southend Echo.</ref>\n\n==Governance==\n\nThe civil parish of Rayleigh became part of [[Rochford Rural District]] in 1894.  In 1929 it was combined with [[Rawreth]] to form the Urban District of Rayleigh, which was abolished in 1974 when the area became part of the District of Rochford.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10245692 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20121224061101/http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10245692 |url-status=dead |archive-date=24 December 2012 |title=A Vision of Britain Through Time : Rayleigh Civil Parish |publisher=Visionofbritain.org.uk |accessdate=13 August 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe constituency of [[Rayleigh and Wickford (UK Parliament constituency)|Rayleigh and Wickford]] is represented in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] by the Member of Parliament [[Mark Francois]] of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]].<ref>[https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/mark-francois/1444 \"Rt Hon Mark Francois MP], Parliament.uk, accessed 8 January 2018.</ref>\n\nIn 2018 Rochford District Council has 25 Conservative members, 3 Liberal Democrats, 3 Green Party, 2 Labour, 4 independents and 4 members from Rochford Residents Party sitting on the council.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/topics/cz3nmpgw3zgt/rochford-district-council |title=Rochford District Council |publisher=BBC |date= |accessdate=2019-01-09}}</ref>\n\nRayleigh Town council is also Conservative controlled, comprising 18 Conservatives, 4 Liberal Democrats, and 1 independent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rayleightowncouncil.gov.uk/upload/files/Councillors/new%20version%20for%20ward%20councillors%20-photos%20and%20information.pdf|title=Rayleigh Town Council}}</ref>\n\nRayleigh Town Council have major responsibilities which include:\n*Consultee on Planning applications in Rayleigh.\n*Christmas Lights and organisation of switch-on event in Town Centre, King George V Playing Field in Eastwood Road, floral displays in Town Centre and entry to Annual [[Anglia in Bloom]] competition, [[CCTV]] in Town Centre, benches, salt bins, litter bins, bus shelters, some street lighting, heritage and memorial plaques, and the Town Centre clock.\n*Four Allotment sites within Rayleigh with over 100 plots\n*Consultee on crime & disorder reduction strategy within Rochford District Member of Rayleigh Windmill management committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.essexinfo.net/rayleightowncouncil/ |title=Rayleigh Town Council |publisher=Essexinfo.net |date= |accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Civic Suite and Information Centre includes the Council Chamber, Committee Rooms, Transportation and Hackney Carriage Office and is located on Hockley Road.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rochford.gov.uk/contact-us-3 |title=contact us |publisher=Rochford Council |accessdate=2019-01-09}}</ref>  The Citizens Advice Bureau and Registrar's Office are also located here.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.citizensadvicerochford.org.uk/our-offices.html |title=our offices |publisher=CAB |accessdate=2019-01-09}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nRayleigh is served by two prominent modes of public transport; bus and train. The bus services are run by [[Arriva Southend]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arrivabus.co.uk/southend |title=Arriva Southend |publisher=Arriva |accessdate=2019-01-09}}</ref> and [[First Essex]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bustimes.org/operators/first-in-essex|title=Bus Times |publisher=First |accessdate=2019-01-09}}</ref> and usually terminate at [[Rayleigh railway station]]. [[Greater Anglia]] run the rail line which leads from [[Southend Victoria railway station|Southend Victoria]] to [[Liverpool Street railway station|London Liverpool Street]], stopping at Rayleigh, running every 10 minutes during rush hour.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.greateranglia.co.uk|title=Great Anglia |publisher=Great Anglia |accessdate=2019-01-09}}</ref> First Essex also operate an hourly coach service to [[Stansted Airport]], numbered X30, which makes a stop at Rayleigh railway station.<ref>https://www.firstgroup.com/essex/airport-services/x30</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstgroup.com/essex/airport-services/x30|title=X30 |publisher=first group |accessdate=2019-01-09}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n[[Image:Rayleigh High Street.JPG|thumb|right|Looking up the High Street towards the church.]]\n\nRayleigh has two secondary schools: [[Sweyne Park School]], formed by the amalgamation of the Sweyne and Park schools, and [[FitzWimarc School]]. It also has seven primary schools \u2013 Down Hall, Edward Francis, Grove Wood, Our Lady of Ransom (Catholic), Rayleigh Primary and Wyburns. The seventh, Glebe Primary School with UHI, was created in September 2014 through the amalgamation\nof Glebe Infant and Nursery School and Glebe Junior School.<ref>{{cite web|title=Glebe Primary Prospectus|url=http://www.glebeprimary.essex.sch.uk/prospectus/|accessdate=30 October 2014}}</ref> In addition, St Nicholas C of E Primary School, a long-established school for the adjoining village of Rawreth, moved in 2006 to a new building just on the Rayleigh side of the parish boundary.<ref>http://www.st-nicholassch.co.uk/the-history-of-our-school/</ref>\n\n==Sports and recreation==\nRayleigh has a golf club on the outskirts of the town; Rayleigh Club (previously Lords Golf & Country Club) is situated on Hullbridge Road to the north of the town.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/589832 |title=photo |publisher=Geograph.org.uk |date= |accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Parks/playing fields===\n\nRayleigh has a number of parks and playing fields.\n\n====King George V Playing Field====\n\nLocated next to Bull Lane, Hockley Road and Websters Way.<ref>http://www.rayleightowncouncil.gov.uk/king-george-v-playing-field/</ref>\n\nIt contains a snack bar and pavilion. As well as a \"Teen\" shelter\n\nIts two grass football pitches are used by Rayleigh FC, Chronicles FC and Ralee FC. It also has a skate park<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rayleightowncouncil.ultx.ovh/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/King%20George%20V%20Playing%20Field%20Management%20Plan.pdf/ |title=King George V Playing Field page 7 |publisher=Rayleigh Town Council |date= |accessdate=2019-01-10}}</ref> and a children's playground, containing a variety of play equipment. The park is also home to Rayleigh Bowls Club (who lease the use of the Pavilion).\n\nRayleigh Lions holds an annual fireworks display on the playing field.<ref>http://www.leightimes.co.uk/article.cfm?id=119719&headline=Rayleigh%20Lions%20Fireworks&sectionIs=news&searchyear=2018</ref>\n\n====Sweyne Park====\n[[Image:Sweyne park sign.jpg|thumb]]\n\nSweyne Park is controlled by Rochford District Council. It is situated north of Sweyne Park School and can be accessed in several ways. The entrance in Downhall Park Way has a small car park, and there is a play area. It has another smaller entrance in Downhall Park Way, adjacent to Canterbury Close. It can also be accessed from Victoria Avenue. In 2008 an entrance was established from Priory Chase. The park has a pond.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/585025 |title=Sweyne Park Pond:: OS grid TQ7991 :: Geograph Britain and Ireland \u2013 photograph every grid square! |publisher=Geograph.org.uk |date=15 October 2007 |accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref> It has a [[bridleway]] running round its perimeter of about {{convert|2|km|mi|abbr=on}}.\n\n* Fairview Playing Field, Victoria Road TQ814914\n* Grove Playing Field, Grove Road TQ825904\n* John Fisher Playing Field (Little Wheatleys Chase, Rayleigh) TQ789914\n\nKingley Wood stands on a steep hill slope beside the A127 and is visible as you approach Rayleigh from London. The small wood is the only surviving ancient wood in Rayleigh, but it has rich and varied [[wildlife]] and a well-documented history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rochford.gov.uk/leisure_and_tourism/woodlands_and_parks/kingley_woods.aspx  |title=Woodlands, Parks and Open Spaces &#124; Kingley Woods |publisher=Rochford.gov.uk |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724164610/http://www.rochford.gov.uk/leisure_and_tourism/woodlands_and_parks/kingley_woods.aspx |archivedate=24 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/598305 |title=Kingley Wood photo |publisher=Geograph.org.uk |date= |accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n====Wheatley Wood====\nThis is a {{convert|64|acre|ha|adj=on}} broadleaved wood established in the late 1990s.\nThe wood was designed and planted by a partnership of Local people and the [[Woodland Trust]].\nThere is a car park at the Grange Community Centre in Little Wheatley Chase, and access to the wood is across the playing fields.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/601857 |title=photo |publisher=Geograph.org.uk |date= |accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Greyhounds and speedway===\nAt least two [[Greyhound racing in the United Kingdom|greyhound racing]] tracks existed in the town. The main venue was the [[Rayleigh Weir Stadium]] which also hosted [[Motorcycle speedway|speedway]] and traded from 1948-1974.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.old-maps.co.uk/#/Map/580650/189412/12/100954|title=OS Plan 1955|publisher=old-maps.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nA smaller short lived track at O'Tooles Meadow, Wickford Road, off the Down Hall Road also hosted greyhound racing and dirt track speedway. The racing was independent (not affiliated to the sports governing body the [[National Greyhound Racing Club]]) and was known as a flapping track, which was the nickname given to independent tracks.<ref>{{cite book|last=Barnes|first=Julia|title=Daily Mirror Greyhound Fact File, page 419|year=1988|publisher=Ringpress Books|isbn=0-948955-15-5}}</ref> The track opened in 1932 but the date of closure is not known<ref>{{cite web|url=https://greyhoundracingtimes.co.uk/2019/04/28/rayleigh-otooles/|title=Rayleigh O'Tooles|publisher=Greyhound Racing Times}}</ref> and it is possible that it may have been the same venue known as the Rayleigh Sports Stadium although it is also possible that the Rayleigh Sports Stadium may have been a third separate venue.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://greyhoundracingtimes.co.uk/2019/04/28/rayleigh-sports-stadium/|title=Rayleigh Sports Stadium|publisher=Greyhound Racing Times}}</ref>\n\n==Public facilities==\n[[Image:Post Office, Rayleigh.jpg|thumb|left|Former Post Office in Rayleigh.]] [[Image:Rayleigh Windmill at night.jpg|thumb|left|[[Rayleigh Windmill]]]]\n\nThere is a small outdoor market on Wednesdays. Until 2011 it was located next to Rayleigh Civic Suite and Information Centre, opposite Holy Trinity Church. In 2011 it moved to the taxi rank in the town's High Street (outside Boots).\nThe market dates back to before 1181 when it was inscribed in the Exchequer Records of Henry II.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rochford.gov.uk/leisure__tourism/district_tour/rayleigh.aspx |title=Rayleigh |work=Rochford District Council |accessdate=9 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615130432/http://www.rochford.gov.uk/leisure__tourism/district_tour/rayleigh.aspx |archivedate=15 June 2011  }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Dutch Cottage]], the smallest and oldest council house in the United Kingdom, can be visited on Wednesdays by prior appointment.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news | last = | first = | author2 = | title = Smallest council house for rent | work = | pages = | language = | publisher = BBC News | date = 14 July 2008 | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/go/homepage/d/int/news/top/8/-/news/1/hi/uk/7504801.stm | accessdate = }}</ref>\n\n[[Rayleigh Windmill]] has been renovated, including a structural renovation of the 19th century brick built building has now been completed. The basic external brickwork has been repaired and the interior has been transformed to provide four storeys of modern display facilities which has turned the windmill into a major tourist and educational attraction in the county. The changes to the windmill allow the public to view the interior and to exploit this local historic amenity for cultural, educational and tourism use.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rochford.gov.uk/leisure__tourism/events_and_attractions/rayleigh_windmill.aspx |title=Rayleigh Windmill |work=Rochford District Council |accessdate=9 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100819100655/http://www.rochford.gov.uk/leisure__tourism/events_and_attractions/rayleigh_windmill.aspx |archivedate=19 August 2010  }}</ref>\n\nRayleigh Mount, a National Trust property adjacent to Rayleigh Windmill, is the site of a Domesday castle erected by Sweyn of Essex with distinctive [[motte-and-bailey]] defences. From its summit it offers sweeping views across the Crouch Valley.<ref>{{cite web |author=ser |url=http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-vh/w-visits/w-findaplace/w-rayleighmount/ |title=Rayleigh Mount |publisher=National Trust |date=17 November 2005 |accessdate=13 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629041245/http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-vh/w-visits/w-findaplace/w-rayleighmount/ |archivedate=29 June 2011  }}</ref>\n\n===Rayleigh Town Museum===\n[[Rayleigh Town Museum]] occupies the  1st floor at 91 High Street and contains many artifacts telling the history of Rayleigh.<ref>https://www.echo-news.co.uk/news/14251208.rayleigh-historical-museum-to-open-in-april/</ref>\n\n==Religion==\n[[Image:Holy Trinity Church Rayleigh.jpg|thumb|right|Holy Trinity parish church]]\nThe [[Church of England parish church]] of the [[Trinity|Holy Trinity]] is at the top of the High Street.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parishofrayleigh.org.uk |title=Parish of Rayleigh Website |publisher=Parishofrayleigh.org.uk |date= |accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref> A church existed on the site in Saxon times and the present building has a [[Norman architecture|Norman]] [[chancel]]. The [[bell tower]] was built in the 15th century and includes stone taken from the castle when that fell into disuse. The church has an impressive [[Tudor architecture|Tudor]] brick porch. The [[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic Revival architect]] [[Clapton Crabb Rolfe|C.C. Rolfe]] restored the chancel in 1873.<ref>Saint, 1970</ref>\n\nThe parish church of [[Michael (archangel)|Saint Michael]] and All Angels is in Sir Walter Raleigh Drive near Sweyne School. It was built in the 1950s when Rayleigh expanded considerably. It has a multi-purpose building which is used by other local groups as well as the church.<ref>Our Lady of Ransom Catholic Church</ref>\n\nOur Lady of Ransom Catholic Church is on London Hill.<ref>http://www.olorchurch.org.uk/home/index.html</ref>\n\nThe United Reformed Church is on Crown Hill.<ref>https://www.christchurchrayleigh.org.uk/</ref>\n\nThe Baptist Church is in the High Street. The building opened for worship on 25 March 1799, shortly before the first Pastor, Rev James Pilkington, was inducted in June 1799. In June 1979, work started on a church extension. This added significantly more seating and completed some much needed repairs.<ref>http://www.rayleighbaptist.org.uk/</ref>\n\n[[Image:RayleighMethodistChurch.jpg|thumb|right|Rayleigh Methodist Church]]\nThe Methodist Church is on Eastwood Road. (Moved from the High Street in 1934).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rayleighmethodistchurch.org.uk |title=Rayleigh Methodist church Website |publisher=rayleighmethodistchurch.org.uk |date= |accessdate=21 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nGrange Free Church is on London Road, at the junction with Langdon Road.<ref>http://rayleighchurches.org.uk/grange-free-church/</ref>\n\nThe Salvation Army are located on the corner of the High Street and Love Lane. The building was the original 1884 Methodist Church, which was sold to the Salvation Army in 1934 when the Methodist Church moved to a larger site in Eastwood Road.<ref>https://www.salvationarmy.org.uk/rayleigh</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:Rayleigh hs 100209.jpg|Rayleigh High Street looking towards Holy Trinity Church.\nImage:Rayleigh sign 1.jpg|Rayleigh sign outside Rayleigh Lanes Indoor Market.\nImage:Map rayleigh.jpg|Map of Rayleigh Town Centre. Found on wall near the Millennium Clock.\nImage:Millennium clock rayleigh.jpg|Side of the Millennium Clock looking towards the Police Station.\nImage:Ye olde crown rayleigh.jpg|Ye Olde Crown.\nImage:Spread rayleigh.jpg|Spread Eagle.\nImage:White horse rayleigh.jpg|Old White Horse.\nImage:RayleighMethodistChurch.jpg|Rayleigh Methodist church from Eastwood Road.\nImage:Rayleigh Town Museum 190916.jpg|91 High Street in Rayleigh.\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* <cite id=refBurrows1909>Burrows, John William. (1909). ''Southend on Sea and District: Historical Notes''. {{ISBN|0-85409-642-6}}.</cite>\n* <cite id=refEpns>English Place-Name Society. (2008). [http://www.nottingham.ac.uk/english/ins/kepn/detailpop.php?placeno=12321 ''The Survey of English Place-Names: Rayleigh'']. Institute for Name-Studies. Retrieved 2008-06-28.</cite>\n* <cite id=refHistoricassess>Essex County Council. (1999). [http://www.essexcc.gov.uk/vip8/ecc/ECCWebsite/content/binaries/documents/Planning396/rayleigh_1999_historic_towns_assessment_report.pdf ''Historic Town Assessment Report for Rayleigh'']. Retrieved 2008-06-28</cite>\n* <cite id=refPercival>Percival, Geoff. (2007-06-05). [http://www.echo-news.co.uk/search/display.var.1523045.0.overwhelming_objections_to_homes_plan.php work= ''Overwhelming objections to homes plan'']. Southend Echo. Retrieved 2008-06-28.</cite>\n*{{Cite book |author=Pevsner, Nikolaus |authorlink=Nikolaus Pevsner |author2= |title=[[The Buildings of England]]: Essex |year=1965 |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |location=Harmondsworth |isbn= |pages=}}\n* <cite id=refRcshistory>Rayleigh Civic Society. (2006). [https://web.archive.org/web/20080509065035/http://www.rayleighbusiness.co.uk/history.asp ''History of Rayleigh'']. Rayleigh Chamber of 